<HEADLINE>Commercial Union profits soar</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484811</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INSURANCE giant Commercial Union yesterday reported almost doubled
profits for 1994 and further relieved fears of cut-throat competition in
the industry.
The company was also bullish about recent acquisition Groupe
Victoire's future impact on earnings.
Particularly strong profits growth in general insurance, which
accounted for 64% of premiums, helped the group increase pre-tax
earnings from continuing operations to #413m from #218m.
The bottom-line pre-tax figure, after a loss on termination of
activities, was #402m (#211m).
Total dividend, after a final payout of 16.29p and adjustment for a
rights issue during the year, was up 8% at 26.4p.
The City was impressed by results which lived up to expectations and
Commercial Union shares put on 10p to 515p in a broadly unchanged
sector.
General insurance profits rose 86% to #347m worldwide, with UK
earnings nearly doubling to #220m.
UK underwriting earned #63m, after a #55m loss the previous year, with
branch operations' profits of #145m offset by losses of #82m in the
London market, principally from old business. Investment income was
slightly lower at #157m.
The overall UK result was helped by higher premiums, better claims
experience and favourable weather conditions. Last year's loss included
#21m attributable to bomb damage in London.
Chief executive John Carter said underwriting conditions in most major
overseas markets continued to improve and, while the UK had seen an
increase in competition during the year, there was nothing to indicate
that an excessive level was developing.
Stockbroker James Capel believes some other analysts' fears of
cut-throat competition in the sector have failed to materialise.
It predicts ''very healthy'' operating results for insurers in
1995-96, accompanied by solid dividend growth, and believes the recent
recovery in their share prices will continue.
The results of French-based Groupe Victoire were consolidated from
September 13. During the four months, it earned life profits of #25m but
incurred a loss of #14m in general insurance operations.
Its addition will increase the life portion of Commercial Union's
total premiums to 40% on a full-year basis.
Looking ahead, Mr Carter said: ''The acquisition of the life and
general insurance business of Groupe Victoire has significantly expanded
the scope of our operations. It is expected to improve the quality of
the group's earnings and support our objective of providing shareholders
with real dividend growth on a sustained basis.''
The general insurance side of Groupe Victoire's business is slowly
responding to the introduction of higher premiums, cost control and
improvements to portfolios.
Overall life profits were up 27% at #154m. The earnings of Commercial
Union's Dutch Delta Lloyd operation, which made the greatest individual
contribution, rose to #84m.
Life premium income in the UK fell from #596m to #585m, with difficult
market conditions reducing sales of new pensions products. UK life
profits were down #3m at #45m.
Overall, general insurance premium income rose 6% to #4316m, with life
premium income 29% higher at #2446m.
</TEXT>
