<HEADLINE>Costain shares tumble</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484812</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES of hard-pressed construction group Costain tumbled 6p to stand
at a mere 12[1/2]p yesterday after the company said that it could not
get an acceptable offer for the sale of its remaining US coal mining
assets and that it was no longer expecting a bid for the group as a
whole.
Costain had announced a bid approach at the end of January. It is now
to retain and manage the US coal businesses and has written down their
book value by about #100m.
The market had been looking for a complete withdrawal by Costain from
coal in the US after the sale of Dolet Hills and some additional coal
assets for around $100m.
Costain shareholders have suffered badly in the last few years as the
value of the company has slumped from #1000m in 1990 to just #65m
currently and what prospect they had of retrieving something through a
bid -- though the terms were unlikely to have been generous -- looks to
have been dashed, at least for the time being.
</TEXT>
