<HEADLINE>Fault discovered in window catches</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484813</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FAULT has been discovered in the safety catches fitted to some fire
escape windows of homes where two toddlers, one of whom died, have been
involved in falls in the past nine months.
Now East Lothian District Council has ordered modification of the
safety catches in 2000 houses.
The move follows a detailed investigation carried out by the authority
in the wake of an incident last month in which two-year-old Evan
Henderson was injured when he fell from a first-floor window at his
Wallyford home.
The council says that the cause of the accident has not yet been
established.
Last week, a fatal accident inquiry at Haddington Sheriff Court into
the death last summer of 21-month-old Ewan Smith, who plunged from the
window of a Musselburgh house, was adjourned after the sheriff ruled the
Wallyford child's fall should also be considered.
Lawyers for the local authority unsuccessfully opposed the move
arguing the windows involved were of a completely different design, and
had different catches. The FAI is due to resume later this month.
The investigation into the Wallyford accident found that, on some
windows, the small plastic peg used to release the window stay in an
emergency was not operating satisfactorily.
The council has now agreed all of them should be replaced by the
manufacturer. Replacement will begin shortly and is expected to take
around 10 days.
The homes involved are two-storey houses and flats across the
district, all of which have been fitted with double glazing within the
last few years. Not all emergency windows are affected.
Housing officers will make sure the catches are in full working order.
They will also ensure householders know how to operate the emergency
windows, and all windows will have special stickers warning they should
not be used for ventilation.
''Safety has to be our primary concern,'' council housing committee
chairman Councillor Pat Fawcett said.
</TEXT>
