<HEADLINE>Hotelier's offer has his angling guests hooked</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484814</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Aberdeen hotelier is offering attractive bait for anglers on the
Dee to throw back the fish they catch to help increase stocks on the
royal river.
New voluntary restrictions are being implemented by beat owners to
maintain the fishing which generates more than #6m a year expenditure
along the river banks.
The fishermen, who pay handsomely for the privilege of casting on the
favourite river of the Queen Mother and the Prince of Wales, are allowed
to keep the first salmon they catch each week.
But Mr Stewart Spence, of The Marcliffe at Pitfodels Hotel, is giving
fishermen on his Commonty beat a farm-bred salmon as a replacement for
each subsequent fish they catch.
He is anxious to ensure that guests on the beat abide by the voluntary
code and it could prove a costly gesture. If, as expected, around 100
fish are caught during the season, it will cost him #2000 but he said
yesterday: "It will be money well spent. It is an investment in the
future. The more we have to give away the better, because it means the
fishing is good.
''The first week's fishing seems to have been very good, and everyone
appears to be taking the voluntary code on board. If the sport is good,
they are quite happy to throw the salmon back.
''Andrew Bradford on one of the other beats is offering smoked salmon
for the fish thrown back.''
The first three anglers to benefit from Mr Spence's generosity
yesterday received their farmed salmon.
Mr Alan Smith, a retired financier from Newcastle-under-Lyme, said the
catch-and-release scheme would be welcomed by all responsible anglers.
He said he had been coming to the Dee for 15 years and, although the
drop in numbers of fish would not have kept him away from the river, he
believed Mr Spence's gesture would encourage people to come and would
help the conservation cause.
The other recipients of the fish were Mr Ray Pickering and John Carr,
both from Stoke-on-Trent.
</TEXT>
