<HEADLINE>Capital growth hits the brakes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART MCINTOSH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,PROPERTY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>TABLE</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484816</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE rate of capital growth in Scotland's property has slowed across
the board, according to the Richard Ellis Scottish Monthly Index (RESMI)
prepared exclusively for The Herald.
The retail sector's annual rate of capital growth slowed down from 11%
in January to 10% for the year to February. Office and industrial
capital growth slowed to 11.4% and 9.0% respectively leading to capital
growth for all property of 10.2% for the year to February.
All three sectors experienced zero month-on-month rental growth in
February, a slight improvement for the retail sector over the decline of
0.2% in January. There was no change in year-on-year rental growth in
any of the sectors. Offices continue to show negative rental growth at
-1.4%, all other sectors showing some annual growth.
Total returns continued to follow a downward trend. All property fell
from 19.7% last month to 18.3% for the year to February. The annual
rates for the office and retail sectors fell to 19.8% and 16.7%
respectively. Total return for industrial property held up well, falling
only slightly from 19.6% previously to 19.2% for the year to February.
YEAR TO END FEBRUARY 1995
...........TOTAL RETURN....CAPITAL GROWTH....RENTAL GROWTH
PROPERTY.....18.3% .........10.2% (-0.1%)......0.2% (0.0%)
Offices......19.8%..........11.4% (0.2%)......-1.4% (0.0%)
Retail.......16.7%..........10.0% (-0.4%)......0.7% (0.0%)
Industrial...19.2%...........9.0% (0.0%).......2.0% (0.0%)
(Figures given in brackets are the results for the month)
