<HEADLINE>Full credit given to solid teamwork</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL KNOX</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484817</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE path to quality accreditations BS5750 and ISO9002 is no easy
route, as Glasgow forklift truck hire specialists, Douglas Gillespie
Plant discovered. But now they are delighted to be celebrating their
success.
''I'm ready to admit that there were times when it meant a lot more
work than I had expected,'' said group chairman and managing director
Douglas Gillespie. ''But our staff were behind us from the start. We
know we are now a more efficient company, which benefits both ourselves
and our customers.''
This proudly independent family business includes many staff who have
more than 20 years' service behind them. That is important to Douglas
Gillespie, who firmly believes that a company is only as good as the
people who work for it.
''From the start, we had two reasons for going ahead. One was that we
knew it should tighten up our procedures in quality and service. The
other was that we were becoming aware that some of our customers were
very interested in quality accreditation.''
The first steps along the accreditation way began in 1992. Group
accountant Gordon Barclay who had been appointed quality manager, held a
series of meetings and training sessions which involved every single
member of staff.
''There were no exceptions,'' said Gordon Barclay. ''We set out to
explain to everyone that it was a priority matter for the firm's future
and not just a way of generating more paper work.''
Meetings and training sessions during working hours, backed up by
''quite a lot'' of management work after hours, included a complete
computer reprogramming as the required operating manual took shape. All
members of staff were invited to contribute suggestions towards the
shaping of the new procedures.
''Several of these suggestions were incorporated in the final
manual,'' said Gordon Barclay. They included a completely new approach
to customer inquiries and service requests, suggested by hire desk
staff. It began with a specially-created questionnaire for each customer
whether old or new.''
That suggestion was followed by others while sales and service
departments discovered they had acquired a new understanding of other
activities within the company.
''Everyone now knows much more about everyone else's job, with an
insight which covers all procedures. Now that these new procedures are
in place and now that we have acquired the quality accreditations,
working totally to these new exacting standards, we feel we have joined
a very exclusive club. Our staff are 100% proud of what we have achieved
-- particularly after the amount of work they all put in towards getting
there.''
Douglas Gillespie Plant point to benefits which include a new, speedy
and efficient way of tracing any fault that may occur. Their widespread
activities cover almost every part of Scotland, but a fault anywhere can
now be very quickly identified and eliminated, while steps are taken to
make sure it does not happen again.
''That is all down to our new manual of procedures 'bible','' said
Gordon Barclay. ''All the work that went into its preparation is paying
off in a major way.''
Congratulations from customers followed the awards. Another result has
been what Douglas Gillespie described as both opening existing business
doors wider and opening totally new business doors for the first time.
''We are being seen in a new light by people who have already achieved
BS5750 and ISO standards. We also find that we are becoming more aware
of other firms who we deal with or purchase from and who are similarly
qualified.''
Both awards are now part of the company logo on all Douglas Gillespie
vehicles and on the firm's letterheads.
The fork truck fleet serves many major commercial customers including
Allied Distillers, Scottish Brewers, ICI and Stoddard Carpets.
Typically, the rental company is particularly proud of the fact that the
Vesuvius Crucible Company, their first significant customer at their
beginning back in 1968, is among the many names which have continued to
do business with them ever since.
Uplifted by a steady growth
DOUGLAS Gillespie takes a considerable pride in the way the firm he
established has grown.
From small beginnings in 1968, it has grown into an organisation with
a #4.6m turnover forecast for 1995 and a predicted growth of more than
#5m for 1996.
''We have remained an independent family business throughout and along
the way we made it an aim never to lose a customer,'' he said at his
Darnley industrial estate headquarters. ''We know we are good at what we
do. Our forward mission is to continue to grow but to keep our feet on
the ground.''
A Glasgow man, Douglas Gillespie had been working in England for more
than 10 years before he returned to Scotland with a great desire to
start in business for himself. He spent some time in America researching
the fork lift rental business and then set up his own fork lift rental
business in East Kilbride. His wife Margaret, at that time a school
teacher, joined him to run the administrative and secretarial side. With
the appointment of two engineers, Douglas Gillespie Plant Hire, Fork
Lift specialists was underway.
Today Douglas Gillespie Plant Hire Fork Lift Company is the backbone
of the Douglas Gillespie group. It operates approximately 350 fork lift
vehicles -- the largest independent rental fleet in Scotland. The group
also operates one of the largest Calor Gas dealership in Scotland and
through its new division, Clarklift Scotland Limited, it is the
franchise holder for one of the world's leading fork lift truck
manufacturer.
From the inital 2000 sq ft start, growth came steadily. A move to
larger premises in East Kilbride was followed by the acquisition of a
12,000 sq ft base at Giffnock, then an additional depot and operating
base at Bellshill. By 1980 their turnover had passed the #1m figure. Ten
years later it had gone through the #2m mark.
The process of acquiring the group's present base at Darnley, a former
Calor Gas depot covering three and a half acres, also took place in 1990
and following an extensive refurbishment programme, Darnley was
established as the new headquarters.
''Two years ago we established Clarklift Scotland Limited as a new
division,'' said Douglas Gillespie. ''Clarklift are one of the world's
leading fork lift manufacturers and we sell throughout Scotland.''
To a wider world, the Douglas Gillespie plant hire name is also known
for another activity. Since the 1970s it has been prominent in its
support of competition golf. Douglas Gillespie at one time represented
Scotland in Youth International competitions.
As a sponsor he established the Douglas Gillespie Pro-Am competition
in the 1970s, bringing together top players, personalities and
customers. In the 1980s he launched a new tournament -- the Scottish
Under 25s professional championships. That was followed by the
sponsorship of the Glasgow Youth Amateur pro championship and the
Scottish Boys Under 16 national championship.
We have remained an independent family business and we make it an aim
never to lose a customer
</TEXT>
