<HEADLINE>Sir Patrick shrugs off anti-smoking litigation.  BAT juggernaut rolls on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>COMMENT,SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484818</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN lawyers are not going to give up easily on the tobacco
industry given the juicy rewards they would receive should they win
their case, the latest being based on a claim for compensation for
smokers allegedly addicted to the practice.
BAT Industries' chairman, Sir Patrick Sheehy, ironically again on
annual No Smoking Day, shrugged off the latest action as he has done
others in the past, pointing out that the industry has never lost a case
yet.
He was confident the industry would win the current action, though it
is on a different scale to others, with 60 US law firms binding together
to make their case, which, they say, if successful, could result in
payouts of between $50bn and $100bn.
At least the political climate is more favourable with the Republicans
firmly installed in Congress, which rules out ideas like a hike in
excise duty to pay for healthcare reform.
Nearer to home, BAT's UK financial services companies, Allied Dunbar
and Eagle Star, have set aside #123m for correcting pensions
mis-selling, with most of the sum relating to Allied.
Sir Patrick's general confidence extends to this business also,
perhaps optimistically expecting the companies to increase their market
share when the sector returns to normal.
This hit is excluded from BAT's 1994 results as it is charged to
contingency reserve. This is just as well as profits would have been
down had it been taken from them. Reported profits were virtually
unchanged at #1802m, but if American Tobacco reorganisation charges are
excluded they were 10% up.
The $1000m purchase of American was only completed this year and gave
BAT full control of the Lucky Strike and Pall Mall brands. With the
American market looking better the acquisition will bring a good boost
to 1995 tobacco earnings.
BAT is maintaining its generous dividend policy with a 9% rise to
21.9p, after a final of 13.4p. In addition, shareholders will receive a
further 2.35p under the foreign income dividend scheme. Sir Patrick said
they remained confident of continuing to pay dividend increases ''well
ahead'' of inflation. Such is the power of the cash flow generated by
cigarettes.
The year was something of a mirror image of 1993, with financial
services relatively weak and tobacco firm. Eagle Star shared its
sector's improvement in underwriting performance, with the loss down
from #142m to #34m, helped by a halving in the mortgage indemnity
deficit.
But after allowing for a sharp fall in the investment total return,
reflecting weak bond and equity markets, its overall profits were
actually lower at #157m. Despite the traumas in its market, Allied
Dunbar's contribution was a little higher, increasing overall life
profits by #10m to #379m, on the back of modest premium growth and tight
control of costs.
Farmers, the US insurance activity, was affected by the Los Angeles
earthquake but good business elsewhere brought a small increase in
profits, though the life side was a little lower.
Back to cigarettes, to the chagrin of the antis, volume rose 4%,
spurred by a 13% jump in exports from the US, UK and Germany,
particularly to the Far East, Middle East and central and eastern
Europe. Brown &amp; Williamson in the US excelled, doubling profits to #395m
on volume gains and better sales mix. The market stabilised and market
share gains were made by brands like Kool.
BAT's ultra-modern factory in Southampton continued to improve
productivity and its exports were well up, with up-market brands like
State Express 555, Benson &amp; Hedges and John Player Gold Leaf to the
fore.
BAT continues to make significant headway into new markets,
particularly in the old Soviet bloc. Once the investment programme is
complete it will have the capacity to make 100 billion cigarettes a
year. China is the ultimate treasure trove as its citizens puff their
way through a third of global consumption but so far BAT serves the
market through exports. Meanwhile, ever active, the group is setting
itself up in Vietnam.
BAT rolls on like a juggernaut and an increase in profits is
inevitable this year. The shares, up 11p at 422p, probably sell at under
10 times prospective earnings and yield 7.2% which looks like value,
until you remember the group's main product. One day some lawsuit is
going to stick and the rating has to bear this in mind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
