<HEADLINE>Location and guidance help new companies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ERIC KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484819</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT hasn't escaped the notice of one Birchwood Courtyards company that
this is the Chinese Year of the Pig. Nothing connected with pigs,
however, can be expected to escape the notice of a firm with the title
New Pig Ltd.
This youthful but growing company has nothing to do with pigs -- it is
rather more interested in the manufacture and distribution of industrial
absorbents.
It was the excellent transport links offered by Motherwell District
which influenced the company's decision to locate at the Birchwood
Courtyards.
The company is a wholly-owned subsidiary of the New Pig Corporation of
Pennsylvania, and its establishment in 1993 represented that
corporation's first step into Europe. The subsidiary is now distributing
its products to different parts of the Continent and Scandinavia -- and
the proximity of the M74, M8 and M73 means, that goods can be well on
their way within minutes, says managing director Alastair McSkimming.
The fast access to Glasgow and Edinburgh airports also means European
and Scandinavian markets are within a few hours' reach -- another
facility appreciated by Mr McSkimming.
Deliveries, too, can be made at any time to New Pig's three units at
Birchwood -- there are no parking or offloading restrictions. ''We can
get our orders out on the same day,'' says Mr McSkimming.
'Pig' incidentally, stands for Partners in Grime. The parent firm was
established in 1985, so the Year of the Pig coincides with its tenth
anniversary. An innovator in providing solutions to industrial and
hazardous leakage problems, it now counts more than 94% of the Fortune
500 among its 100,000 US customers, and has a $55m turnover.
Its first product was an absorbent sock, and it now offers no fewer
than 1200 products.
The Scottish subsidiary was already enjoying the fruits of
Motherwell's prime location, based at the district council's industrial
estate at Righead, when the opportunity came to move to Birchwood. ''As
a distribution centre, the location is excellent,'' says Alastair
McSkimming.
His company occupies about 12,000 sq ft in its three units, but is now
looking to double its space to cater for expansion.
Elsewhere at the Birchwood Courtyards, there is similar high praise
for the development's transport links from a company which is eyeing up
world markets for an innovative new product which could make tyre
punctures virtually a thing of the past.
Tyresafe (International) Ltd anticipates a worldwide response to an
invention which seems destined to make a major contribution to road
safety. Its tyre sealant, developed over a five-year period by Donald
Daisley with the help of several Scottish universities, is water-based
and injected through the tyre valve.
It coats the inside of the tyre and prevents air loss in the case of a
puncture of up to 15mm in diameter. ''You could be driving along a
motorway, have a puncture, and not even know about it,'' says Daisley.
''That's a lot better than struggling with the wheel for control of your
vehicle.''
He claims that other sealants deal only with much smaller holes and
that they are unsuitable for heavy or fast vehicles. One road-rally team
at a recent Inverness event unexpectedly took second place after not one
of its five cars developed a puncture. This, after careering at up to
130mph over forest roads.
It was the only team in the event which did not have to stop and
change wheels due to such tyre damage and the performance of the
Tyresafe sealant has caused a stir in the rallying world.
Daisley, who is the firm's technical director, and Ed Craik, its
managing director, pay tribute to the speed with which Motherwell
District Council found them a suitable factory. ''We approached them on
August 18, 1994,'' says Craik, ''and got the keys to our new
headquarters on September 6.''
The council also helped with a low-cost loan, which was welcome at a
time when the company was constructing its own customised manufacturing
facility. From a cold start, Tyresafe now employs nine people and has
just clinched its first export order, to Malaysia.
Negotiations are under way with companies in France, Australia, Kenya,
Zimbabwe, and Russia and the product has attracted keen attention from
various police forces, including Strathclyde, and other multi-users such
as fleet operators.
Already the fast access to the national motorway network has proved a
boon. Says Ed Craik, ''The location could not be better. We are now
taking our product to the world marketplace, and are doing so from the
perfect base.''
</TEXT>
