<HEADLINE>Cadbury Schweppes sweetens its profits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE,CITY EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484820</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH its recent purchase for #1076m of the Dr Pepper/Seven-Up
companies in the US, confectionery and soft drinks group Cadbury
Schweppes has really launched itself into the big league world market
for soft drinks and the prime focus for the company this year will be
absorbing and managing Dr Pepper.
But meantime, it continued to make progress in most areas in 1994, not
badly hurt so far by the cola wars in the UK. And acquisitions have
helped boost overseas market penetration in both its confectionery
business and in soft drinks.
A full contribution from A&amp;W Brands lifted volume growth US carbonated
soft drinks by 51%, while European confectionary saw exports to Russia
almost treble -- Russians, it seems, now consume one million bars of
Cadbury's chocolate per day.
Pre-tax profits last year increased by almost 15% from #416.3m to
#478.5m after a provision of #23m to complete the programme of
re-shaping the Spanish beverages business, much in line with projections
made at the time of the Pepper deal.
Shareholders are to receive a second interim dividend of 11p taking
the total to 15.60p, a rise of 8.3%.
Group sales advanced 8.2% from #3725m to #4030m of which 4.7% was from
acquisitions and disposals and 4.5% from increased activity. There was a
1% drop on exchange rates.
Cadbury Schweppes is also able to report that trading margins
strengthened from 11.7% to 12.5% over the year. A particularly
interesting aspect of the results is the progress of Coca-Cola Schweppes
Beverages (CCSB), the UK bottling operation with Coca-Cola. Progess here
was, and is, under threat from the outbreak of cola wars whereby the
supermarkets bring out their own products in an attempt to undercut the
premium prices enjoyed by Coke.
In fact, despite the flood of own-label colas, total volumes grew by
10% last year with cola brands up 9%. The cola share held overall with
volume at a record. The exceptionally good weather helped but an
improvement in margins and market share in the middle of the wars was
still not bad going.
As Cadbury group chief executive David Wellings pointed, it shows that
soft drinks are not confined to supermarkets although prices fell as
Coke was forced to offer discounts and incentives to head of the
competition.
The current year could prove tougher, though, and it cannot be assumed
that there will be another warm summer to help mitigate the impact.
Chairman Dominic Cadbury, commenting on the group's progress, said:
''The 1994 results continue our momentum and confidence that we will
make further progress in 1995. The acquisition of Dr Pepper/Seven-Up
gives us the opportunity to compete in the mainstream of the beverage
market from a position of growing strength. We do not underestimate the
challenge but believe we have the experience and tools for the task.''
Cadbury Schweppes is also part of the Camelot National Lottery
Consortium and while it is still early days, the company said the
lottery has come up to expectations in financial terms.
Cadbury Schweppes shares slipped 3p to 423p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
