<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Investing in Motherwell's business future</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ERIC KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484822</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUCCESS, it seems, does breed success after all. And taking a chance,
as in the case of 26 high-class industrial units owned by Motherwell
District Council at Strathclyde Business Park, can pay off.
Not that there was any real risk of not attracting businesses to The
Birchwood Courtyards. The situation could not be bettered, the
environment was right, and the district council, having invested no less
than #4.4m, was proving flexible in its leasing agreements.
Today the council is celebrating the fact that all 26 units are let,
that 136 jobs have been created, and that work is about to start on a
third phase of this project.
As for breeding success, some of the companies which have moved in are
already seeking extra space.
The proximity of the development to Scotland's motorway network, its
easy access to Scotland's two major cities and their airports, and the
fact that this is a greenfield site with no parking problems have
combined to create an environment which is geared to expansion,
optimism, and the generation of employment.
That is what the whole project is about, so the council and its
Industrial Development and Estates unit must feel its investment is
paying off. It is hard to believe that this beautifully landscaped
industrial facility was disused farmland only four years ago.
''Buying the land and having these units built on a speculative basis
was a departure for us,'' says Gordon Smith, Head of Industrial
Development and Estates. ''It was our first new site for 20 years, the
others owned by us were inherited when the council was established in
1975.
''We were also aiming for a different market. Rental levels have
exceeded #4 per sq ft and it has become clear that companies are
prepared to pay for the opportunity to operate in such a quality
environment. The high specification of the units has also been a
factor.''
The units in the first two phases are between 2000 and 5000 sq ft but
Phase Three is going to consist of four at between 4850 and 6900 sq ft.
They should be ready by spring of next year and, says Gordon Smith, ''we
would be disappointed if they didn't generate a further 150 jobs.''
Companies moving into the first two phases have had every help from
the district council in the provision of rent-free periods, flexible
leases, and business assistance services.
The council will be equally responsive to the needs of those
interested in phase three which, as Smith points out, will probably be
the last major industrial development carried out by Motherwell District
Council before the new North Lanarkshire Council takes over in April,
1996.
''It will be a birthday present to the new council,'' he says. ''With
any luck, it will have some tenants as well.''
There is no doubt about the main reason for The Birchwood Courtyards'
success.
Companies based there are at the heart of Scotland's motorway system
with the M8, M74 and M73 only minutes away. It is a dream location for
companies seeking a manufacturing or distribution base with fast access
to north, south, east or west.
Glasgow and Edinburgh, along with their international airports, are
easily accessible and the main electrified Glasgow-London rail route
places Motherwell District about four-and-a-half hours from London.
Also, the Eurocentral Scotland Freight Terminal at nearby Mossend is
soon to provide direct freight access to Europe's 320 million consumers.
Some of the companies now based at The Birchwood Courtyards have their
sights set on Europe and beyond, with Scandinavia, all points of Europe,
North America, and Malaysia already in mind. They are at the heart of
things at the Business Park, and the units they occupy are designed for
twenty-first century success.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
