<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>RTZ pulls off major mining coup and pushes earnings up by 60%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484823</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RTZ appears to have
pulled off a major coup -- it has an agreement to buy its way into
Freeport-McMoRan Copper which will give it immediately about 10% of the
world's fourth-largest copper mine.
The pit contains 40 million ounces of gold -- the largest known
deposit.
Chief executive Robert Wilson could scarcely conceal his excitement
yesterday that the Grasberg mine in Irian Jaya in Indonesia could, in
due course, come under RTZ control.
As with all major mining decisions, the rewards will take time to
arrive. There will be little impact on earnings until 1998.
The City liked the deal and the better than expected results for 1994.
They included a much higher than expected dividend and a statement
about metal prices and demand which was the most optimistic anyone can
remember the world's largest mining group ever having made in the past.
Investors liked what they saw and pushed the shares ahead 26p to 755p.
Attributable profits after tax jumped by 60% to #595m with #173m
coming from higher prices while volume accounted for another #35m.
Copper prices averaged 105 cents per pound during the year compared with
1993's 87 cents and the current 133 cents.
RTZ expects that after an overall 7% improvement in 1994 metal prices
there should be increases of about 3% to 4% both for 1995 and 1996.
Current prices are still 32% below their 1988 peak.
Thanks to the group's long-range planning, even if there is any future
softening of prices, they will be countered by additional group capacity
coming on stream. RTZ is in the fortunate position of having the bulk of
the world's low-cost mines in its portfolio.
Grasberg will have a copper production price of 23 cents a pound which
compares with the 40 cents of RTZ's other operations such as Bingham
Canyon in the US and Escondida in Chile.
There are another eight major projects at various stages of
development including exploration for diamonds in Canada and expansion
of aluminium capacity in the Australian state of Queensland.
So if there is any global over-capacity it will be other producers who
will bear the pain. Cost efficiency is such that RTZ was able to take
#32m of costs out of the business last year.
The US coal operations, which produce about 50 million tons annually,
are worth considerably more than their acquisition costs as a result of
the the recovery in the American economy and demand for low sulphur
coal.
The capital expenditure programme has peaked at #534m (#276m). Work on
the Bingham Canyon smelter is almost complete and it will become
operational soon to reduce copper costs by 14 cents a pound.
After the Grasberg deal, gearing could increase from 7% to about 25%
including the #300m or so acquisition costs and #500m of exploration and
development expenses for the mine.
Production for next year is planned at 500,000 tonnes of copper and
1.5 million ounces of gold.
RTZ is boosting its dividend total by 34% to UK taxpayers through the
use of Foreign Income Dividends.
There is a final Foreign Income Dividend of 11.5p and a conventional
payment of 7p which together raise the total to 27.5p to put the shares
on a 4.5% yield.
Pencilling in attributable profits of #800m for the current year seems
a bankable proposition which would leave the shares trading at 10 times
likely earnings.
</TEXT>
