<DOCNO>GH950309-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lloyds to close drugstores division</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484824</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Lloyds Chemists were decimated when the company disclosed
that it is having to shut down its drugstore division of 308 outlets
because it can no longer compete against the plethora of retailers
selling cut-price toiletries. The shares slumped 48p to 237p.
A review of the division has yet to be finalised but it is expected to
lead to the closure of 100 shops. Around 180 of the rest will be
converted to a new health and beauty format within the chemists
division, and a further 30 will become Holland &amp; Barrett stores.
Finance director Michael Ward said that both the drugstore market and
consumers had changed since the industry's heyday in the seventies and
eighties. Lloyds has decided to invest its money in its other businesses
where it can make good margins.
These continue to prosper and enabled it to offset the loss produced
by the shops on overall group profits. In the six months to end-December
taxable profits moved up just 1.4% to #26.6m despite a near-20% increase
in turnover to #550.3m.
There was a marginal increase in fully-diluted earnings per share to
14.04p, but the company's confidence in its future prospects was
demonstrated by the decision to raise the interim dividend by 7.4% to
2.9p per share. There is a scrip dividend alternative.
On a divisional basis, the chemists business performed well despite
the timing of the flu epidemic. Its sales rose by 4% on an underlying
basis.
The company remains on the lookout for further chemists chains to
acquire. It made several purchases in the first half including a number
of independent chains in Scotland such as the five Millers stores in
Edinburgh.
Holland &amp; Barrett, the healthfood retailer, reported 6% growth in
underlying sales. Twenty-one new stores were opened in the period,
bringing the total to 324.
The pharmaceutical division showed strong growth in sales and profits.
It is the largest wholesaler in Scotland. The integration of the
wholesale pharmaceutical depots continues and is on track to be
completed by the end of 1995. The veterinary division reported a 60%
increase in its profits in what remains a buoyant market.
Trading in the first nine weeks of the second half is said to have
been positive with overall group sales 19.3% ahead of the comparable
period last year. However, that masks a 4% decline in drugstore sales
underlining the problems the business faces.
</TEXT>
