<DOCNO>GH950309-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Asian falls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484825</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE timing of The Scottish Asian Investment Company's planned doubling
of its holdings in the trouble-torn Hong Kong market will be crucial to
full-year performance.
Reporting a 16.2% decline in net asset value to 248p in the six months
to January 31, the Glasgow-based investment trust revealed plans to
target the colony in a big way on any market weakness. It had previously
cut back substantially in Hong Kong.
The fall in the Murray Johnstone-run trust's net asset value came
against the backdrop of respective 15.6%, 5% and 25.2% declines in stock
markets in Malaysia, Singapore and Hong Kong.
Malaysian equities accounted for 24.7% of the #51m fund at the halfway
stage, with shares in Singapore making up 20.1%, and Hong Kong equities
accounting for 14.4%.
Since the year end, the trust's net asset value has recovered to 264p.
Scottish Asian will also be looking to reduce its holdings in Malaysia
by more than one-third on anticipated market strength in the run-up to
the country's general election.
Rising US interest rates, fall-out from the Mexican financial crisis
and the Chinese succession issue all hit sentiment in the six months to
January.
A major sell-off by US investors during January hit Scottish Asian's
holdings, which are primarily blue chips, particularly hard.
The trust, which aims for capital growth through investment in Asia
except Japan, managed a 39% rise in net asset value to 296p in the year
to last July in spite of a poor second half.
In line with policy, no interim dividend will be paid.
</TEXT>
