<DOCNO>GH950309-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The future is mobile for phone firm's extensions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HARRY CONROY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,PEOPLE BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484826</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR years ago Richard Emanuel borrowed #3000 from his bank and
launched DX Mobile Phones.
The gamble paid off and the Bank of Scotland manager who agreed to
back the young 22-year-old must be rubbing his hands with glee.
''I was the sales manager with a small mobile phone company,''
explained Richard, ''and I thought I could do better''.
He was joined on his new venture by Rae McDonald, who worked beside
him in his old job. ''It was a brave thing for Rae to do at the time as
she gave up a pretty secure job,'' said Richard.
The gamble certainly paid off for everyone involved. DX expects to
have a #12 million plus turnover this year, a massive leap from last
year's #4 million, and Rae is now office manager with a staff of 85 to
look after.
Despite the rapid growth which saw DX sell around 120 phones in the
first year of business to sales in the region of 30,000 this year,
Richard Emanuel expects more growth.
''This year we will open up in another eight locations to strengthen
our position in Glasgow, Edinburgh, and Aberdeen. This will give us a
presence in areas that we are not in yet,'' he said.
He points to the fact that the number of mobile phones in the UK is
expected to grow from the existing 3.5 million to 11 million in five
years time.
''There is only a three to four per cent market penetration in
Scotland,'' Richard said, ''which is less than half the penetration in
England. There is plenty of room for growth.''
To keep pace with the rate of expansion DX may go down the franchise
route. ''One of the problems of becoming larger is that it is more
difficult to maintain management control to ensure our quality of
service,'' explained the youthful managing director, ''but if people
have a stake in their own business it is easier''.
Why the DX title? Richard was reading a book by a Canadian business
guru who wrote that to succeed in business a person requires Desire and
Expectation which prompted Richard to name his company DX.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Beazer advances at half-time mark</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484827</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHO wants to be a housebuilder these days? The market is tailing off
and bad weather is currently adding to the uncertainties caused by the
economic climate, writes ANDREW WILSON.
Even what is usually regarded as the best in the industry is being hit
with Beazer Homes chief executive Dennis Webb saying yesterday that
reservations in the first couple of months in 1995 are 9% below those of
a year earlier in what is usually the beginning of the best selling
season of the year.
The company, which was spun off from Hanson last year at 165p (now
126p), saw half-time pre-tax profits leap 57% to #24.5m on a 53% rise in
turnover to #205m.
Margins improved slightly to 12.3% but were held back by the sharp
increase in the number of social housing units sold from 276 to 719.
These include those brought in with the Mowlem Homes' acquisition for
#31m and where selling prices average #38,100, a fall from the preceding
year's #41,000, which has resulted in dragging down the Beazer overall
average by #500 to #61,500.
The Walker Homes subsidiary built 128 units at an average price of
#80,000 and seems set to effectively double last year's total.
Altogether Beazer sold 503 units in Scotland with a 7.5% market share.
Social housing margins should improve as the Mowlem units are brought
up to Beazer levels of profitability of around 10%. However, that will
coincide with a likely drop in national sales on social units as
Government grants are cut further -- by about #600m.
Beazer is well heeled with net cash of #54m which is being used to
expand the land bank with requirements for the next three years now
covered at 17,961 plots.Full-year profits seem likely to emerge at
around #52m compared with #33.9m for the preceding nine months. The
interim dividend is 1.95p with a 5.75p total possible for a 5.7% yield.
* CUSSINS Property increased full-year pre-tax profits 57% to #2.22m on
sales 19% greater at #23.9m. Private house sales rose 14% to 323 units.
The dividend total has been increased 25% to 3.75p with a 2.35p final.
</TEXT>
