<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cashing in on our equitable heritage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HARRY CONROY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>CHANGING FOCUS,SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484828</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
From its distinguished history in banking, Scotland has now become a
major financial centre. Harry Conroy reports on our fastest-growing
indigenous industry
SCOTLAND may not be in the Top 10 of footballing nations in the world
but when it comes to hard cash we are up there with the best of them.
As a nation we recently nudged into the Premier League of the world's
centres for handling equities under management.
In Europe we are the third financial centre, behind London and Paris,
but ahead of Frankfurt.
It is facts like these which allows Professor Grant Baird, chief
executive of Scottish Financial Enterprise, to feel no sense of
inferiority when mingling with European or global business bosses.
After all, among the SFE's 200-odd membership are some world leaders
such as Standard Life, the largest mutual assurance company in Europe
and General Accident, the third largest general insurer in the UK and
the 26th largest in the United States.
The financial sector in Scotland has deep roots going back hundreds of
years with the Bank of Scotland this year celebrating it's 300th
anniversary.
It is this long history which allows Scotland to claim the oldest
professional bodies of their kind in the world in the Institute of
Chartered Accountants of Scotland founded in 1854 and the Chartered
Institute of Bankers in Scotland founded in 1875.
''There is no doubt that our financial services sector is seen as
independent from London,'' said Professor Baird, ''and we are
expanding''.
This expansion can be seen on the jobs front where, in 1993, the
estimated number of people employed in banking, insurance and business
services was estimated to be 209,000. This figure had risen to 218,000
in 1994.
Among the new companies to arrive is the Abbey National's personal
finance direct phone service which, within the next three years, will
employ 250 in their Glasgow headquarters, while General Accident Direct
are also increasing their their workforce at Bishopbriggs.
Financial and business services is Scotland's fastest growing sector
in terms of employment with 70,000 jobs created since 1985.
The success story includes the arrival of Barclays Stockbrokers in
Glasgow in 1989. In their first year Barclays Stockbrokers employed 97
staff. Today it is breaking through the 400 figure.
Allied Provincial Securities, created in 1986 by the merger of eight
regional stockbroking firms, has its head office in Glasgow and all the
firm's settlements are done in the city.
The presence of such firms has meant that the Scottish Stock Exchange,
a unit of the London Stock Echange, has grown in importance and is now
the largest regional stock exchange in the UK.
Glasgow handles one third of the transactions completed by the London
Stock Exchange.
Tony Vine-Lott of Barclays Stockbrokers illustrated the importance of
Glasgow as a Stock Exchange centre when he said: ''We have more than
90,000 customers with total assets in the region of #1,100m which we
invest on their behalf through Glasgow.''
Scotland's financial heritage dates back to the seventeenth century
when the Bank of Scotland was founded in 1695 but Edinburgh blossomed as
an international investment centre when the legal companies began to
invest money on behalf of their rich merchant clients.
Their activities gave rise to the growth of investment trusts and
Scottish money helped build the Canadian Pacific Railroad, while Scots
investors owned ranches such as the ''Matador'' in Texas.
Scottish based fund managers now control more than #40 billion of
funds with over one third of UK investment trusts managed in Scotland,
including two of the largest independant trusts, the Alliance Trust and
the Scottish Investment Trust.
Grant Baird pointed out: ''In the past eight years there has been
almost a four-fold increase in the value of funds managed in Scotland.
Our strength in this area continues to grow.''
More than 20,000 are currently employed in the Scottish life sector
and the eight Scottish life companies have funds of #92.5 billion under
their control.
The Scottish life sector is reckoned to have 18.6% of all the UK
long-term life assurance and pension business, and 21% of UK personal
pension business.
''The number of people employed by our life companies has more than
doubled since 1986'', said Professor Baird.
Despite the size of the Scottish financial sector, and the importance
to our economy it was a disparate force until Scottish Financial
Enterprise was formed in 1986.
''Our aim,'' said Professor Baird, ''is to enhance Scotland's position
as a financial sector of world standing.''
The SFE has acted as a catalyst and was heavily involved along with
Scottish Enterprise in ensuring that AIM (Alternative Investment Market)
was successfully launched last month.
It was expected that AIM could have a major spin-off effect on
Scottish brokers, solicitors and accountants who could grab a major
slice of the work involved in floating smaller companies.
''Our membership ranges from the main banks and merchant banks, to
brokers, lawyers, and accountants who provide the support services in
Scotland.
''It is the presence of such an infrastructure which can attract more
business to Scotland through AIM,'' said Grant Baird.
Scottish banks have also in recent years begun to flex their financial
muscle.
Since 1986 their total assets have grown by 180% to #74.2 billion and
they continue to lead the way in may areas of banking.
It was Scots who invented watermarks on banks, and would you believe
it, introduced cash credits, the forerunner of overdrafts.
The financial sector now accounts for almost 20% of Scotland's GDP,
and one in nine Scot's are employed in it.
The introduction of information technology means that geographical
location is no longer important. Expertise and reputation is what is
required, and the Scottish financial community has plenty of both.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Education can make Scotland world class</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHANIE YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SOAPBOX,SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484829</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND faces a stark challenge as it approaches the millennium. It
must accede to the need for nothing less than a cultural revolution if
it is to survive as an economic force and we are to maintain and improve
our standard of living against competitor nations.
The seat of that challenge lies in education, attainment of
qualifications and their relevancy to our industrial and commercial
infrastructure. Patently, in any rapidly moving economic environment,
the quality of the output from our educational and training
establishments needs continuous development -- to at least the level of
our industrial and commercial rivals. By implication, that must be the
responsibility not only of the educationalists, but also of employers,
in equal measure.
For a text book lesson in the way forward, witness many of our highly
successful inward investing companies. A major component in that success
is their own commitment, and that of the workforces, to continuous
skills development -- a corollary of the need to remain competitive in
the international marketplace.
ASCETT, an industry-led body chaired by John Ward (Director of IBM's
operations in Scotland and Northern England, and Chairman of CBI
Scotland) was established in 1993 by the Secretary of State for
Scotland. Its key purpose is to oversee and report annually to the
Scottish Office on progress towards a set of quite specific education
and skills targets for the year 2000, as well as to advise the
Government on the performance and policies required to achieve them.
Launched in April of last year, the Education and Training Targets for
a Competitive Scotland -- the first of their kind in Scotland -- demand
that four key targets be met:
1. Eightyfive per cent of young people attain SVQ Level II -- five
standard grades, or equivalent.
2. Seventy per cent attain SVQ Level III -- three highers, or
equivalent.
3. Sixty per cent of the workforce to be qualified to at least SVQ
Level III.
4. Fifty per cent of organisations recognised as, or committed to,
Investors in People.
These are targets designed to significantly lift Scotland's levels of
attainment in education and skills training to increase the power of our
economic engine. To be fully achievable, they require not only the
committed input of Government and educationalists, but that of the wider
business community. In short, they are about making Scotland
world-class.
To put the size of the challenge into focus -- 69% of young people
managed the first target in 1992, the benchmark year. Fifty per cent
succeeded in attaining the second target and 42% the third. Just 21
companies had completed assessment for, or committed themselves to, the
Investors in People goal. By comparison, France has already achieved
goal three, a target we're not scheduled to hit until the turn of the
century.
The targets are set against a need to keep pace, or close gaps, with
competitors in North America, other parts of Western Europe, Japan and
emergent economic forces in the Far East and Eastern Europe.
To achieve target one, Scotland must maintain its average annual
increase of 2.7%. Measured from 1990, we are currently on schedule, but
many things could upset the rate of progress. It is necessary, for
example, to encourage all young men and women, not in full-time
education, to aim for an SVQ at Level II or above. This means we need
high-quality careers education and advice provision.
The second target, I admit, is demanding. To succeed here, we need to
accomplish the projected advances in meeting target one and use this as
a foundation for higher level qualifications. Since 1990, the average
annual increase has been 2.9%. In order to reach the target, we need an
annual increase of 3.48%.
Acceptance of the need to undergo continuous learning, or Life Long
Learning, as it's been dubbed, is crucial among both employers and
individuals. It is central to our long-term industrial and economic
health and is already the focus of human resource development in several
large manufacturing concerns.
Success depends upon a variety of factors, but chiefly upon
implementing and achieving the SVQ framework across all sectors.
There is a link to the fourth target concerning the Investors In
People programme. This award is intended to provide a framework for
improving business performance by demonstrating the association between
people development and practical business performance. The programme is
undergoing a review in Scotland with the objective of making it more
beneficial to all sectors and companies, including the small business
community. By the end of 1994, 650 companies had committed to it.
A consultation document, World Class Scotland, is available from
ASCETT , 120 Bothwell Street, Glasgow G2 7JP. It is free of charge and
we welcome responses to it.
The challenges facing us are broad, but they also carry depth in
relation to all our futures. We all have a responsibility to our
economy. Put very crudely, if we don't apply ourselves as a nation to
the tasks ahead, perhaps the phrase that starts off with ''Wha's like
us, damn few . . .'' will come to represent something dangerously at
odds with the original sentinment.
The jury is out until January 1, 2000.
* Stephanie Young, Director of the Advisory Scottish Council for
Education and Training Targets (ASCETT), was talking to Yvonne Wightman.
</TEXT>
