<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Powered back to the future</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484830</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
There has been no shortage of irony in Alan Jefferson's life since he
arrived in Scotland seven years ago.
He came north to take over the position of sales director of the
Clydesdale chain, then seen as a successful expanding company. But Alan
did not stay long in the position as he ''did not see eye to eye on
policy'' with those above him.
Shortly after his departure from Clydesdale he joined ScottishPower to
set up a seperate retail division in readiness for privatisation.
The task facing the newcomer in his job was daunting. In 1990 the new
division made a loss of #5.3m but by 1993/94 he had turned this round to
a #7.4m profit.
The turnaround is partly due to ScottishPower's purchase last year of
39 superstores -- formerly trading as Clydesdale!
Alan's memory of ScottishPower's showrooms on arrival is of clocks!
''There were 20 suppliers to our 73 shops. Each manager could order
directly. We had every kind of clock you could think of but it was not
the way to run a business. There was no way you could control it.''
Nowadays the clocks are gone and ScottishPower are now more focused on
what they sell.
In 1992 Alan moved ScottishPower Retail into TV and audio equipment.
The Retail Divisions turnover is approaching #200m this year making it
the UK's third largest electrical retailer.
This growth has meant that ScottishPowers share of the white goods
market has gone from 16% to 35% and in the audio field they have gone
from zero to 20%.
Although he had not lived in Scotland until his work brought him here
Alan was no stranger to the country.
He spent most of his holiday's around the Ullapool area of the West
Highlands enjoying his favourite pastime of birdwatching.
But it is not just our feathered friends that Alan is keeping an eye
open for it is also any possible sites for expansion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blue-chip contractssit well on the board</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,TRAILBLAZERS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484831</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS week's TrailBlazer focuses on the evolution of one of the most
successful young companies in the north Glasgow area. In 1987, David
Baird, a former electronics engineer with the Anderson Strathclyde
mining group, established Kelvinside Electronics Ltd (KEL) in
Kirkintilloch, from what originally formed the group's electronics
division.
''Anderson Strathclyde was going through a lot of restructuring at the
time and had no further use for the electronic division,'' Baird
explains, ''I could have stayed with the group but my future role was
unclear and it would probably have meant relocating. I realised that the
electronics division still had potential on its own merit and Anderson
would still have a need for the product.''
A feasibility study confirmed this potential, which was sufficient
motivation to set up the company and provide a fully comprehensive range
of services to clients requiring the input of specialist knowledge and
expertise in the field of electronic design and manufacture. It was
originally utilised in the production of control panels and air flow
detection instruments with Anderson as the main client.
Though business flourished in the first year the company has had its
hurdles to overcome. During its second year of operation the mining
industry entered its downward spiral and it became clear to Baird that
the company had to diversify into other more promising areas of
production if it was to continue.
''The prosperity enjoyed during our first year allowed us to spend the
second year bringing in new personnel and developing the business
towards a new client base,'' said Baird.
The company expanded its services to include electronic design,
prototyping, CAD -- Printed Circuit Board (PCB) design, full component
procurement, PCB assembly, final system assembly, inspection, testing
and packaging. The client base expanded to include companies in fields
such as aerospace, the automotive and marine industries, computer
manufacture, offshore petrochemical and the entertainment sector.
''For the luxury jet market we have taken a basic concept and produced
a range of galley and entertainment control panels'', added Baird, ''All
of the panels were designed by KEL and are fully supported and
maintained by the company.''
The firm have also completed a high-volume automotive project
involving PCB design, manufacture and test of a panel which illuminates
dashboard instrumentation.
Manufacturing services offered by KEL range from ''free issue'' PCB
assembly through to complete procurement of all materials required
within a system build including enclosures, power supplies, wiring and
so on.
When the company was approached by Dunbartonshire Local Enterprise
Company (LEC) and invited to become a growth partner, Baird agreed that
the time for expansion had arrived. With some assistance from the LEC,
new custom-built premises are currently being built in Kilsyth to where
KEL hopes to move in September. This represents an investment of around
#1.5m over the next two years by KEL. Sales and marketing manager, Paul
Brooks, joined the firm 10 months ago as part of its expansion
programme. ''Our five-year plan which started six months ago, is to
increase the size of the company by further developing our customer base
and bringing more employment to the area,'' he said.
The company currently employs a staff of 16 and, mainly through word
of mouth and personal referrals, has established an enviable customer
base with many blue-chip companies including IBM (UK) Ltd, British
Aerospace and Scottish Power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>En masse answer to contrition industry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANTHONY TROON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,INNUMERATE NERD</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484832</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Women's Day, National No Smoking Day . . . yesterday
seemed a little crowded. We considered all the psychological pressures
during our coffee break in the Nerd House commissariat.
''I'm glad these 'Days' are getting bunched together like that,''
offered The Braces. ''It leaves more of the year free for normal life.
If you behave normally on one of these 'Days', people look at you as if
you're some kind of rat. Lend us a fag, Angelica.
Angelica Banana-Skyne, the High Whitecraigs polymath, tossed her
packet across with a frown. ''You are a rat,'' she said, ''on this of
all days''.
The Braces was flummoxed. ''Angelica,'' he said, ''you're smoking too.
You know what we decided. One for all, all for one, and all that. We
would not bow to psychological coercion.''
Angelica said that wasn't what she meant. This was also International
Women's Day, and The Braces should be lending her a cigarette. ''See
what you mean,'' said The Braces, taking one of Angelica's super-low tar
tipped, incinerating the far end, and coughing slightly. ''Gad,'' he
said, ''these are horrible''.
We came to the conclusion, though, that The Braces had stumbled upon
an interesting if somewhat radical concept. If all the ''Days'' which
were designed to inflict feelings of anxiety and remorse upon us were
amalgamated, then the contrition industry would be severely castrated,
which seemed an appropriate term for Women's Day.
For example, we could continue to combine International Women's Day
with National No Smoking Day, bring in Mother's Day, Father's Day and St
Valentine's Day, and invent some new ones like Vegetarian Day, Jogging
Day, No Soap Opera Day, No Jokes Day and International Celibacy Day. The
pressure groups would have their moment, and the whole thing could be
disposed of in 24 hours. It could be called ''International Guilt Day''.
We liked the idea. But what would be the best date?
''How about February 29?'' asked Angelica, reaching for her packet of
fags. As a special gesture to mark yesterday's celebration, The Braces
clunked open his Zippo and gave her flame.
* The awful plight of Cedric Brown, chief executive of British Gas --
called back before the Commons select committee to discuss a bonus
scheme which could increase his modest basic salary of #450,000 by 125%
-- has been haunting me. I have been having dreams about it.
People, who have salaries, do not like to discuss them. This is an
ancient code. Some prefer not to debate them with their spouses, let
alone Commons select committees. For the same reason, people do not like
to discuss their winnings at the dog track with their spouses, or with
Commons select committees, although you don't tend to get bonus schemes
at the dog track.
As a minor player in the affairs of Nerd House, a mere functionary in
our gloom-laden financial services sector, I imagined myself summoned to
a committee room in Westminster and asked to explain my earnings.
Chairman: ''It says here that your earnings fluctuate between #20,000
and #30,000 a year. Do you expect us to believe that?''
Me: No. ''I can hardly believe it myself.''
Chairman: ''We have recently interviewed a Mr Cedric Brown who earned
more than 20 times that amount before we even started talking bonuses.
Mr Brown put up a very articulate case for the level of his earnings. Do
you think you can do the same?''
Me: ''I would certainly hope so. I recall that Mr Brown was
accompanied at his hearing by the chairman of British Gas, but
unfortunately my own chairman is not able to be with us today, due to a
Spring run of salmon on th River Carron.''
Chairman: (looking agitated): ''Spring run of . . . Damn. This hearing
is now concluded. But there is a strong chance you may be recalled.''
Me: ''I can't think of anything else I could . . . err . . .''
Chairman: ''Your preliminary written submission did not mention a
Spring run of salmon in the River Carron, for a start. Hearing
dismissed.'' (Bang of gavel as members change into warm tweeds,
ghillie's hats, and rush out).
I wake up, sweating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
