<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ladbroke lobbies for a level playing field with the Lottery.  Pools firm suffers a 15% decline in its turnover</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484833</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE POOLS industry has been badly affected by the success of the
National Lottery since its inception last November but that is partly
because it is not a level playing field.
Peter George chief executive of Ladbroke, owners of Vernons --
Britain's second largest pools company behind Littlewoods -- said that
the pools companies had been treated ''quite shabbily'' and were
effectively having to compete with one hand tied behind their backs.
In particular he cited the preferential rules governing the Lottery in
areas such as advertising and the roll-over of prize money. He said that
the campaign to get betting duty substantially reduced would continue.
Football pools companies currently pay 37.5% of their revenues in tax
whereas the National Lottery only pays the Treasury 12% of its income.
Vernons turnover has dropped 15% since the launch of the lottery but
the company refused to say how much of the #2.3m fall in profits was
attributable to the lottery. Ladbroke remains committed to the Vernons
business, which remains profitable, although it has had to be
restructured to take account of its declining fortunes with the loss of
95 jobs. Ladbroke has also chosen to make a prudent writedown of #100m
in the brand value of Vernons, effectively valuing it at nothing in the
balance sheet.
However the rest of Ladbroke's betting business, including racing,
continues to prosper. The division made a record profit of #98m last
year on turnover of #2637m.
Deregulation of the UK market allowing evening and Sunday betting,
more attractive shops selling food and non-alcohoic drink and the
ability to establish amusement machines in betting shops all suggest
more profitable growth in the future. Having acquired three casions last
year, Ladbroke hopes to develop the business both at home and abroad to
take account of liberalisation in this sector of the market.
Following the agreed sale of the Texas Homecare DIY business to
Sainsbury's for #290m, Ladbroke will be able to pay off all its
outstanding sterling debt and focus on its core divisions of hotels and
betting.
Its Hilton hotel chain has proved resilient throughout the recession
which is surprising given that 60-70% of its clients are on business.
However it has benefited from its geographic spread worldwide. In what
remains a tough market its operating profit held steady at #126.8m with
the average room rate just 1% higher.
The performance of the business improved in the second half and has
continued in the current financial year, helped by a recovery in demand
in some of the Continental markets such as Germany and the opening of
four new hotels. The UK hotel chain performed well, benefiting from
further strengthening in the economy with good increases in both
occupancy and room rates.
Ladbroke sees further growth potential from opening in City centre
sites where it is currently unrepresented, developing resort hotels for
business customers offering a range of leisure and entertainment
activities such as golf and casinos in addition to conference facilities
and extension of the Hilton brand name into new areas.
The total dividend was maintained at 6p after the payment of a final
shareholders' payment of 3.6p. This followed a jump of 20.3% in annual
profit before tax and exceptional items to #128.5m. Exceptional items
for the year amounted to a charge of #358.3m before tax and included
#201.8m relating to the write-off of reinstated goodwill on the sale of
Texas Homecare. Other exceptional items included a #38.2m provision for
loss on sale of Texas Homecare, #53.4m relating to a fundamental
reorganisation of the Texas business resulting in the closure of 40
outlets and a profit of #75m on the termination of the Hong Kong Hilton
management contract.
Ladbroke shares dipped a penny to 171p.
</TEXT>
