<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legal right to assistance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484834</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE situation Mr and Mrs Wishart find themselves in need not have
happened had they been timeously advised of their right to financial
help from the Department of Social Security.
Under the National Assistance Act 1948, (Choice of Accommodation)
Directions 1992, and various other sections, if Mrs Nellie Berry had
less than #3000 in savings she was entitled by law to weekly help with
fees up to #198.40 per week. This applies even is she owns a house, and
the total rises after April to #204.40 per week.
There are benefits and drawbacks in making this claim which is
mandatory and not discretionary on the DSS.
Advantages are that you do not go near the social work department and
do not get means tested other than for the DSS cut-off limit. It is a
must that to get this help you do not seek help from your local
authority. The main advantage is that no repayment is made even when the
elderly resident dies and the house is sold.
Disadvantages are that under this system the resident does not get a
personal allowance (pocket money). The amount is a little less than one
might get under the Community Care Act, too, but this is more than made
up for in that the daughter or other carer can then keep on a job and
any small top-up payment to the residential home is catered for.
You must use a private home and not a local authority home to qualify.
Most private homes will give very good care for between #194 and #220
per week, and there are many very good homes to choose from. The scare
stories of a very few homes in trouble for poor care practices should
not put people off from using one of the many good private homes.
Full publicity and use of this right would help save Strathclyde
Regional Council social work department an enormous sum every year which
it could spend elsewhere to everyone's benefit, at least until the
Government catches on and changes the law. I have successfully used this
Act.
David Watson,
Sunart Residential Home
For The Elderly,
58 Alexander Street,
Airdrie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Electricity storm is rumbling on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484835</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE NEW part-paid electricity shares lost further ground yesterday,
dipping to their issue prices at one point before steadying.
PowerGen ended 2[1/2]p lower at 187[1/2]p, just a shade above the 185p
sale price, after touching 183p. National Power was finally 1p down at
175[1/2]p, after a low of 171p, against their 170p issue price.
Northern Electric continued its precipitate decline, tumbling 104p to
793p as dealers assumed Trafalgar House would withdraw its bid. The
company itself was still talking with OFFER, the industry watchdog.
Shares of the other English electricity distributors were all sharply
lower, with analysts unwilling to forecast where they would stabilise.
Meanwhile the storm over the threat of industry regulator Professor
Stephen Littlechild to impose stricter price controls over the
distributors continued and there were widespread calls for the Professor
to resign.
Big investors were furious and there was mutinous talk that they would
try to cancel their cheques. However a spokesman for the Government's
advisers Kleinwort Benson and BZW said they had entered a binding
contract and could not cancel.
David Manning, investment director of Legal &amp; General, which did not
put in for shares, commented: ''I don't expect our institutions to try
and withdraw. It is the sort of thing the Americans might think about
doing.''
Coming after the Barings crash and the current weakness of sterling,
the debacle is another episode to dent the City of London's position
worldwide.
Small investors will no doubt be right behind the British businessman
who reportedly issued a writ against the Treasury and its advisers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lucky Ludo makes a profit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT MCLAUGHLAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484836</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE public offer of shares in the two English electricity generators
excited my interest on behalf of the portfolio I run for Ludovic
Ranfurly.
I believed that it might be possible to engage in a bit of opportunism
by buying and selling. And, as I had already hinted in an earlier column
that I would go for this issue, I felt obliged to do so though I knew
that the penny piece allotments would be made even worse than usual by
the Treasury's insistence that all applicants be forced to appply for
both stocks. That certainly deterred me from applying for both Ludo and
Gilly his wife.
I bid for 1000 shares for him only and was allotted 255 National Power
and 170 Power Gen. Such allotments make nonsense of intelligent
portfolio management. I can see the Government's point of view -- they
would like to spread a little jam. As it happens I just sold the
allotments through Tilney his brokers first thing on Monday morning,
getting a good price which left him with a profit of #25.
The #25 will go to his cash holdings but it left me moaning until I
read about Professor Littlechild, the electricity industry regulator.
Seldom can anyone in such a position have got a thing as wrong as did
the Professor when he regulated the electricity companies six months
ago. The damage he did when correcting his own inadequacy this week has
been immense. His timing had all the sensitivity of the German advance
through Belgium in August 1914, coming the day after the generators
offer and three days before decision day for the Trafalgar House bid for
Northern Electric.
The two generating stocks are sound enough investments and should be
held by those who are content with small holdings or can build them up a
bit. But the appeal of all utilities has been reduced and the
prospectuses on which they were sold shown to be misleading. Ludo is
lucky not to have had his fingers burned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>T&amp;N ishauntedby past</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484837</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GHOSTS from the past continue to haunt T&amp;N as the front line
technology autocomponents group has had to increase its estimate of
current year costs against US asbestosis claims by #10m to about #50m.
In November, the City was shocked when the former Turner &amp; Newall made a
#140m provision against claims which chairman Colin Hope said were made
higher by the ''scandalous behaviour of the American legal profession.''
To preserve cash, T&amp;N is maintaining the 1994 dividend total at 10.85p
but will reduce that for the current year to 6p to save about #35m
including the advance corporation tax.
Pre-tax profits ended 85% lower at #10.7m.
However shareholder loyalty has been encouraged by a remarkably good
trading result with operating profits jumping 47% to #180m after #20m of
exceptional charges. T&amp;N is meeting its performance targets of a 10%
return on sales with a rise in 1994 from 8.7% to 10.3% on turnover 16%
higher at #1936m and has started off 1995 with record production runs to
supply German and French customers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pound claws its way back from overnight massacre.  Clarke and George meet.  Industrial output falls. French raise rates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484838</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE pound staged a partial recovery from a post-war low of DM2.22 in
Far Eastern trading as central bankers appealed for calm on the foreign
exchange markets.
But the Bank of England was not expected to raise UK interest rates in
defence of sterling after a drop in industrial production in January
reinforced other indications that the economy had slowed down.
Continuing turmoil on the foreign exchange markets forced the Bank of
France to impose a 24-hour, 8% lending rate in place of its 6.4%,
five-to-10-day emergency rate after the franc had fallen to an all-time
low of Ffr3.5880 to the German mark.
Denmark, Belgium, and Portugal also increased short-term rates in an
effort to stabilise their currencies within the ERM.
After its overnight battering sterling managed to move up to DM2.2650
in mid-afternoon before ending European trading at DM2.2528, only
slightly lower than on Tuesday despite the exceptional volatility of its
trading range.
But it lost ground to around $1.6175 as the dollar perked up to
DM1.3920 and 90.95 yen, well clear of overnight all-time lows.
Sterling's trade weighted index retreated to 86.0 from 86.5 after a low
of 85.8.
The Bundesbank said the latest movements on currency markets were
exaggerated and not in line with economic fundamentals. It welcomed the
decision by the Bank of France to raise interest rates as well as
assurances by the US that the authorities in Washington believed a
strong dollar was in the national interest.
A call by Bundesbank council member Hans-Juergen Krupp for lower
German interest rates was thought to represent a minority view within
the central bank.
Later Bundesbank president Hans Tietmeyer said, ''We will see if we
have room for a small rate cut. We will also naturally have to see
whether we should raise interest rates in the foreseeable future.''
Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan told the House of
Representatives' budget committee that the dollar's weakness was
''unwelcome'', ''troublesome'', and ''very likely overdone''.
The dollar crashed to fresh overnight lows of 88.75 yen and 1.3450
mark despite further intervention by the Bank of Japan, which has become
increasingly agitated about the knock-on effects of the strong yen.
Mr Greenspan also said that the US had very large blocks of marks and
yen to use in the foreign currency markets and its ability to intervene
would not be impaired by the Mexican rescue package.
Concerted intervention by leading central banks late on Thursday and
Friday last week failed to arrest the dollar's decline and was widely
perceived to have been half-hearted and ill-timed.
In London arch-bear Nick Knight said the dollar would remain weak
until US rates were raised substantially.
He added that his February 17 forecast that the dollar would fall to
90 yen and DM1.40 had been surpassed by a large margin and repeated his
prognostication that the Dow would fall to 3200 and the FTSE-100 to 2400
as a weak dollar pushed the US economy to a hard landing.
The stock market took its cue from the fall in output and retrieved
some of its recent losses, but trading was nervous. Sentiment was also
helped by a slight easing in currency tensions and an encouraging batch
of corporate results. The Footsie closed 15.1 points higher at 2992.1.
Industrial production fell by a seasonally adjusted 0.5% in January
against expectations that it would increase by 0.5%. The December figure
was revised down from 0.8% to 0.6% and the year-on-year rate fell back
sharply to 3.7% from 5.3% in December.
Oil production was hit by the bad weather in the first half of January
and oil and gas extraction fell by 1.2% between December and January.
There was all-round weakness in manufacturing output, which fell by
0.6% after gaining 0.5% in December. Year-on-year growth was cut from
5.2% to 3%.
Manufacturing also declined in November. Indeed the Central
Statistical Office revised that fall from 0.6% to 0.9%.
As a result manufacturing edged down 0.1% between the latest two
three-monthly periods, a clear signal that output had slowed to a
snail's pace.
However, compared with the same three months a year ago manufacturing
was 4.3%. The Treasury said the pace of expansion had clearly slowed in
recent months, but business surveys pointed to a healthy manufacturing
sector based on export success.
The latest CBI survey claimed that export orders were at record levels
and last week's Purchasing Managers' survey pointed to a pick-up in the
pace of manufacturing activity after a slowdown over the previous six
months.
James Capel's Adam Cole noted that two-thirds of the January fall in
manufacturing output was attributable to engineering, where the trend is
strongly upwards, but exceptionally volatile with monthly movements of
1% in either direction in recent months.
Retail sales also fell in January, suggesting that the economy got off
to a slow start this year. This provides some encouragement to the
Treasury and the Bank of England that higher interest rates and
increased taxes are restricting growth to a more sustainable pace.
The Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke, met the Governor of
the Bank of England, Eddie George, for about an hour in the morning. The
currency crisis would have been discussed though it scarcely rated a
mention in the Treasury's monthly monetary report published to coincide
with the meeting.
By mid-morning the pound's trade weighted index was about 2.7% below
its year-end level. Its loss against the mark, offset by gains against
the dollar bloc, was 7.5%.
Strength against the dollar should help to curb inflationary pressures
by reducing sterling-denominated commodity prices, and weakness against
the mark should be good for exports.
But if this went too far some manufacturing sectors could run into
capacity restraints and raise their prices. A rough rule of thumb
suggests that a 3% to 4% drop in the trade weighted index is equivalent
to a 1% fall in base rates.
Thus sterling's weakness has fully offset the 0.5% increase in rates
last month. If this persists it could cause concern to the Chancellor
and the Governor when they meet next month.
</TEXT>
