<TEXT>
* KENNY Dalglish was back on familiar ground last night -- looking
down on the rest of the Premiership.
Blackburn had lost top spot for 24 hours with Manchester United
winning at Wimbledon on Tuesday, but the side, managed and developed by
Dalglish, proved once and for all against Arsenal with a 3-1 win that
when the pressure is really on they do not flinch.
Alan Shearer passed a fitness test on his dodgy knee less than two
hours before kick-off, but the Blackburn striker brought Arsenal to
their knees with two goals -- taking his tally for the season to a
remarkable 31.
Graeme Le Saux also weighed in with a spectacular strike as Blackburn
retained their three-point advantage over United with both clubs having
10 games left to play.
While there was joy for Shearer, it was a miserable night for Ian
Wright. He was dropped to the subs' bench by caretaker manager Stewart
Houston.
Wright replaced John Hartson in 58 minutes, but by then the Gunners
were chasing the game, and they did pull one back through Steve Morrow.
