<HEADLINE>Same-again Scots for Twickenham</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484840</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND go into the Grand Slam showdown against England in 10 days
with an unchanged side.
Manager Duncan Paterson, announcing the make-up of the squad at
Murrayfield yesterday, said that the selection meeting on Tuesday night
had been one of the speediest on record. In fact, and in a tone which
indicated that this had not always been the case in recent seasons, he
said that he had managed to get home from Edinburgh to Galashiels that
same night.
There was little doubt that the selectors would keep faith with the
side which demolished Wales 26-13 at Murrayfield on Saturday.
There was, perhaps, a case to be made for bringing Tony Stanger on to
the bench to cover the wing and centre positions, but the selectors have
obviously decided that to tinker with the 21-man squad at this late
stage in the Five Nations' campaign would be to tempt the fates which
have operated so gloriously in Scotland's favour since the tide turned
against Canada in January.
Ever the perfectionist, Paterson declared that although the same
personnel would uphold Scottish honour at Twickenham, there had been
much thought given to detailed analysis of the game against Wales.
''We had a bit more time to look at the video-tapes from Saturday, and
obviously without wanting to take anything away from a tremendous
performance, we did look at certain areas where we could improve.''
Specifically, and no doubt with Rob Jones' second-minute try at
Murrayfield on Saturday in mind, Paterson pinpointed concentration,
first-time tackling, and, without naming them, the necessity for
''certain individuals'' to put in more tackles than they had done
against the Welsh, as being the areas that will require more spit and
polish before the winners-take-all encounter against England.
Paterson underlined the crucial roll now played in international
preparation by the video recorder.
''The big advancement this year is the technology available,'' he
said. ''I'm quite pleased that it wasn't around when I was playing, I
can assure you of that. Individuals are now very closely monitored and
there is no hiding place.''
The SRU has access to all video footage shot by the BBC at Murrayfield
internationals and, using footage provided by 13 cameras from seven
different angles, one of director of rugby Jim Telfer's tasks is to edit
segments showing in comprehensive detail the performance of individual
players.
The type of non-broadcast material which the Scottish coaches make use
of focuses on ''one-on-one'' player situations where the ball is
elsewhere on the park. ''We have looked closely at certain areas, and
while they were minor things they are things that can be put right and
hopefully that will be done before Saturday week.''
The manager said that the Twickenham game represented a huge
challenge. ''It's no secret that England are in the top three nations in
the world at the moment, or at least they should be. We have always said
that we want to be in the top six. A good result against England would
help those ratings along a wee bit.
''But one of the tremendous things in Scotland this season has been
how the squad have taken each step one at a time, and we just hope that
we can take one more very big step on Saturday week,'' he said.
The manager also revealed that the 26-strong World Cup squad will now
be chosen on April 4, two weeks later than planned. This will give more
time for potential squad members such as Alan Sharp, Andy Nicol, Peter
Walton, and Damian Cronin to overcome injury problems. Sharp, Walton,
and Nicol are this week undergoing intensive physiotherapy at the
Lilleshall Sports Injury Centre in Shropshire.
The international squad session at Murrayfield, which is normally
staged on a Sunday before at international, will take place on Saturday.
This, said Paterson, would allow the players, and in particular the
Exiles, to spend a rare Sunday with their families.
The decision to offer a league amnesty to players involved with the
international squad also was applauded by Paterson. ''It takes away the
risk of injury and, given the injury list we are carrying at the moment,
it gives peace of mind that we are not going to lose anybody else. From
that point of view it is very advantageous,'' he said.
Tickets for the Twickenham match are said to be changing hands on the
black market at stratospheric prices. The Scottish allocation of 4800 --
the regulation number for Twickenham -- is sold out and the Scottish
support will be outnumbered in the 60,000 all-seated stadium.
Scotland -- A G Hastings (Watsonians); C A Joiner (Melrose), G P J
Townsend (Gala), S Hastings (Watsonians), K M Logan (Stirling County); C
M Chalmers (Melrose), B W Redpath (Melrose); D I W Hilton (Bath), K S
Milne (Heriot's FP), P H Wright (Boroughmuir), G W Weir (Melrose), S J
Campbell (Dundee HS FP), R I Wainwright (West Hartlepool), E W Peters
(Bath), I R Morrison (London Scottish).
Replacements -- I C Glasgow (Heriot's FP), A G Shiel (Melrose), D
Patterson (West Hartlepool), J Richardson (Edinburgh Academicals), J
Manson (Dundee HS FP), K D McKenzie (Stirling County).
England -- M J Catt (Bath); T Underwood (Leicester), W D C Carling
(Harlequins), J C Guscott (Bath), R Underwood (Leicester); C R Andrew
(Wasps), K P P Bracken (Bristol); J Leonard (Harlequins), B C Moore
(Harlequins), V E Ubogu (Bath), M O Johnson (Leicester), M C Bayfield
(Northampton), T A K Rodber (Northampton), D Richards (Leicester), B B
Clarke (Bath).
Replacements -- J E B Callard (Bath), P R de Glanville (Bath), C D
Morris (Orrell), G C Rowntree (Leicester), R G R Dawe (Bath), S O Ojomoh
(Bath).
Referee -- B W Stirling (Ireland).
