<HEADLINE>Hearts may be facing a new managerial crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484843</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS Hearts move towards their Scottish Cup quarter-final match against
Dundee United at Tynecastle this weekend, they could face another
managerial crisis.
Tommy McLean, the man persuaded to take over after he had quit
Motherwell, seems to be growing more and more disillusioned by life in
the capital.
There had been suggestions previously that all was not well at
Tyncastle, even though McLean had dragged his side clear of relegation
and steered them to that famous cup victory over Rangers.
Yesterday, McLean confirmed things were not proceeding to his
satisfaction -- and the hint was there that he may be ready to turn his
back on the club in the summer
He pointed out: ''I could have remained at Motherwell for the next
three years or so and won nothing -- but my job would have been safe.
''It was just that I did not like the way the club was going. I
disagreed with what was happening.
''Things were in place, there were good players there, but I was not
going to be allowed to spend any more money on the team. All the
available money was to go on the new stand.''
Now McLean must feel he is in a time warp, trying to strengthen a team
but forced instead to listen to the bullozers outside as a new ground is
built.
No wonder he feels frustrated. No wonder that one of the outstanding
managers in the country could be ready to leave it all behind.
He admits ruefully: ''The money that there is at this club has to be
spent on the stands. I cannot buy the players I would like.
''Let's face it -- if you spend #50,000 on a player then you get that
kind of value. What you get is a #50,000 player and this club deserves
better than that.
''We need big-time players. That's what we must be able to provide for
the supporters.
''If that is not going to happen, then I will have to look at where I
am going. This is the situation I left behind me.
''There is no way this is an ultimatum to the directors. I am just
stating my position. It's how I feel.''
Hearts will go into the Cup clash without midfielder Jim Bett, but
with the confidence that United have a bad record at Tynecastle -- and
that the holders have lost their last two games in the premier division.
Meanwhile, Falkirk, who drew at Fir Park on Tuesday, have found their
survival fight hit by suspensions as they head for Ibrox on Saturday.
Defender David Weir was sent off in the 2-2 draw with Motherwell and
automatically misses the match, while Steve Fulton and new signing Paul
McGrillen are also out because of suspension.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>English song is off-key</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484844</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEWARE of Greeks bearing gifts and Englishmen singing Scotland's rugby
praises. The canny war of words over Scotland's Grand Slam showdown with
England on Saturday week has begun.
This time around the Englishmen appear to have taken a leaf from
Scotland's 1990 pre-match schedule when, at every opportunity, the Scots
lauded England to the rafters.
They deny it to this day but on March 17, 1990, Will Carling's
Englishmen arrived in Edinburgh over-confident. They had swallowed hook,
line, and sinker the bait offered by the Scots who were admitting to
anyone daft enough to listen that it was going to be a privilege just to
share the same turf with the lilly-whites.
This week already, England manager Jack Rowell has been singing a
paeon of praise for Scotland's Gavin Hastings. The captain, said Rowell,
was ''majestic.'' The team was ''impressive.'' And the Scottish forwards
were playing ''better than 1990.''
Yesterday, Carling chimed in with his own gilt-edged commendation for
the Scots. ''Scotland were very impressive in defeating Wales,'' he
said. ''There is a spring in their team. Their reaction-times and
discipline were good. Their unity and collective will is worrying.
''We were always hoping that we would be involved in playing for the
Grand Slam in this fixture -- but we didn't spend any time forecasting
the fortunes of other teams in the Five Nations.'
''We weren't concerned whether Scotland would be involved in the same
ambition as us, but now that they also have won three matches, it will
make the match a real occasion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dons to bus fans for vital Firhill match</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484845</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN will bus their supporters free of charge to Firhill on
Saturday for the vital relegation game against Partick Thistle.
The cash-strapped Pittodrie club, who know their premier division fate
could hinge on the outcome, are prepared to go deeper into debt to get
the backing they need.
Pittodrie supporters' chief Neil McDougall welcomed the move
yesterday, and expects thousands of fans to take up the offer.
He said: ''Chairman Ian Donald told me about the scheme, which is a
tremendous gesture. The club obviously appreciates that this game is
like three cup finals rolled into one.
''I want all Dons fans to rally behind the team in the remaining
fixtures and do their bit to boost the team. I am sure there will be
thousands extra on the gate at Firhill because of this offer.''
Caretaker manager Roy Aitken said: ''I have stressed all along that we
-- players, directors, management, and supporters -- are all in this
together. We share one common aim, to see the club climb out of the
present situation in the league.
''At this stage, our fans have a more important role to play than ever
before. The more we have behind us for such a vital game, the better.
''The club, in association with Grampian Transport, are providing free
buses for those travelling to Glasgow. The players and I appreciate this
initiative.''
Aitken saw Partick Thistle turn up the heat in the relegation battle
by beating Dundee United on Tuesday, and admitted: ''They fully deserved
their victory by showing more willingness.
''It was always going to be a hard game for us down there, but it is
even harder now as Thistle will be lifted by this result.
''It will come down to whose attitude and determination is greatest.
But we will ensure that we are able to handle it.
''Our fate is in our own hands. and I know my players have the
qualities to get us out of trouble. There are nine games left, and a
couple of wins for us will turn the screw on someone else.''
Midfielder Paul Kane is still receiving intensive treatment for a calf
injury in an effort to be fit for Firhill.
* PARTICK THISTLE could be facing a money crisis after they recorded
the lowest premier division attendance of the season.
A crowd of only 2627 turned out to watch Tuesday night's match against
Dundee United, and that has left Thistle officials counting the cost of
their mudbath pitch.
Secretary Robert Reid said: ''A lot of people probably thought the
game would be off, having been postponed five times previously.
''The United fans, in particular, would be unwilling to make the trip
in those circumstances. It was also the start of four home games in
quick succession, and our supporters are now picking and choosing when
to spend their money.
''There are other problems with midweek games, such as football on
televison, that can also affect attendances.
''Tuesday night's attendance was easily our lowest league turnout of
the season, and that figure included all the hospitality.
''However, the 2-0 victory should make it a different story when
Aberdeen visit. That is a vital match, and I expect a much better
attendance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>District scheme proves a winner</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484846</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE were further frustrations this week for Eastwood District
Schools, when their Bank of Scotland Schools Cup quarter-final match
against Queen Victoria School, Dunblane, scheduled for Tuesday, was yet
again postponed.
A win over QVS would give the Glasgow side a place in the semi-final
against Madras College, St Andrews.
The Eastwood formation was the brainchild of Tom Robertson, a former
teacher at Eastwood HS, and draws from five secondary schools in the
south Glasgow area. In addition to Eastwood HS, which has always been a
rugby school, the consortium comprises St Ninians, Williamwood, Wood
Farm, and Mearns Castle.
Robertson's involvement not only continued after his retirement but
increased. ''I took a job as a youth development officer with Clarkston
Rugby Club,'' says Robertson, who reckons that the catchment area is
such that each school should be able to field seperate teams.
Co-operation among the five secondary schools, however, has produced a
situation where they can field teams for each year group. A healthy sign
that rugby is prospering under this system is the fact the Eastwood
District Schools run a second XV in addition to it strong first side.
''Schools rugby is definitely on the increase in the state sector
after reaching an all-time low during the teachers' strike in the
1980s,'' says Roberston.
''I think that there should always be schools rugby. It is the most
efficient way of presenting the sport to youngsters.''
As a youth development officer Robertson thinks that introducing rugby
to primary schools is the best way forward. ''I teach youngsters in
primary schools and then pass them on to local clubs. Thereafter it is
up to the clubs to hold on to them. Also, it is much easier to teach
secondary pupils if they arrive already with the basic skills.''
The success of the district scheme can be measured by the growing
fixture list, which now inlcudes many of the independent schools.
Results against sone of the top schools has been encouraging,
particularly last season when the first XV defeated Keil School. This
season the most heartening result was a draw with Kelvinside Academy at
Balgray.
The most eagerly awaited game this Saturday goes ahead at Auldhouse,
where Hutchesons' and Glasgow HS meet in what should be a quality match
between two successful sides.
Meanwhile, St Aloysius' College, who have also had a frustrating
series of postponements of their quarter-final cup match against Peebles
HS, will try to get the game played today at Millerston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Warriors' secret weapon</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484847</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STENHOUSEMUIR manager Terry Christie is ready to unleash an ''Unknown
Warrior'' in Saturday's Scottish Cup quarter-final tie with Hibs.
Neil Aitken, 23, a fifth-year student at St Andrews University where
he is studying laser physics and optoelectronics, could make a comeback
for the biggest game in the club's history.
The 6ft-plus defender or midfielder was a regular until suffering a
stress fracture in his right ankle. However, despite the pain, he played
on for more than a year until sufficient cover was available.
Aitken's last first-team appearance was against East Fife in August --
he was on the bench for Tuesday night's match against Berwick -- and he
has managed only one reserve game recently because of the weather.
Manager Christie has no qualms about including Aitken, Stenhousemuir's
longest-serving player, in the cup squad.
He said yesterday: ''Neil has had a horrific time with the injury, but
is a very good player, a terrific athlete, and a fearsome sight when in
full flight.''
Aitken, due to graduate Bachelor of Science this summer, said: ''It
has been a bitter pill to swallow, missing out on the excitement.
''I suppose you could call me the 'Unknown Warrior'. It wold be a
tribute to the manager's confidence to be included against Hibs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484848</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* JOE Kinnear's crusade against ''diabolical'' refereeing is supported
by the vast majority of Premier League managers, Wimbledon owner Sam
Hammam claimed yesterday.
However, a worried Hammam admitted: ''Joe may need to be crucified to
eradicate inconsistency among referees.''
Kinnear, already facing an FA inquiry after an incident at Newcastle,
could find himself in deeper trouble after being ''sent off'' at
Selhurst Park on Tuesday. He confronted official Robbie Hart on the
pitch and faces the prospect of another protracted touchline ban.
''We expect a disrepute charge on Joe Kinnear and I have some concern
that he will suffer in one way or another,'' Hammam said.
''We have to look at the positive side of what Joe is trying to
achieve; it's in the long-term interests of football and referees.
''The real problem is not Joe Kinnear, but consistency of refereeing
and the quality of officials.
''I can't remember a manager who hasn't complained, including
highly-respected people like Kenny Dalglish and Joe Royle.''
Kinnear was outraged when Alan Kimble was sent off for failing to
retreat 10 yards from a Manchester United corner -- his second
''bookable'' offence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Galloway transfer deal may still be on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC utility man Mike Galloway could still get the transfer to
Leicester City he wants -- in spite of the hiccup that appeared to have
wrecked the deal yesterday.
Last night, Celtic manager Tommy Burns said: ''The problem arose
because Mark McGhee was in bed with flu over the past couple of days.
Now we are back in touch with him and talking about a permanent move for
the player.''
McGhee, a former Celtic striker and now the Leicester manager, was
back with his relegation-haunted side at Loftus Road last night and
hopes to finalise talks today.
Back at Parkhead, Burns refused to confirm or deny rumours linking the
club with Arsenal's 31-year-old striker Ian Wright. Reports suggested
that Wright would join the Glasgow side in a #2m deal on a
#10,000-a-week salary.
Arsenal denied that any approach had been made, and the salary figure
looks well beyond the reach of Celtic. Their highest-paid player,
captain Paul McStay, earns just half that sum.
* PROMOTION and relegation issues will be involved in the midweek
fixtures after the Scottish League arranged a new programme. The
fixtures are:
Tuesday: Premier division -- Partick Thistle v Motherwell. Division II
-- Dumbarton v Stenhousemuir; Morton v Clyde.
Wednesday: Division III -- East Stirling v Montrose.
* DUNFERMLINE defender Gary Paterson was yesterday transferred to
Stirling Albion for a nominal fee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skye claim tie after call-offs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DAN MACLENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SKYE Camanachd's controversial Glenmorangie Camanachd Cup fourth-round
tie against Oban Camanachd will not now be played on Saturday.
The island side have lodged an appeal claiming the tie following the
postponement of the match on Saturday, the second time in two weeks it
had been called off.
In a letter to Camanachd Association Secretary Alistair MacIntyre
yesterday, Skye accused opponents Oban of ''deliberately or wilfully''
misleading the president, Duncan Cameron, who took the decision to call
off the game last Friday night.
The match had originally been scheduled for a Saturday morning field
inspection. Skye say in their letter they are sure Cameron would not
have posponed the tie ''if he had been in full possession of the
facts.''
The letter then had to be amended when secretary MacIntyre pointed out
that under the Association's rules, Skye would have to claim the tie and
lodge a #50 appeal fee to have the match halted this weekend.
Skye then followed the official's advice and amended their appeal
formally to claim the tie.
</TEXT>
