<HEADLINE>Scot strikes Bolton's winner</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND striker John McGinlay was the toast of Brunton Park last
night when his late winner earned Bolton a 3-1 win on the night -- 4-3
on aggregate -- and a place in the final of the Coca-Cola Cup at Wembley
on April 2.
All had looked lost for the home side when Swindon's Jan Fjortoft
scored 12 minutes into the second half. But a double substitution by
Wanderers' manager Bruce Rioch sparked a fightback.
Four minutes after having sent on former Aberdeen striker Mixu
Paateleinen and Richard Sneekes, Jason McAteer gave the home side a
lifeline by scoring. Then five minutes later Paateleinen netted to leave
extra time on the cards.
But with just two minutes remaining, a mistake by the Swindon defence
left McGinlay to steer the ball home for his sixteenth goal of the
season.
''We showed character to come back like that,'' said McGinlay. ''The
spirit in the team is tremendous and they showed here.''
In the other semi-final, second leg a goal from Robbie Fowler gave
Liverpool a 1-0 success at Crystal Palace, 2-0 on aggregate.
0 Cushioned by Fowler's goal deep into injury time in the first leg,
Liverpool could afford to be patient last night. And they did not have
to wait too long.
Palace looked in vain for an offside flag in 27 minutes as Fowler
peeled off Richard Shaw and raced clear onto McManaman's long ball down
the left.Keeper Nigel Martyn came off his line but Fowler threaded his
low, angled shot into the net.
