<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gearing up for success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Amateur Swimming Association has plugged in to the
Stirling University bursary scheme as a means of further promoting the
sport.
At present there are five swimmers -- Scots Kerry Martin, Pauline
McLean and Forbes Dunlop, plus English pair Susan Colling and Andrew
Lane -- benefiting from a set-up that includes financial assistance and
full-time coaching and back-up facilities.
The aim is to increase the number of swimmers to an annual intake of
eight, and Martyn Woodroffe, Scotland's Director of Swimming, recognises
it as the way ahead.
''It is something that has been talked about for years, and I think it
is an excellent way for our sport to grow,'' he said. ''The SASA have
become involved this year, and we will be doing our best to promote it
all over Britain.''
Next weekend, the Stirling five will get the chance to advertise the
benefits when they compete in the British Universities' championships at
Crystal Palace with the aim of clinching places in the team for the
World Student Games in Japan in August.
The final selection will not be made until after the National
championships at Coventry in July, but posting an early qualifying time
would ease the pressure.
</TEXT>
