<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots let it slip</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HERIOT Watt, the defending champions, surprisingly crashed out of the
British Universities women's championships yesterday when they were
beaten 2-1 by Bristol in a semi-final.
The Scots looked to be cruising in the early part of the match, and
this viewpoint was substantiated in 16 minutes when Val Neil shot them
into a lead.
With Bristol looking overawed by the occasion, Heriot Watt gave the
impression that the battle would be won long before the interval.
Unfortunately for them, their attack failed to capitalise on numerous
openings, while just before the break, Bristol broke through, forced a
corner, and on three occasions forced the Heriot Watt keeper, Katie
Goldsack, into fine saves.
However, with nine minutes remaining, disaster struck for Heriot Watt.
Firstly, their defence was caught flat footed when Jo Corbett broke
through on the right.
The Scots' rear-guard not only failed to cut out her cross but then to
dispossess Polly Harrison in front of goal. This strike brought about
another tremendous rally from Heriot Watt, but their prospects of
forcing the equaliser disappeared when winger Susan Gilmour was given a
temporary suspension three minutes from time.
</TEXT>
