<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Estates 'under threat'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484857</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN legislation, depicted as the theft of landowners' property
rights, could lead to an increasing number of private estates being sold
to charities and conservation bodies, it was claimed yesterday.
Michael Wigan, owner of Borrobol estate in Sutherland, warned,
however, that ''green'' tourism would not provide the number of jobs
supported by the present system of ownership.
''There will be fewer hotels and keepers, ghillies and dog handlers,''
he told a Scottish Landowners' Federation conference at Battleby, near
Perth. A lot of colour would go out of the countryside and there would
be less money in local economies. He also feared that any jobs created
would not go to existing local people.
''The whole image of the landowner is already being changed by the
erosion of property rights and the accretion of a wide range of
responsibilities,'' he told his audience. ''Estate ownership is becoming
less desirable and that is one reason why so many estates are up for
sale.'' Private individuals did not wish to become responsible at every
turn to the apparatchiks of the regulating agencies, he said.
With the threat of designation under the various conservation
regulations hanging over capital values like the sword of Damocles, an
increasing number of estates would be bought by the ''financialy
favoured'' such as charities which were outside the tax net, he
forecast.
Mr Wigan complained that the new European Union habitats directive was
shrouded in secrecy but could have serious implications for Scottish
landowners. ''What is more alarming is that we have been told by the
Scottish Office not to be alarmed.''
Farmers had already had to face up to restrictions and changes in
agricultural practices demanded by Scottish Natural Heritage, he said.
For the future he feared more compulsion and less compensation for
activities given up by the farmer or landowner.
The concept of Sites of Special Scientific Interest had got off to a
bad start in the North of Scotland, he said. ''Designation has become a
form of penalty. Those favoured by where they live have become the
victims.'' Crofters and farmers might fail to spot an erosion of quality
because it happened so gradually. ''Along comes a strutting official
waving scientific papers and saying: 'Look sharp you fools, this needs
protection'. It may only be because of tradtional land use that there is
anything to designate in the first place.''
In Caithness, he said SNH officials were perceived as ''non-native,
university-bred, theoretical land experts who had never got their hands
dirty''. In addition, each one tended to have a particular specialism
which did not relate to land management as a whole.
''The latest boobytrap for those who have waited 35 years for a forest
to mature is a ban by Highland Region on the weight of vehicles which
can use small roads -- making it uneconomic to remove the timber.''
The chairman of Scottish Natural Heritage, Magnus Magnusson, who was
the next speaker at the conference, suggested Mr Wigan had been
''perhaps a teensy bit partisan''.
There was an alarming and frustrating number of myths and
misconceptions about statutory SNH designations, he said. The fact was
that designations worked entirely on the voluntary principle. With
SSSI's, for example, notification that a site was regarded as of special
scientific interest made no difference to the management regime unless
the owner agreed. There was an ultimate deterrent of compulsory purchase
by the Secretary of State for Scotland but that had never been resorted
to.
There were now more than 1300 SSSI's in Scotland and these would
provide the building blocks for UK site protection under European and
international obligations. The ultimate aim of the two European
directives -- the European Wild Birds Directive and the Habitats
Directive -- was to establish a network of sites to protect Europe's
most valuable habitats and species.
Mr Magnusson said that under the European provisions the regime would
be ''tougher'' because of the Government's obligation to conform to the
EU directive. SNH had no intention, however, of using its powers
arbitrarily or frivolously. Despite what had been said, there was no
evidence whatsoever that capital values were reduced by SSSI
designation, he claimed. There was some clear indication that the
reverse was true. There was a premium to be achieved from owning land in
good health and good heart.
''Is it really sensible to value land just on how many stags there are
to be shot or on how many salmon are to be caught, or how many grouse
can be killed in a day?'' he asked. ''Is there not a case for thinking
that the natural heritage of land should be valued as a whole resource
rather than just those specific exploitable aspects of it which, in
themselves, are often vulnerable to outside activities and events beyond
the owners' control?''
The SNH was currently entering into positive management agreements
with site-owners covering nearly 120,000 hectares at a cost of more than
#4m a year, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hide 'back to spiteful best'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484858</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HERBIE Hide's mentor has been burning the midnight oil, keeping his
diary up to date. The WBO champion's trainer, Freddie King, carefully
notes down his man's progress in the build-up to Saturday's defence
against Riddick Bowe at the MGM Grand Garden, Las Vegas.
Whenever Hide has looked particularly mean, King has picked up his pen
later that evening and recorded the fact on the appropriate date.
And ''Herbie is back to his spiteful best'' is a prominent sentence in
King's personal log. He said: ''Believe me, Herbie is an absolute
gentleman outside the ring.
''But inside it he's a nasty, horrible person. He is an animal between
those ropes. And that's the way he's got to be.
''Once we've activated our plan, there can only be one winner. He'll
come out fighting to keep his title. Okay, Bowe is powerful but, if he
can't hit Herbie, he can't hurt him.
''And Riddick will never be hit as Herbie will do on Saturday. Bowe is
nowhere near as fast either. The preparation and build-up is what's
going to win this fight, that's the way I see it.
''Bowe probably rates as the best heavyweight in the world at the
moment. But, if you look back to his 1988 Olympic final against Lennox
Lewis in Seoul, he turned away and didn't want to know.
''I believe a leopard doesn't change his spots. No one has hit him so
hard since, and Herbie will be the next one to hit him as hard.''
However, that is not the way the bookies see it. Casinos along the
glitzy Strip in the gambling capital of America make Bowe 6-1 ON to move
back into the world title picture, while Hide is a 9-2 shot.
</TEXT>
