<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Liz is out to put the men in their place</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MISOGYNISTS everywhere, read this and tremble. Having been neutered by
newspapers yesterday on International Women's Day, you probably thought
the eulogies on the monstrous regiment were over. But no. Today we give
you yet another female capable of doing men's work -- athlete Liz
McColgan.
But the blunt truth is that, like the fighter pilot who has outgunned
men to climb into the cockpit, Liz is also up to the job.
Her club, Dundee Hawkhill, is to enter her in the national six-stage
road relay a week on Sunday at Kirkintilloch.
The race is normally for men only, but, ''Females may be entered,
subject to scrutiny, as this is predominantly a men's event,'' states
the entry form.
The format of the race, for which entries close on Saturday, is three
laps of six miles and three of three miles.
''I expect to run one of the longer stages,'' says the former world
10,000 metres track champion. ''It will be my final warm-up before the
London Marathon on April 2. I'm also racing a half marathon this weekend
in Portugal.''
* JOHN Regis, whose participation at the world indoor championships
seemed in jeopardy following a thigh injury, will travel to Barcelona
today.
Regis, who strained some fibres a week past Monday while racing in
Stockholm, hopes to contest the 200m, confirmed team spokesman Tony Ward
yesterday. ''The injury has responded well to treatment,'' he said.
The news is a welcome boost to a team depleted by the absence of most
of leading performers, but it is asking a lot for Regis to survive three
rounds on the bends of the Palau St Jordi arena.
The IAAF president, Primo Nebiolo, yesterday said he would make a
personal appeal to Linford Christie -- who has declined to run the 60m:
''If I see him.'' Christie is due in Spain to support the team, though
Britain has already named Mike Rosswess as replacement. Noureddine
Morceli succumbed to similar appeal at the 1993 outdoor world
championships, fuelling speculation that the IAAF paid him.
* UK athletics chiefs this week bemoaned the lack of a 60,000-capacity
stadium which prevents Britain hosting world or European track
championships. But one world athletics event is being staged in Britain
this year -- on Arthur's Seat, Edinburgh.
And yesterday Jim Darby, the Scotland team manager for the World
Mountain Racing Championships, launched an appeal for help. ''I want 50
pipers -- one every 200 metres around the course -- playing something
stirring to set Scottish hearts on fire, and frighten the Italians.''
The event still needs a major sponsor, so Darby can promise no money:
''Just the pride of Scotland -- it could be worth 30 seconds a runner to
our teams.''
If your pibroch is at Scotland's disposal, dial Darby on 0620 893165.
* SOME pointed questions are inevitable on Saturday at the Scottish
Athletic Federation's annual meeting in Edinburgh's Grosvenor Hotel
(1.0pm). It will be the first opportunity for clubs to query more than
#50,000 squandered in the past year.
Officers of the former women's cross-country and road running body
will be smug about having salted #10,000 in a trust. Despite the best
legal efforts of the federation, the money remains locked away, and so
escaped fiscal armageddon.
But some clubs wonder whether it is appropriate for Eleanor Gunstone,
one of the trustees responsible for denying this money to the sport, to
be standing for the post of convenor of SAF's road-running and
cross-country commission.
* MORE than 2000 athletes from 171 schools will line up in eight races
at the TSB Scottish Schools Cross-country championships on Irvine's
Beach Park on Saturday -- the country's biggest athletics meeting of the
winter.
Emma Gorman, defending over-17 girls' champion, will be up against it,
having raced in Britain's world championship trials last weekend, and
may find the challenge of Kristina Gormley too strong.
International track stars Andrew Young and Ally Donaldson are among
the favourites for the over-17 boys' title, but Kevin McAlpine has won
at each of the three other age groups, and has the incentive of making
history if he wins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Torrance reigns on royal links</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484860</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAM Torrance and Barry Lane, playing superbly together, led the charge
as Europe beat Africa 4-0 yesterday in the Sahara Cup over the Royal
Golf Links at Agadir in Morocco.
Lane shot five birdies and Torrance two to beat Tony Johnstone of
Zimbabwe and South African Retief Goosen by 65 to 69 in the opening
match of this better-ball medal contest played on the eve of the
Moroccan Open on King Hassan's private course.
David Gilford and Italian Costantino Rocca beat South African Gavin
Levenson and Moroccan Mohamed Makroune 65-67, Howard Clark and Peter
Mitchell dismissed Wayne Westner and Jeff Hawkes of South Africa 66-70,
and Swedish duo Per-Ulrik Johansson and Anders Forsbrand beat South
Africans John Bland and Ian Palmer 65-68.
European captain Torrance was delighted. ''This is the second time
I've captained Europe and we've won both times,'' he said. ''The
previous time was in the Four Tours championship in Adelaide in 1991.''
The 41-year-old Scot selected the European pairings and said his only
doubt was whether he should play with Clark -- with whom he has enjoyed
success in the Ryder Cup -- or Lane, but he decided to put Clark with
Mitchell, who had never played in this type of event before.
Londoner Mitchell said he was ''very nervous,'' but still shot five
birdies while Clark had only two.
Gilford, who has twice won the Moroccan Open, clearly likes the
course, which is one of the best on the PGA European Tour. ''It's pretty
tight in places,'' he said, ''but you must not be afraid of it.''
Forsbrand, winner of the Moroccan Open last year, and Johansson both
played well, and African captain Johnstone, asked to comment on the
score, said: ''It's never exciting when you are whitewashed. I could sum
it up in one word -- ouch!''
Torrance is joined by 12 others Scots in today's field -- Gordon Brand
Jr, Brian Barnes, Bernard Gallacher, Brian Marchbank, Gary Orr, Andrew
Coltart, Adam Hunter, Ross Drummond, Mike Miller, Stephen McAllister,
Craig Ronald, and Dean Robertson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBINSON HOLLOWAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484861</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* IAN Woosnam came to Florida, to the Honda Classic here in Fort
Lauderdale -- his first golf tournament of the year -- to bring his game
back into shape.
Thus far, the 27 holes he has played in practice have made him only
hopeful, and he was unable to use the practice facilities yesterday
afternoon when a fierce wind storm descended, cancelling the rest of the
pro-am and tossing all of the tents and corporate sky boxes around the
course.
Woosnam will play five straight weeks in America, though he admitted
that his expectations are low. He last played in December at the Johnnie
Walker in Jamaica, and in the interval spent two months ''doing not a
great deal, not touching a club.''
In discussing his chances for the Masters this year, or the other
majors, Woosnam laughed and replied: ''It took me 29 or 30 years to get
one major, it'll probably take me another 30 years to get another.''
</TEXT>
