<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hats off to Jazz</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH BRUCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
With the Glasgow festival programme just completed Keith Bruce
savours the prospect
We are trying to make the festival more accessible. Too much jazz has
a mystique about it. You don't have to understand what the tenor
saxophonist is doing -- if you're enjoying it, that's enough
I MADE no promises about consuming millinery if this year's Glasgow
International Jazz Festival was anything more than disappointing, but I
did hint at concerns about what new director Derek Gorman had in mind.
Not that Gorman, a chap who was brought into the organisation as much
for his business and marketing background as his enthusiasm for the
music, is likely to take his eye off the bottom line.
He inherited a #90,000 deficit and has set himself three years to wipe
it out, but that doesn't mean he and his team have put together a dull
and conservative festival -- just a very varied one.
''This is the best job I've ever had,'' he beams. ''But I'm conscious
of the responsibility to the music and to the city. It's not like simply
putting on a gig. We've had eight years of terrific festivals and there
is a lot of public money involved.''
So what are the sponsors and funders (particularly Glasgow City
Council with its #140,000 investment) going to see for their money this
year? A great deal of music if they have the legs and ears for it.
The only use of the Royal Concert Hall is for a rare jazz set by Andre
Previn in the company of bassist Ray Brown and guitarist Mundell Lowe.
Gorman hopes that the hall's classical concert-going clientele will be
so intrigued to see the other side of the man's musical character that
they will be fighting the jazz aficionados for tickets.
Along the road at the Theatre Royal, the festival returns to its
original home for popular concerts with shows by singer Carol Kidd on
the opening Friday and veteran violinist Stephane Grappelli the
following night.
The closing concert a week later reunites, for the first time in a
decade or so, legendary Glasgow trad-jazz band The Clyde Valley
Stompers, with players reassembling from as far afield as Switzerland
and Canada.
Fans of that sort of good-time music will also be booking for the
Dutch Swing College Band and/or the jump jive of King Pleasure and the
Biscuit Boys, who both have gigs at the Marriot Hotel, where there will
also be a club every night, with Fionna Duncan fronting the resident
band.
By now there will be a few readers grinding their teeth and muttering
into their breakfast pints of real ale about the lack of any
challenging, modern music. To which Gorman might wish to say: you are
part of the problem, not the solution, just as the folk who won't
venture out for an unfamiliar name are missing out.
''We are trying to make the festival more accessible. Too much jazz
has a mystique about it. You don't have to understand what the tenor
saxophonist is doing -- if you're enjoying it, that's enough. There has
been a perception problem with the Glasgow International Jazz Festival,
not a programming one -- John McLaughlin plays great, swinging jazz
guitar.''
And indeed, McLaughlin will be back with a trio as part of an Old
Fruitmarket programme that has been designed to dovetail with the one at
the City Cafe bar in the City Hall. There should be enough there to
please the chaps in the (usually imaginary) goatees and berets.
Here's a taster: Paul Motian's Broadway Music with saxophonist Lee
Konitz; a tribute to Charlie Parker by the Pete King quintet (including
trumpeter Gerard Presencer) with two very special guests, one of them a
renowned US saxophonist; the Jazz Crusaders, now back to using their
full name after their flirtation with pop; and a veritable feast of
trumpeters -- Cuban Arturo Sandoval, South African Hugh Masekela, young
American Roy Hargrove, England's Guy Barker and Scotland's Bruce Adams.
Adams is part of an all-star Scottish band that includes the
festival's two saxophone-wielding musicians-in-residence, Bobby Wellins
and Joe Temperley and guitarist Jim Mullen. Wellins is writing a
commissioned piece for the band and Strathclyde Youth Jazz Orchestra and
Gorman is keen to ''promote the Scottishness of the festival and the
contribution Scottish musicians have made to jazz.''
The first weekend encompasses a youth jazz day on the Saturday (July
1) and Scottish Jazzworks, a showcase for indigenous talent at the
Ramshorn Theatre. The following weekend drummer Tom Bancroft and his
chums once again get the run of the place, this time calling in European
musicians to add to the pandemonium.
Gorman acknowledges that there is a fine line between patronising
people and telling them things they might not already know -- but that's
what he's aiming at with this year's publicity material, including a
jazz festival tabloid which will be distributed with The Herald at the
end of March when tickets go on sale.
Inevitably, however, and despite incentives, like weekend tickets and
venue passes, music fans will make their first investment in the type of
sound they know that they want to hear. Gorman is sure that if they're
wearing ears they won't be disappointed: ''If you like good music we
challenge you not to find something you like.''
</TEXT>
