<HEADLINE>Women's open 'will go ahead'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484863</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the euphoric aftermath of the #3m three-year sponsorship of the
women's European Tour by American Express announced this week, the
tour's chief executive, Terry Coates, declared: ''The Scottish Open will
not be allowed to go to the wall.''
Coates added: ''We have already assured BBC TV Scotland (who broadcast
live transmissions last summer) that the tournament will go ahead at
Dalmahoy in August. We are talking to various parties and are
optimistic.''
0 If necessary,some of this week's windfall could be used to keep the
Scottish championship alive.
The #150,000 tournament, which Laura Davies is due to defend from
August 3 to 6, lost its title sponsor, Skoda, after only one association
when the Czech Republic car manufacturer was taken over by Volkswagen.
''Under its new mangement the marketing direction was changed,''
Coates explained. ''But the joint organisers of the tournament, Carnegie
Management and Parallel Media Group, are out there, working together.''
Scottish commerce's notorious reluctance to back sporting events in its
own backyard may yet be overcome.
