<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Careful McRae lying fourth in Portugal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN HORTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484864</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN the TAP Rallye De Portugal reached last night's rest halt in
Povoa De Varzim, Colin McRae, driving a Subaru Impreza, was in fourth
place, 1min 11sec behind his team-mate and rally leader, Carlos Sainz
from Spain.
After having retired from the first two rounds of this year's world
rally championship, 26-year-old McRae, from Lanark, and co-driver Derek
Ringer, from Glasgow, made a careful start, recording sixth fastest time
on the first of the scheduled 31 timed special stages.
They moved up into fourth place by the end of the third stage, gaining
one place when the British-built Ford Escort of Francois Delecour hit
trouble.
Delecour overturned his car when he tried to save a few seconds by
cutting a tight corner. ''I cut a slow corner and touched some big rocks
on the inside,'' said the Frenchman. He continued minus a windscreen and
power steering and his misery ended in stage five when his car stopped
with oil pressure failure.
Over the first six damp and muddy dirt road stages, last year's
winners Juha Kankkunen, from Finland, navigated by Welshman Nicky Grist,
were uncatchable in their Toyota Celica and moved into a 13-second lead
over Sainz. After the icy tarmac of January's Monte Carlo rally and last
month's snowbound Swedish rally, Kankkunen, four times world champion,
said: ''It is a nice change to feel some earth under our wheels.''
On more familiar stages around Fafe, the most northerly point of the
event near the Spanish border, Sainz attacked and snatched the lead on
the eleventh and final stage before the overnight halt.
In third place is the Toyota of reigning world champion Didier Auriol.
The third Impreza from Subaru, crewed by Richard Burns, from Reading,
and Robert Reid, from Perth, restarts today's second leg in eighth
place. Today's leg includes 10 timed special stages and 150km of
competitive driving.
The 1700km rally finishes in the Atlantic resort of Figueira Da Foz
tomorrow evening. Interim results after 11 of 31 special stages:
1, C Sainz/L Moya (Subaru Impreza) 2hr 07min 51sec; 2, J Kankkunen/N
Grist (Toyota Celica) 2-07.57; 3, D Auriol/B Occelli (Toyota Celica)
2-08.35; 4, C McRae/D Ringer (Subaru Impreza) 2-09.02; 5, A Schwarz/K
Wicha (Toyota Celica) 2-10.5; 6, B Thiry/S Prevot (Ford Escort) 2-11.35.
</TEXT>
