<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nicol finds fellow Scot tougher than expected</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484865</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Nicol survived a closer than expected encounter against fellow
Scot Martin Heath to claim his place in today's quarter-finals of the
Andersen Portuguese Open in Lisbon.
The No.4 seed now meets Australia's world No.9 Anthony Hill, with a
match against world No.1 and defending champion, Jansher Khan, the
likely reward for the winner.
Nicol, 21, went into the match against Heath as odds-on favourite,
having won the Scottish Championship final easily in December.
He did win in straight games, but Heath, ranked 33 places lower, had
his chances to cause an upset before going out 15-13, 17-15, 15-8 in
just under an hour.
The second game was crucial. Heath, who has never beaten his fellow
countryman as a senior, led 9-7 and 10-9 then fought back from 14-11
behind to level the scores and force Nicol to three set points.
However, on the fourth game ball the more experienced player clinched
the marathon 26-minute game by 17-15 and Heath's chances of a famous
victory had really disappeared.
While the 21-year-old from Oban could be happy with a performance that
proved he could soon join Nichol in the upper echelons of the world
rankings, the victor was less than overjoyed.
''I wasn't too pleased with the way I played,'' said London-based
Nicol who, worryingly, has recently suffered a lengthy bout of
tonsillitis for the second time in a year.
He insists he is fully fit, but that may just be a cover.
Today's encounter against Hill could be billed as the battle of the
crocks.
The Australian was a straightforward 15-17, 17-16, 15-3 winner over
England's Paul Johnson, but he readily admitted to feeling sickly and
even went as far as paying a visit to a local doctor.
For Nicol, there are only happy memories of their one previous
meeting, in the 1993 Singapore Open final when the Scot won to record
his first major success.
Results:
Jansher Khan (Pakistan) beat Paul Steel (New Zealand) 15-5, 15-11,
15-6; Peter Nicol (Scotland) beat Martin Heath (Scotland) 15-13, 17-15,
15-8; Anthony Hill (Australia) beat Paul Johnson (England) 15-7, 17-16,
15-3; Rodney Eyles (Australia) beat Danny Meddings (England) 15-9,
17-16, 13-15, 15-9.
</TEXT>
