<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Weir to defend crown at home</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484866</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAUL Weir, Scotland's two-time world champion, will defend his World
Boxing Organisation light-flyweight title in his home town of Irvine on
Wednesday, April 5, against Renato ''Ric'' Magramo of the Philippines.
Amazingly, it will be the little Scot's fifth world title contest in
10 fights as a professional, having previously held the straw-weight
crown. He gave that up and won the vacant light-fly title in Irvine last
November by outpointing South Africa's Paul Oulden.
And yesterday, 27-year-old Weir expressed his delight at making his
first defence at the Magnum. ''I have made no secret of the fact that I
want to fight in Scotland all the time, and to do so in my home town is
a bit special.''
His manager, Tommy Gilmour, who will promote the show, said: ''This
was Paul's decision alone. I am as patriotic as anyone, but I would have
been happy to take the huge offer which was on the table for Paul to
fight in South Africa.
''After all, it's my job to get the best deal I can for my boxers.
Paul, however, is taking half the cash he could have earned elsewhere
just to fight in Scotland.''
The champion added: ''I've won my two world titles in Scotland, and
before I call it a day I would like to win the flyweight crown here as
well.
''Why should I go away when I'm happy here and happy with the money?
What's the point of facing the heat, humidity, and hostility when I can
enjoy myself here?
''Don't get me wrong,;we're all in this game to make as much money as
possible, but if I can make it easier for myself by getting fights at
home then that's what I'll do.
''That way I'll live to fight another day and keep myself on course
for my target of winning three world titles, making a fair bit of money
and retiring before I am 30.''
Certainly, Weir will be a big favourite to beat the 31-year-old
Magramo, who, in his last contest, won the Philippines championship.
The man from Manila has only just come into the top 10 rankings and,
although a tough little fighter, has had 12 losses and three draws in
his 42 professional contests.
The name may sound familiar to the older generation of boxing fans in
this country. Perhaps they may remember Magramo's father, Ric, being
outpointed by former world flyweight champion Walter McGowan at Paisley
Ice Rink in November, 1963.
Willie ''The Mighty'' Quinn, the middleweight from Tranent, will
feature in the main supporting bout at Irvine against a selected
opponent, and Gilmour said:
''Willie has all but served his apprenticeship and should shortly be
fighting for some kind of championship.''
Others Scots on the bill will be Ian McLeod (Kilmarnock), Hugh Collins
(Stirling), Mark Breslin (Barrhead), and Joe Townsley (Cleland). And
there should be an explosive battle at flyweight when unbeaten Keith
Knox, of Bonnyrigg, goes in against Anglo-Scot Louis Veitch, the Central
Area champion.
Top price for the show is #40 with the other tickets priced at #30 and
#20.
* SACRAMENTO has been chosen as the venue for Lennox Lewis's final
eliminator for the WBC heavyweight championship against American Lionel
Butler on May 13.
It was one of four cities in the running for the fight, the Briton's
first since he lost the WBC title to American Oliver McCall at Wembley
last September.
Dublin, Reno, and Las Vegas were also in contention, but the
15,000-seater Arco Arena -- home of the Sacramento Kings NBA basketball
team -- came up with the best offer.
</TEXT>
