<HEADLINE>REM cancel Glasgow date</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484867</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL European indoor dates for R E M's current world tour, including
the two due to have taken place on April 16 and 17 at Glasgow's SECC,
have been cancelled following the brain haemorrhage sustained on-stage
in Switzerland last week by their drummer, Bill Berry.
However, all their European outdoor dates, due to take place later in
the summer, will go ahead as planned.
From Monday, SECC ticket-holders will therefore have two choices. They
can either claim a refund, or pay a small additional amount in order to
exchange their tickets, originally priced at #19 and #21, for #23
tickets for R E M's outdoor Scottish show, scheduled for July 27 at
Murrayfield Stadium.
Having undergone successful surgery to clip a ruptured aneurysm on the
outer surface of his brain, Bill Berry has been making a steady
recovery. Swiss doctors are confident that he should be discharged from
hospital within eight to 10 days.
</TEXT>
