<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sex and the moralising, modern Pharisees</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>BOOK REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484868</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IWAS thinking about sex the other day. We in the Tory Party think of
practically nothing else, as you must have gathered by now, and spring
has also sprung in the SNP. Mr Robert Hughes has an affair and resigns
from the Government; Ms Roseanna Cunningham has one yonks ago and has
had to withstand the wrath of the wicked Winnie of the North.
How obsessed we are becoming by the necessity to prove our politicians
are whiter than the driven snow. Selection committees will soon be
employing private detectives to check on the background of the
candidates.
Are there skeletons rattling in your cupboard, Councillor? Bones and
bones of them, my dears, but you would not wrench them from my lips
without applying the burning coals. Why don't you mind your own
business? But it is our business to know whether public figures can be
trusted because if they cheat in their marriages they might do the same
in their task of representing us. Yes, they might but there is little
evidence to suggest such is likely to be the case.
Cecil Parkinson and David Mellor were rather effective ministers as I
recall. Prime Ministers Wellington, Palmerston, and Lloyd George would
not have passed the fidelity exam, Presidents FDR and JFK would have
failed it miserably.
Yet the modern Pharisees, who set standards they rarely live by
themselves, continue to demand their sacrificial lambs. A new book,
published this week, hurries to their cause.
Dr Patrick Dixon, a 37-year-old happy husband, the father of four
children, is the author of the tome in which he thunders: ''We worship
two things in life -- sex and cash.'' Sexual promiscuity, he insists, is
the cause of all society's ills, it is simply too expensive to tolerate.
Why, three out of four married men who have affairs will be divorced by
their wives. (What is the figure for the other way round, I wonder?)
It all stems from the swinging sixties, folks, although some of us who
were around at the time don't remember them being quite so explicit or
exciting. Dr Dixon, however, can even put a price on our affairs; they
have cost the nation ''#124 billion over the past 40 years''.
Ecky thump -- that's a bit of a choker. How does this non-money
worshipping moralist calculate this sum? His bill includes the lost
earnings of the 1500 people who die each year from Aids, all screening
and treatment for cervical cancer, the approximate cost of second homes,
half the annual bill for children in care, 175,000 divorces per year and
the cost of benefits and loss of earnings of single mothers.
Hang on there, Doc, there seems to me to be a few flaws in your
diagnosis. You don't actually have to be promiscuous to catch Aids, not
all cervical cancer sufferers have slept around, the sole cause of
divorce is not a bit on the side.
There are women, even as you read, who are enduring domestic violence
on a horrific scale. There are families whose lives are being torn to
bits by drink or drugs. There are children who are being regularly
abused. The message to them cannot be to shut up and stay put.
Separation does hurt children; listening to rowing parents night after
night damages them a lot more.
Dr Dixon and his wife waited until they were married before they had
sex. Good for them. They waited several years to have children.
Wonderful. He might have waited a bit longer, gathered a little more
experience of married life before pontificating.
For Dr Dixon is of the ''all we need to do'' school of moralising. All
we have to do is stay in our own beds and evils like crime and
unemployment will vanish into the air. Oh, and I am pretty sure he
believes Mum should always be the one who stays at home with the kids,
too.
Forgive me if I decline to swallow the sugared pill. I was divorced;
the main fault for the breakdown of the marriage was certainly mine.
Yet, while I sincerely regret the hurt that was caused, I am not at all
sorry that the split was made and I do not believe it would have helped
a single member of my family if we had stayed in the unhappy alliance.
If we wish to ease the strains on family life we should look very
carefully at the stresses we pile upon the institution of marriage. Our
work rate for a start.
Politicians are the worst sinners -- who would willingly opt for the
sort of hours they choose to endure? We should also look at ways in
which young women, and mothers, can pursue their careers without feeling
guilty.
We might consider not so much a minimum wage but a maximum shift. If
lorry drivers and airline pilots are restricted in the time they are
allowed to be on duty, do the rest of us not deserve the same
consideration? To be fair to Dr Dixon he has some ideas, higher child
benefit, increased ''wedding anniversary'' tax allowances, though,
surprisingly, he does not tell us how much they will cost. But even
those will hardly banish infidelity.
There should be fiscal advantages in being married rather than simply
living together. In encouraging people to be wed, however, we should
never condemn them to a life of misery when the relationship goes wrong.
There is a price to be paid for that, too.
* The Rising Price of Love by Dr Patrick Dixon is published by Hodder
and Stoughton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Roy Williams and the Ronnie Rae Trio, Moir Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484869</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF there wasn't a good deal of back patting going on after the
inaugural concert of the Jazz Co-op, then there certainly should have
been. This new organisation made a triumph out of what could have been a
disaster.
The scheduled headliner for this crucial gig (for which members of the
Co-op had put up the cash) was saxophonist Scott Hamilton, but he pulled
out at the eleventh hour because of illness. Rather than cancel the
event, the Co-op took a risk and co-opted British trombonist Roy
Williams into playing as substitute.
The risk paid off. And probably with dividends. Not only did the
packed Moir Hall (no-one left when on discovering the programme change)
get one of the world's top trombone men, but everyone there will get a
discount on their ticket for Hamilton's rescheduled gig, on April 25.
Appropriately enough, the Co-op was launched to the tune of A
Beautiful Friendship; the first of a selection which balanced the
oft-heard with the seldom-played. In the latter bracket was Up With the
Lark -- a delightful Jerome Kern waltz which, Williams informed us, has
only been recorded twice, by Stan Getz and Joyce Grenfell.
Richard Rodgers' most sublime composition, My Romance, was --
unusually -- delivered almost defiantly; Williams clearly au fait with
the emphatic nature of the lyrics. The sentiments of That's All --
suitor stating his case -- similarly shone through. This was the kind of
smoochy number for which you save the last dance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484870</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUCH research as there is, and it isn't much, indicates that the
majority of computer users are middle-class white men with college
degrees. Approach the Internet, though, and the first thing you notice
is that expensively-educated twenty-first century boy can't spell, can't
punctuate, and thinks syntax is what you pay for downloaded porn.
Sometimes language within this parallel universe is so nearly private
as to be incomprehensible. Symbols and acronyms swirl in a mist of teen
slang and college argot. Neologisms -- ''spamming'', ''flaming'',
''newbies'' -- evolve and die like single-cell organisms. Serious
discourse jostles with dumb gossip. For the beginner the problem, ironic
amid a communications revolution, is understanding a word.
None of it amounts to a linguistic shift -- ignorance presages few
revolutions -- but as an example of global English the Net is
depressing.
The digital revolution tends to inspire excitement or fear. For those
who have just found the biggest toy in the world, the freedom of the Net
is the model for a new kind of democracy. For others, there is only
apocalypse, the end of books, of literate culture, and of real human
intercourse.
Both schools are wrong, but neither completely so. Missionaries for
the Net, eager as early Christians for electronic miracles, face the
obvious problem that computers haven't abolished reality. On-line
liberty, with its absolute freedoms of speech, thought, and (virtual)
assembly, makes nothing happen. Crime and poverty continue, whatever
pretty pictures form on your screen.
The prophets of doom are equally determined to understand only one
message. Arguments in the US (among those still capable of conducting
one) have reached the point where mass literacy has been given up as a
lost cause and ''oral development'' is the issue. The worry is not
whether children will learn to read but whether they will learn to
speak.
Blame the screen, say the terrified. It's not the garbage that pours
from a TV that matters most, though it matters, but that a child
passively consuming television is not talking to parents or peers. The
same is true of computers, perhaps more so, what with their addictive
games, their mute obedience, and their enforced solitude. Speech is the
foundation on which literacy is built. Speechless, the young think only
in images.
Newspapers, obsessed with making reading easier, with making articles
short and pictures big, don't help. In all this, needless to say, books
are an elite joke.
But hold on. One simple truth about the information revolution is the
extent to which it depends on text. You can't use the Net unless you can
read and write, however ineptly. After the telephone age, e-mail is
rehabilitating the simple letter, albeit digitised, as a form of mass
communication.
Similarly, entire books are already on line. True, you can't access
them like paperbacks, nor stuff them in your pocket for a day at the
beach, but that is, technologically speaking, a minor obstacle. The
nature of narrative will change -- ''interactive''' being the gruesome,
operative word -- but narrative, central to all communication, will
persist.
The parallel fear that newspapers will cease to be is another fantasy.
Some, like the Daily Telegraph, are on-line now, while extracts from
this paper appear in one of CompuServe's many ''forums''. People will
use papers differently, but news and comment will remain assets for
service providers. Reading is being encouraged, not discouraged.
Computers are likely to abolish paper rather than words, or at least
change the relationship between them, but it's not clear if that's a
tragedy.
Think of the obvious: a CD-ROM can store an encyclopaedia. The art of
book-binding may die, words will not. Software exists which will, even
while you sleep, ''customise'' a private newspaper from nominated
sources, pull together text and photographs, and print the lot in a
package shorn of advertising.
Yet if the medium is truly the message, what is it saying? First, that
our relationship with text is changing faster than at any time since
Gutenberg. Secondly, that digital technology, left to itself, will split
society in two.
Computers cost money; getting on line costs more. If information is
power the poor are impotent. The information-rich are acquiring more
wealth, digital and literal, while the poor, unable to use or afford
shiny laptops, become more impoverished, intellectually and materially.
New Age netsurfers, preaching of empowered masses, hate such talk,
just as those proclaiming the death of the book forget that literature
has coped since the epic of Gilgamesh was a hand-chiselled Babylonian
best-seller. The point is that the ability to defeat poverty by picking
up a book and starting to read will soon be a thing of the past.
Call it the information trap. If anyone wants to worry about the
underclass, this is the place to start.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Who is Eddie Linden? Old Red Lion, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROLE WODDIS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484871</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
0''I'm just a wee Scottish Catholic homosexual,'' he replied. Eddie
Linden -- for those who don't know -- is the founder and creator of one
of the UK's most influential poetry magazines, Aquarius.
A hob nobber with London's great and good and a legend in his own
lifetime. Fostered out, barely literate, the illegitimate offspring of
an Irish mother who moved to Glasgow, he has yet managed to create a
niche for himself through his abiding love of words and language.
Clearly respected and admired as an editor and publisher on a
shoestring, Axel Pedersen's seedy bedsit would seem to suggest that,
despite his literary fame, potential destitution is but a stone's throw
away.
William Tanner's intriguing play (based on a book by Sebastian Barker)
comes therefore as a kind of object lesson and celebration of the
humanising power of art. It is also, however, a cautionary tale for
Tanner introduces a Pinteresque young intruder -- Stuart (played with
seductive charm by Dallas Campbell), a gay, literary scavenger in every
sense, a contrast in generational, sexual, and artistic attitudes to
Eddie. Where ex-public schoolboy Stuart is brashly confident, working
class Eddie is diffident and inhibited, an unashamed romantic still.
As Eddie, Michael Deacon is a touching, if somewhat overblown innocent
(misleadingly so if the slight, dapper real live Eddie in the bar is
anything to go by) but memorable enough as this self-styled ''liberal
socialist'' who at 60 continues to ply his own distinctive, gently
rebellious furrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ellen van Schuylenburch/Desiree Delauney, The Tramway,Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484872</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW Moves Across Europe continues to impress. The latest double-bill
featured two strongly individual women whose solos were a celebration of
dynamic technique, creative curiosity and personal integrity.
Silence is a rhythm too is a product of intense, trusting
collaboration between Ellen van Schuylenburch, Indian dance-maker,
Daksha Sheth and musician Shrikanth Sriram.
Van Schuylenburch is, to begin with, a thrilling performer. As the
music booms and resonates, her lithe, disciplined limbs carve out
sculptural shapes that hint at points of origin. Fiercely beautiful,
compelling stuff.
Alcool -- choreographed and performed by Desiree Delauney -- was
compelling but ferociously unsettling.
Clothed or naked, Delauney radiates a kind of visionary fervour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Starched Aprons at RSAMD, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484873</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN Ena Lamont Stewart's hospital drama was first performed by
Glasgow Unity Theatre in 1945 the setting was contemporaneous, but in a
later re-write Stewart rooted the action in the twenties. This version
by second-year BA students is a composite of both scripts and is located
in the forties, in a ''non-wartime period'' which, considering the
references to the Gestapo and lipstick shortages, must be post-war
Glasgow.
The liberation of women which the war facilitated is stifled on the
wards of Rutherston General Hospital, where the concept of career women
owes more to Florence Nightingale martyrdom, with Sister Barton stalking
the polished corridors proclaiming she is wedded to her vocation and
inspiring a reign of terror.
Out of earshot the nurses are not such a cowed bunch, with amusing
exchanges between the girls whose burning vocation seems to be to
grab-a-guy. This spawns much comedic interludes and romantic intrigues
which the cast make much of, with some sturdy character acting, but they
fail convincingly to convey the dramatic tensions underpinning the
various relationships. Many of Stewart's more insightful lines are
thrown away and the production needs a subtler touch to save itself from
being reduced to a nurses 'n' doctors soap opera.
However, Rosemary Chivers manages to evoke a vulnerable soul behind
the formidable armour of Sister Barton, and Dawn-Claire Robertson's
chatty telephonist, Miss Hart, is nicely pitched. Alasdair McCrone's
direction is turgid at times but any turgidity was instantly relieved
with a fantasy sequence, a la Dennis Potter, where Miss Hart dances with
four tuxedoed chaps like a twinkle-toed Ginger Rogers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Beastie Boys, Barrowland, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PETER EASTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484874</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CHALLENGING and totally incomprehensible opening slot from MC
Hurricane, the Beasties' regular DJ, indicated that the rapper's message
would be swallowed by the booming bass. A pity since the Hurra's
unbroadcastable material is destined rarely to be heard.
But rap is not all you get from the Beasties anyway, and certainly it
plays little part in Jon Spencer's universe unless you count repeated
crys of ''blues explosion''. This is not the blooze as ye know it, but a
wondrous weird and mutant thing, part Hendrix (as a real voodoo child)
part psycho-billy wildman. Spencer, formerly of the attitude-laden Pussy
Galore, is howling at your door. He is bad medicine and surprise support
act of the year.
The Beasties emerge crying ''Yo!'' (like you do) but transform
themselves instantly into the Dead Kennedys. Then it's Take DAT: tape
carries the load while the Beasties rap, shoulders hunched, arms waving,
fingers pointing (impossible to tell what any of this is about, but a
couple of the tracks sound pretty good).
Then MC Adam picks up a fuzz-bass and makes thunder like Jack Casady
from the Airplane of old. After which the Beasties become the Clash,
then (for the old folks) the Brian Auger Trinity, and even (yikes!)
Santana and Sly Stone. A grand musical tour that is stylish,
accomplished, witty, and fun.
The Beasties are punk pranksters who wrote the book of white rap years
ago. Obviously they love their record collection. May they never grow
old.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New move on rights of disabled</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484875</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEW attempt to ban discrimination against the disabled in Scotland
was launched in the Commons yesterday.
Labour MP Gordon McMaster (Paisley South) gained a formal first
reading for his Civil Rights (Disabled Persons) (Scotland) Bill without
debate.
The measure would set up a Disability Rights Commission to enforce
anti-discrimination laws and improve access to polling stations for the
disabled.
It is among several launched by Opposition MPs who claim the
Government's Disability Discrimination Bill, currently before
Parliament, does not go far enough.
The Civil Rights (Disabled Persons) Bill, introduced by Labour's Harry
Barnes (Derbyshire North-East), gained its second reading last month.
However, it stands no chance of becoming law without ministers' support.
There was a row last year over a similar measure when it was blocked
after Tories tabled a huge list of amendments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Disclosure bears closer scrutiny</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484876</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
William Russell reviews Demi Moore's latest, hugely controversial
film, tries to decipher another Jodie Foster Oscar-nominated role, and
considers John Candy's last screen performance
New releases Disclosure (18)
Directed by Barry Levinson
Nell (12)
Directed by Michael Apted
Wagons East (PG)
Directed by Peter Markle
All on general release from tomorrow.
Mrs Parker and the Vicious Circle (15)
Directed by Alan Rudolph
At Glasgow Film Theatre from tomorrow.
SEXUAL harassment of men by women is all the rage. Barry Levinson's
latest film, Disclosure, based on a Michael Crichton novel, although
unashamed tosh, rides the bandwagon in great style. It is one of those
films which has its cake and eats it, because the harassment in question
is physical, which allows the staging of an aggressive sex scene between
the stars -- or their body doubles.
The American cases which have been reported, however, are not about
men being raped by women, but about the poor boobies having to endure
girl talk all day long at work, or face up to suggestive remarks about
parts of their anatomy.
In other words, women in power, because sexual harassment is all about
having power, do to men what men in power do to women.
Michael Douglas, Hollywood's most put upon leading man -- the women
who have abused him include Kathleen Turner, Sharon Stone, and Glenn
Close -- is now ravaged by Demi Moore, who certainly has the muscles for
the task. They both work for different branches of a Seattle-based
computer company. When he is passed over for the top job she gets it.
Ten years earlier they had had a steamy affair, and have not seen each
other since. He is happily married and has two children. Ms Moore, once
installed in her new office, invites him up for an after-hours drink and
chat. No sooner is he inside her lair, and the white wine poured, than
she throws herself upon his body, suggesting they resume where they left
off.
He is tempted, but after ripping off her knickers, decides better of
the whole thing, does up his flies and leaves. Next day she accuses him
of sexual harassment. Furious, he returns the compliment. The sexual
harassment issues are well enough argued, but soon abandoned because the
film changes direction and we are embroiled in a chase up and down the
information highway as Douglas tries to save his job.
The trip through the recesses of the firm's computer with the aid of
an amazing virtual reality machine is very gripping and, in spite of the
fact that the story is basically arrant nonsense, the film does
entertain which is more than can be said about Nell.
Produced by Jody Foster, directed by Michael Apted, it is one of those
movies in which a female star plays someone who is disabled, although
not so it affects her looks, in order to get an Oscar nomination, which
has duly happened.
Foster is Nell, a wild woman of the woods whose existence is
discovered after the death of her mother. She speaks an incomprehensible
tongue and is painfully shy. She could be an idiot, but she is not, as
the handsome GP from a nearby town, Liam Neeson, who finds her,
realises.
A lady therapist from the state university, Natasha Richardson, is
dispatched to research the situation and she and Neeson establish a
relationship with Nell. But the wicked media find out and the idyll is
over.
The subject is potentially interesting, and Apted, a distinguished
director of documentaries, tries to give the absurd goings on some sense
of reality, while Neeson does his best with an improbable role.
But nothing can disguise the fact that Foster's prancings, mouthings,
and frantic hand gestures are other than those of a Hollywood star
shrieking ''Gimme, gimme another Oscar''. Boredom reigns from start to
finish.
Better by far, but shamefully not nominated in this year's ladies'
list, is Jennifer Jason Leigh in Alan Rudolph's Mrs Parker and the
Vicious Circle. It examines the life of Dorothy Parker, poet, wit,
critic, Hollywood scriptwriter and drunk, one of the influential group
of writers, painters, and poets who lunched at the round table in the
Algonquin Hotel in the 1920s and wrote much of the New Yorker.
It is a marvellous performance which manages to encompass Parker as a
young woman high on words and whisky, and then as an old woman in the
depths of cynicism and despair.
Dorothy Parker comes across as enchanting, repellent, vicious, and
loving, but above all sad. She was a woman, as somebody says, with ''a
passion for unhappiness''. Her marriages were disastrous, her love
affairs just as bad, her abortions numerous, and her suicide attempts
frequent.
Jennifer Jason Leigh's decision to imitate Parker's voice is the one
flaw in her performance. Dorothy's accent was at times impenetrable and
this affects comprehension of some of the verse which she recites.
Immaculate support is provided by Campbell Scott as Robert Benchley, her
closest friend, but never her lover, and the large supporting cast who
play the assorted Algonquin wits, notably Wallace Shawn as the hotel's
maitre d' who has the bright idea of the round table.
The film is handsome to look at, and the decision to shoot the
latter-day Dorothy in Hollywood in the late 1930s and in New York in the
1950s in black and white, is inspired.
Parker's reputation as purveyor of wit, wisdom, and cynicism, and a
user of words beyond compare, is well portrayed. The film rambles
slightly, but it remains the best thing Rudolph and Miss Jason Leigh
have done.
Peter Markle's Wagons East is a hilarious spoof western starring John
Candy. The basic premise is inspired. Having gone West, a group of men
and women decide the place has not lived up to expectations, abandon the
town of Prosperity, and head back East just as the raiload and the
government launch a great land race.
These misfits, spoiling things by heading in the wrong direction, have
to be stopped. Candy, in his last film, and a splendid cast make the
most of the material, especially John C McGinley. He plays a gay
bookseller who decides at the end of the long, long trail that maybe he
has not given the West a chance, announcing, as he rides off into the
sunset, that he has heard of this place called San Francisco.
It is well worth going along for the ride.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Former MP changes seat target</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484877</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NICOL STEPHEN, who for five months was Liberal Democrat MP for
Kincardine and Deeside, has decided to give up his ambitions for the
seat and switch his attention to the new Aberdeen South constituency.
The Aberdeen lawyer won the seat at a November 1991 by-election but
lost it in the subsequent General Election to Tory Mr George Kynoch.
At that time, Mr Stephen, 34, pledged to continue to serve the
constituency, to which he had been committed since before the 1987
election, and to win it back.
Now, in the light of the parliamentary boundary changes, he has
decided to move on and is one of the six Liberal Democrat applicants for
the candidature at Aberdeen South.
Mr Stephen, who is still prospective candidate for Kincardine and
Deeside, said he believed both seats winnable and it was a tough
decision as he had represented a major part of both areas during his
time as MP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Telling it straight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484878</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAEL Apted has a low opinion of the off Broadway play, Ideoglossic,
on which his film, Nell, starring Jodie Foster in an Oscar-nominated
role, is based, writes WILLIAM RUSSELL. ''It was so far off Broadway,
you could not see it,'' he said. ''It is, frankly, not a very good
play.''
A producer, who acquired the rights, showed the play to Foster, and
seven attempts at writing a script followed.
The problem was getting beyond the play's romantic love story between
a young doctor and a girl he was helping, who had grown up in isolation
speaking an invented language. The rights were then sold to Fox, and the
dramatist William (Shadowlands) Nicholson brought in to rewrite the
script. It was Nicholson who turned the whole project round, he said.
Foster then decided she did not want to direct the film, but to play the
girl -- the film is made by her production company -- and that was where
he came in.
''I only read the play as part of my research,'' he said. ''My agent
sent me the first draft of the script and after a week Jodie gave me the
job. I went to Portland, Oregon where she was shooting Maverick, and we
did a huge amount of work on it. There were a lot of changes.''
He thought Foster had picked him because she thought it a good idea to
have a director with experience of making documentaries. Nell is about a
young girl found living in a mountain shack after the death of her
mother, who had given birth to her as the result of rape and had fled
from society.
She speaks in an unintelligible language. A young doctor, played by
Liam Neeson, from the nearby town, and a speech therapist, played by
Natasha Richardson, sent by the state social work department, try to
find out how they can communicate with this wild woman.
''Ideoglossic'' is the term for a language people develop between
themselves. Apted and Nicholson developed their own version -- Nellish
-- which Foster speaks in the film.
Nell differs from most wild children in that she speaks a language
which is based on English. With most wild children it is impossible to
communicate because their language was not based on any known language.
She has also had a loving, if isolated and secret upbringing and has not
been physically abused.
''I did not want to make a depressing film,'' he said. ''Equally I did
not want the story just all wrapped up sweetly. At the end you see her
looking at the little girl, the daughter of the doctor and the therapist
who helped her, and you see that sense of loss. She remembers her dead
twin.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Theft from asbestos victims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484879</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR articles on asbestosis on successive days (March 3 and 4) reflect
the rising concern about the growing human costs of asbestos as more and
more people die from appalling asbestos-related disease.
Clydebank must be the asbestosis capital of Britain with an illness
rate 500 times the national average because of shipbuilding,
engineering, and the asbestos factory.
We are nowhere near a cure but we could stop the work of the appalling
Compensation Recovery Unit (CRU) of the Department of Social Security.
This claws back benefit paid to asbestosis sufferers if they win
compensation from the employers who poisoned them -- #1m has been clawed
back from asbestos sufferers already this year.
Consider that the victim has to prove he has the disease -- no easy
task. Then he has to prove where he got it perhaps 20 or 40 years ago.
Then, is the firm or its insurer still in existence?
Then there are all the revolting games of delay by lawyers and
insurers. The DSS then claws back any benefit paid out to a sufferer
since he found out he had the disease.
The highest sum the DSS has reclaimed from a victim this year (not an
asbestos sufferer) was #84,000. This is part of the #100m which the CRU
has got back from victims of accident, illness, and disease alone this
year.
What is the point of protesting about a low settlement? All extra
money won would go back to the Treasury because of the delay.
What is particularly revolting is that the Government takes your money
even if it has been awarded for ''pain and suffering'' rather than loss
of earnings.
This is nothing less than Government theft.
Over 200 MPs have signed my early day motion to get rid of the CRU. We
await the report of the Social Security Select Committee which has been
investigating the CRU.
I have now received over 140 letters from all over Britain from people
who have found National Insurance a fraud.
''Why did we pay our stamps all those years when the Government claws
back our benefit after calamity hits us?''
What private insurance company would be allowed to behave in such a
fraudulent way?
Tony Worthington, MP,
House of Commons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Law plea on ethics of gene research</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN,POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484880</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
URGENT legislation is needed to cope with the moral and ethical
consequences of rapid advances in human genetics, Professor Sheila
McLean, of Glasgow University, told MPs yesterday.
Giving evidence to the Science and Technology Select Committee,
Professor McLean warned that gene research is raising questions about an
individual's right to medical privacy and access to insurance which are
not covered by existing legislation.
She called on the Government to appoint a Royal Commission which could
evolve into some sort of body that would oversee developments in
genetical science and guide resulting legislation.
''What we need is a Royal Commission which is acting transparently,
but with a specific remit to consider how the law might impact on these
subjects, from surrogacy arrangements to medical records,'' she said.
Mr Spencer Batiste, Tory MP for Elmet, said things were changing too
quickly. A commission would ''cement everything'' into place and look
''fairly silly'' after a short period of time.
Professor McLean said she did not want extremely directive
legislation. Instead, it should create a structure like a licencing body
with powers to police genetics, but also with sufficient built-in
discretion to allow it to adapt to unforeseen scientific advances.
She said the speed with which research into the human body's genetic
structure -- the international human genome project -- is advancing
makes setting up a legal framework a matter of urgency. ''We don't have
long.''
Professor McLean heads the Law School's medical law unit, which is
examining the legal, ethical and social implications of the human genome
project, the first law school to do so. It hopes to host an
international conference on genetics next March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gerrymandering</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484881</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS one of the Tory councillors on Stirling District Council and the
elected member for Bridge of Allan the comments of George Robertson, MP,
on gerrymandering took my breath away by their sheer hypocrisy (February
27).
It was the Labour Party which suggested to the Boundaries Commission
that the status quo recommended for Stirling should be reconsidered --
and wouldn't it be a good idea to move Bridge of Allan and the
accompanying ward into the Clackmannan parliamentary constituency?
It knows well that to remove Bridge of Allan from Michael Forsyth's
constituency would effectively wipe out his majority.
As for Mr Robertson's comment about betraying the Stirling voters on
tax, what does he mean? We reduced the council tax by 26% last year, and
improved services.
Mr Robertson should check the facts that are fed to him before making
public statements, although he does know the facts on local taxation. As
a resident in Stirling district, he is a beneficiary of the 26%
reduction.
Brenda Holliday,
10 Chalton Road,
Bridge of Allan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trading places as East looks to the West</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484882</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Education and training have always been important but they are
arguably even more essential now given the changing nature of work and
trade liberalisation. Low-skilled uneducated people in northern Europe
increasingly face the prospect of long-term unemployment and poor living
standards as they cannot hope to compete with ''cheaper'' workers in the
emerging markets of the Far East, Latin America, and Eastern Europe.
The issue of Eastern European trade's likely impact on the developed
countries of Europe is an interesting one. Since the beginning of the
year there has effectively been a single market open to all East
European countries in all industries barring steel and textiles. So far
there does not appear to have been the cataclysmic effect on some
industries in the West that had been expected.
It is still relatively early days in terms of developing Eastern
Europe's trade with the nations of the European Union. However EU trade
with the East is growing strongly -- nearly doubling between 1985 and
1992 -- with the prospect of more to come. Aggregate trade flows with
the East have increased much faster than overall Community trade since
1985. Trade with Eastern nations now accounts for about 15% of non-OECD
trade in the European Community.
So far exported products from Eastern Europe have not been in direct
competition with some of our more sensitive industries such as
agriculture, cars, and steel, which have been afforded protection. The
Europe Agreements, for example, provide special treatment for the
perceived sensitive sectors, which account for as much as 40% of imports
from Eastern nations.
The largest increases in import penetration have been observed in
industries such as building materials, wood, and metal products and
mechanical engineering. For instance, imports of structural metal
products, boilers and reservoirs, cement and rolling stocks, have risen
more than sixfold between 1985-86 and 1991-92.
Research carried out by the Centre for Economic Policy Research (CEPR)
suggests that among northern European countries Britain and Italy are
most vulnerable to cheaper imports from Eastern Europe. The areas of
Britain most exposed are said to be the Midlands and Northern Ireland
where there is already high unemployment. This is because East European
countries have a comparative advantage in the kinds of manufacturing
industries which predominate in these regions, namely motor cars,
glassware, steel, plastics, rubber, textiles, metal and wood
transformation, and printing.
Southern European countries such as Spain, Portugal, Greece, and parts
of Italy have similarities with Eastern Europe in terms of their
comparative advantages in certain industries. However, at least in the
short term, southern European industries which use unskilled labour and
require little capital, such as clothing, furniture, and leather goods
are expected to continue to prosper.
Traditional heavy and light industries within the EU, particularly in
countries such as Britain, France, Germany, and the Benelux, that use
unskilled labour will come under growing pressure. As they become less
competitive, there will be a shift in these economies towards
organisations which receive their added value from the knowledge and the
creativity they put in rather than the muscle power.
We are already seeing this with the growth of the more obviously
knowledge-based business sectors of consultancy, finance and insurance,
advertising, journalism and publishing, television, healthcare,
education, and entertainment. This makes sense. The profitable future
for Western nations in the long term lies in specialising in
high-technology industries such as office equipment and electrical
appliances and those industries which rely heavily on human capital such
as pharmaceuticals and aerospace.
Thirty years ago nearly half of all workers in the industrialised
countries were making or helping to make things. In another 30 years'
time this figure may have dropped to 10%. It has already declined to 18%
in the US.
Although some forms of protectionism are likely to remain in
particular markets and particular regions, traditional industries in
northern Europe will not be able to compete in the long term unless they
specialise in particular value-added niche sectors of the market. This
has already been proven. For example, access to new technology has
improved productivity and made it economically viable to invest in
certain types of shipbuilding, textiles, and the manufacture of footwear
and ceramics in northern Europe, in the face of strong competition from
the Far East.
However, there could be potential social problems as the gap widens
between those with high incomes and highly prized skills and those
unskilled manual workers who are effectively priced out of the jobs
market. Some analysts forecast that the wages of unskilled labour could
fall by up to 7% compared with a rise of 10% for highly skilled people.
Even if this were to happen, the wages of unskilled workers in northern
Europe would still be 'way ahead of those available to similar workers
in the East. This could encourage some migration of labour from poorer
Eastern countries such as Romania and Bulgaria to more affluent Western
nations.
We have already seen a taste of the problems to come with the recent
French seamen's blockade of the Channel ports in protest at the use of
cheaper Polish crews. If similar unrest is to be avoided in other
sectors of industry then more investment will have to be made in
education, skills, and training to create better, more secure jobs. This
will help to offset the adverse effects of trade liberalisation which
overall should bring large economic benefits to the EU.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Saving the inheritance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484883</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE NHS was set up to care for people who were ill and needed
treatment or whose needs for care were such that other facilities like
homes could not cope with them.
It was not set up as a free substitute for residential care to enable
families to inherit their parents' money intact, and it does no favours
to an old person to put him/her into a ward where often enough the other
patients are too mentally and physically disabled to provide company.
During various spells working for the NHS I often came across people
who didn't need hospital care in medical wards where they occupied beds
needed by ill people; or in geriatric wards.
Some were awaiting places in local authority homes but others were
there so families could inherit their cash.
One man I remember had had a stroke and needed care, but not in
hospital. He had plenty of money and was more than willing to go to a
nursing home but his family always blocked the transfer arrangements.
The permanent staff were used to such situations -- his family wanted
his money. They had never looked after him themselves and would never
have had to. The man was mentally alert but lonely and miserable as the
other patients couldn't talk to him and the nurses were too busy.
The best of the residential homes, however, provide stimulation,
entertainment, and company for the residents. I have visited several,
and they are far more suited to alert old people's needs than a
hospital.
There is nothing new about having to pay for residential care -- it
has been this way since 1948, I believe. The poor pay nothing.
There is no ''right'' to inherit money. If someone does, it is good
fortune -- after all, millions inherit nothing.
Dallas Carter,
117 Calder Tower,
Motherwell.
</TEXT>
