<DOCNO>GH950309-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doubt about the truth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484885</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR editorial presented a balanced view of the issues in the Ayr
child sexual abuse case (February 28), while other papers were
vindicating parents, pillorying social workers, when, in fact, we are
still in doubt about the truth.
Again a senior court has overturned verdicts of more junior courts
almost five years later. Where are children in this situation when the
responsible adults have to use a system which can interpret the truth as
they see it?
You say the evidence has not changed. What does this system say to
children who have given their accounts of what happened to them to
sheriffs, panel members, and professionals? Do children have a voice or
does the legal system take precedence?
Social work training has focused on the complexity of the task of
hearing the child. The Clyde Report drew attention to the fact that
interviewing children is not a prescribed process of question and
answer. It is about establishing trust between adults and children over
a period of time.
What the law looks for is clarity, consistency, and corroboration --
the very things a child is going to find difficult.
Social workers work within a legal framework and act on decisions made
by courts. They are only too aware of the issues and are often left with
feelings of distress that children are left in vulnerable situations
because the weight of evidence required by the current system is well
beyond reasonable doubt.
Gayle McGregor,
90 Habbieauld Road,
Kilmaurs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Salutary point</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR coverage of the Ayrshire sexual abuse case was in general
balanced, in particular the concluding point in the leader, ''Doubt is a
frequent fellow traveller in the search for the truth about sexual
abuse'' was a wise and salutary one (February 28).
However, by way of contrast, Michael Fry's comments (March 1) were
both uninformed and unhelpful. He refers to the ''bungling of individual
social workers'', omitting to mention the scrutinising and
substantiating of the evidence of abuse, in 1992, by professions other
than social work.
While Sheriff Miller refers to the case as ''complex, complicated, and
disturbing'', Michael Fry reduces it to simple social work ''bungling''.
Secondly, his assertion that ''social work does not rest on theory''
is palpably untrue. Social work has an impressive and expanding
knowledge base, so much so that the profession has consistently argued
for a longer professional training period to do greater justice to the
range of social work theories available.
Current social work thinking emphasises the importance of minimum
necessary intervention, looks critically at US originating theory, and
is not utopianistic in believing social problems can be ''cured''.
Michael Fry's contribution adds nothing to the wider understanding of
so sensitive a subject as child sexual abuse but instead fuels existing
misconceptions and prejudices.
Ian Brodie,
141 West Nile Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
