<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What a life for teachers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484888</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I DO so agree with E Keating's modest proposal that teachers should be
banned from driving in order to free the roads of congestion during term
time (March 3). However, this does not go far enough as it takes no
account of the serious problems created elsewhere by these self same
teachers after the end of term.
It is well known that they enjoy long holidays on the Continent in the
summer, thus causing unacceptable congestion at air and sea ports
throughout the high season. It would therefore be a prudent move to
withdraw not only their driving licences but their passports as well, so
that they would not be able to go gallivanting abroad.
Not only would this measure ensure that normal people could travel
with ease on their own well-deserved holidays, but into the bargain
teachers would then be forced to spend their large salaries here in the
UK supporting the British economy instead of bringing it down as they
have been doing for far too long.
Naturally teachers could, as duty required, be issued with special
documents to enable them to travel abroad with pupils on officially
sanctioned trips. These special passports would of course be able to
restrict their access to beaches, cafes, discos, pavements, etc, and
include perhaps some form of curfew arrangement so that their presence
would cause the absolute minimum of inconvenience to real people with
families.
Teaching is a vocation, not a vacation -- and it's about time these
so-called teachers started living in the real world.
A Brown,
27 Kingsdyke Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
