<HEADLINE>Cabinets on the doorstep</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484889</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I NOTE that the cable company at present excavating in Bearsden has
begun an expensive advertising campaign in this newspaper. What a relief
to know that what we are seeing is just a ''rapid installation
programme'' with ''a certain amount of digging and pavement work''.
We poor beleaguered citizens of Bearsden think it's the Third World
War. Maybe they will be back to finish the road resurfacing in the
spring.
Such a pity, too, about the cabinet -- so large, so ugly, so many,
just like the gas board, the SSEB, and BT used to have. A case of ''Back
to the Future'' perhaps. And, as the ads proudly proclaim, ''No
unsightly satellite dishes or aerials'' -- just lots of unsightly
cabinets instead.
At least those people who opt for Sky TV have the choice, a freedom
denied to those like me with cabinets on their doorsteps, installed
without consultation, without consent, without apology. Free-standing
too; so much for the claims of ''sensitive'' siting.
The information superhighway may indeed be wonderful, but does it
really require arrogant, patronising bully-boy tactics to enforce it on
the unsuspecting public? And I haven't even mentioned the tree roots or
the environment yet. As consumers we have the ultimate choice, and every
day brings better and cheaper alternatives. So, yes, tel your friends,
tel everyone, tel them NO.
Veronica T Ford,
20 Ralston Road,
Bearsden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
