<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Power to the people -- and heat in the pipeline</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PAT AGNEW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>OPEN FORUM,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979484891</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN 1925 Britain was behind other industrial countries in the use of
electricity: the whole system was in need of standardisation, there were
too many small and inefficient generators, and many small towns had no
electricity supply.
The Weir Committee recommended that generation be concentrated in
large efficient power stations, and that the country should be covered
by a ''grid-iron'' of high-voltage transmission lines.
That was sensible in 1925. But what was sensible in 1925 is not
necessarily sensible now.
It is no longer true that large power stations are the most efficient.
It is not possible to turn the energy in a fuel into mechanical or
electrical power with 100% efficiency: this is against the laws of
physics. In a conventional power station between one-quarter and a half
of the energy in the fuel is turned into electrical power, and the rest
heats up the cooling water. At Longannet, for example, nearly two-thirds
of the energy in the fuel is wasted in heating up the Firth of Forth.
If this heat could be used for a central heating plant, there is no
theoretical reason why a power station should not be 100% efficient.
Such a unit, providing both heat and power, is called a Combined Heat
and Power (CHP) plant. Since, unlike electricity, heat cannot be
transmitted over long distances, CHP plants must be built where the heat
is needed. They produce more heat than power, and are most efficient if
they are operated as central heating units that produce electricity as a
valuable by-product.
One of the reasons put forward for linking Northern Ireland to the
Scottish grid is that Northern Ireland is over-dependent on oil for
generating electricity. Coal reserves are many times larger than oil
reserves, and any fossil fuelled power station that is expected to last
more than 30 years must be coal fired.
Up to now coal-fired power stations have been like Longannet: a bit
messy, inefficient, and usually very large. But some years ago the
Swedes, like the Northern Irish, were worried about their
over-dependence on oil. They built a coal-fired power station of a new
type in the middle of Stockholm. It is on the quayside: the fuel is
conveyed from the ship to the covered storage area by enclosed
conveyors, so that there is no dust.
It burns the coal in a way that traps the sulphur (the chief cause of
acid rain) in the ash. The ash conveyors are also enclosed and the ash
itself, instead of being an environmental nuisance, can be used to make
paving blocks or hardcore for building, so that it is a valuable
by-product.
This station has been in service since 1991. Since it is connected to
Stockholm's district heating system it functions as a CHP plant and is
therefore at least twice as efficient as any coal-fired unit in the UK.
The most progressive cities in Europe all have district heating
schemes. Stockholm, Copenhagen, Paris, and Vienna all have them. There
are over 50,000 miles of pipes distributing hot water or steam around
the cities of Europe: they are increasingly coming to be heated by CHP
plants.
The city of Brescia, in Northern Italy, generates so much power in its
municipal heating plants that in winter it has a surplus to sell to the
Italian grid, earning revenue for the benefit of the local taxpayers.
The heat for a district heating scheme can be provided by any
convenient fuel. In continental cities municipal rubbish is often used.
As the technique of coppicing is developed, wood chips will undoubtedly
be used more and more (growing coppice wood is a better use of land than
set-aside, it provides employment and income for farmers, and the
coppices are havens for wildlife).
These CHP schemes are to be found mostly in cities where the elected
local authority has the duty, or at least the power, to provide the
citizens with a full range of public services.
A power station that throws away two-thirds of the energy in its fuel
may well be the cheapest way of providing electrical power if
electricity is considered in isolation. But if a town council is
responsible for providing heat, light, and power, a CHP plant is likely
to be the most economical way of doing so because heat that would be
wasted in a conventional power station can be sold very cheaply,
reducing the consumer's total fuel bills.
The structure of local government in Northern Ireland is one of the
things that will have to be settled over the coming months. This is an
opportunity to give the councils the power to provide really efficient
services.
The British Government is committed to reducing carbon dioxide
emissions, and the best way of doing this without reducing the services
provided is by improving efficiency: the use of CHP can double the
efficiency with which fuel is used. Small CHP plants are being used more
and more, but fuels other than gas are most conveniently used in
district heating schemes and the structure of local government in this
country has, up to now, inhibited their use.
The future lies with local energy conversion to serve local needs. The
EU has promised #240m for refurbishing the city centres of Belfast and
Londonderry: there will never be a better opportunity to give these
cities modern district heating schemes, to put them on a par with
Stockholm, Copenhagen, Paris, and Vienna. If this opportunity is taken,
Northern Ireland could set an example that could begin the process of
dragging the British electricity supply system into the second half of
the twentieth century. Connecting Northern Ireland to Scotland, so that
power can be generated at Longannet for use in Belfast, would simply
fossilise a system that made sense in the 1920s but makes no sense now.
* Pat Agnew is Economics Speaker for the Scottish Green Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
