<TEXT>
* YOU are convinced your student son or daughter is taking drugs. You
are naturally worried. What do you do about it? Before you decide on a
confrontation you would do well to equip yourself first with some
knowledge of today's drug scene. Drugline Scotland is a free and
confidential information and advice service for callers who have a drug
problem or who are worried about someone who may be taking drugs.
Telephone 0800-776600, 24 hours, seven days a week.
* YOU found a lump in your breast or you've been called back after a
mammogram for ''further investigation''. Panic. Is it cancer? Put your
mind at ease and get hold of some facts by ringing one of the following
helpline numbers run by Breast Cancer Care: Glasgow 0141-353 1050;
Edinburgh 0131-221 0407; Nationwide Freeline 0500-245345.
* MORE than half a million elderly people in the UK are entitled to
free sight tests and financial help with spectacles, yet they miss out
because they are not registered blind or partially blind, says Help the
Aged. The charity has now launched a free booklet, Better Sight. Send an
sae to Sight, Help the Aged, St James Walk, London.
* A NIGHT out may carry more hazards than a hangover. If you drink
more than two-and-a-half pints of beer, or five single whiskies, or five
glasses of wine in a day (more than six units) your chances of
triggering a stroke are increased.
A study in Finland reported in the current issue of Monitor Weekly,
found that a recent high intake of alcohol was a significant factor in
stroke victims. The evidence is more convincing since the group studied
(people under 40) are not particularly liable to strokes. But all
patients in the study had taken more than five units of alcohol during
the 24 hours prior to falling ill.
* TALKING to your doctor can be just as effective as taking drugs for
depression. Researchers at Oxford University compared three groups of
patients who were given different treatments for depression. Those who
had just counselling improved by 60% after 12 weeks compared to those
given anti-depressents (52%) and 27% on placebo only drugs.
* IF you want to see how fit your doctor is, enrol him for the annual
eight-and-a-half mile Muckle Toon Doctors Run, which takes place on
Sunday May 14 in Dumfries and Galloway. For application forms write to
Dr Tom Kennedy, Health Centre, Langholm, Dumfries and Galloway, DG13
OJY.
ANN SHAW
</TEXT>
