<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Age may not weary us quite so much</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICHOLAS POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484893</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NICHOLAS POWELL reports from Paris on research that could help
everyone feel better -- except the drug companies
THIS may be no elixir of eternal life, but it is a genuine feel-good
factor. A naturally-occurring molecule with an impossibly complex name,
isolated 30 years ago but only experimented on recently, is being hailed
in the US and France as a potent agent in the fight against aging.
DHEA in its abbreviated form, Dehydroepindrosterone Sulphate to be
scientifically correct, will not make anyone live longer. It will not
smooth out wrinkles, or combat serious diseases such as Alzheimer's,
sclerosis, Parkinson's or rheumatoid arthritis. But leading scientists
have great hopes that DHEA will spur the body on to fight troublesome
effects of ageing, and help combat afflictions as diverse as rheumatic
pain, memory loss, certain forms of cancer linked with the agieng
process, and cardiac illness.
It could help stave off the onset of AIDS, as the level of DHEA in the
bloodstream is known to decrease in HIV-positive patients when they
begin to develop symptoms. DHEA should improve general feelings of
psychological and physical well-being. Our deaths will remain largely
genetically programmed, and turn up to their appointments. But getting
there should be less of a bore. The human and economic implications are
enormous.
And the molecule DHEA is secreted by the adrenal glands which sit atop
the kidneys. It flows around the bloodstream in huge quantities for such
a substance (between 10 and 100 times as much as other steroids) and has
an impressively long shelf life -- DHEA ''lives'' for ten hours in the
system.
A neurosteroid, which acts on the nervous and immune systems, DHEA
also contributes to our growth. It appears in our bodies around the age
of seven and peaks in quantity around the age of 25, after which the
future is just one long decline -- by the age of 70 we have only about
10% of the DHEA we had as lads and lassies. What complicates matters
considerably is that the amount of DHEA going the rounds varies
considerably from one individual to another. And the amount drops even
lower with age in people who have had less to start off with.
DHEA has been complicated to research because it is peculiar to man
and some of our big ape cousins, who have less of it. It is not found in
the sort of animals usually tested in laboratories, although one
laboratory rat, to confuse matters, had some in its brain -- so it can
be located in animals' nervous systems. Nevertheless, laboratory tests
using huge doses of DHEA on animals like rats cured them of numerous
diseases and even prevented cancer in one species predisposed to the
illness.
French professor Emile-Etienne Baulieu, inventor of the morning-after
contraceptive pill for women, RU 486, and holder of the prestigious US
Lasker Prize for Medical Research, first spotted DHEA in the early
1960s. But as it is cheap to synthesise and as a natural product, it
can't be patented, and because it may help reduce medicine consumption
by elderly people, drug companies have not been forthcoming to help
research it.
But what does DHEA do? The endocrine glands use it to produce male and
female hormones. More generally, it keeps us fit and our inequality in
the face of the diseases that beset old age can be linked, Prof Baulieu
and his colleagues think, to the inequal distribution of DHEA among
individuals.
An old friend of Prof Baulieu, Samuel Yen, who is Professor of
Medicine of Reproduction at San Diego University, California, has just
concluded a preliminary six-month trial on men and women aged between 71
and 94. The product, compared to a placebo, was taken orally in small
doses. Eliminated effortlessly, it had no side-effects and produced an
improvement in the physical and psychological well-being of a
significant number of patients -- 82% of the women and 67% of the men.
Patients reported enjoying better sleep, feeling of greater energy and
an improved reaction to normally stressful situations. Sex drive was not
affected but a few said pains and stiffness in their joints had
improved.
When will they be sure it can do more? Prof Baulieu says that while
certain characteristics of DHEA still need to be described, he is
convinced that the substance in small doses will produce no
side-effects. The next step in research will be a comprehensive trial,
due to begin soon in three Paris hospitals. Stocks of serum dating back
a number of years (DHEA remains stable in such conditions), will be used
to determine how levels vary from one individual to another, especially
as they age, and how its level in the bloodstream ties in with histories
of illness.
Professors Baulieu and Yen hope that DHEA will have revealed all its
secrets within the next three or four years. If its promises come true,
the molecule should be a huge money-saver for national health services.
People over the age of 60, in France at least, require twice as much
medical attention and consume two and a half times as much medicine as
the national average. The difficulty could be getting drug companies to
co-operate. For however much there is to be said of the value of DHEA,
precious little money apparently stands to be made from it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>See, that's her, now it's your turn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN SHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484894</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Actress Dorothy Paul has thrown her heart and soul into our women's
health campaign. Ann Shaw explains her role -- and how you can help
ONE OF Glasgow's best-loved actresses, Dorothy Paul, has a new role to
play -- and it is one that will be rembered for years to come. For
Dorothy is to launch our Coffee Break, an innovative fund-raising
venture for The Herald's Campaign for Women's Health.
So, please join Dorothy at the Glasgow Moat House International at
10.30am on March 27 to find out how you can help raise money for our
One-Stop gynaecological clinic at Glasgow Royal Infirmary. Already funds
stand at more than #26,000. We expect to open the clinic early this
summer, but we need your help.
Just back from hillwalking in New Zealand, Dorothy welcomes the
opportunity to launch our inititiative. ''So often women put their own
health last. Let's hope that this new clinic at the Royal Infirmary will
become a prototype for others throughout Scotland.''
Now in her mid-fifties, she knows all about the problems women can
have in middle life. She is a firm advocate of Hormone Replacement
Therapy. ''Without it I could not do my job. I tried coming off for a
few months and it was a disaster. I've been on it for seven years.''
She is enjoying increasing fame and fortune -- and she is bouncing
with energy and good looks. So what's her secret? Quite simple. She puts
it down to exercise, Evening Primose oil and HRT.
With two marriages behind her and a long spell as a single parent of
hertwo daughters, now grown up, life has not always been easy. Born in
Dennistoun, the daughter of an electrician and a musical mother, Dorothy
learned to play the piano and sing from an early age.
She entered showbusiness as an 18-year-old at the Tivoli in Aberdeen,
but first came to fame on STV's One O'Clock Gang.She has a special place
in the affections of many Glaswegians through her highly successful
one-woman show, See That's Her, based on her early life in Dennistoun.
She has a personality that has been described as electrifying, warm
and honest without being intimidating, pushy or patronising. In other
words a very likeable Glaswegian, true to her roots.So, we are delighted
Dorothy has agreed to host our first fund-raising Coffee Break.
After Dorothy has got things off to a rousing start, our Marketing
Department will reveal the mechanics of our novel fund-raising venture,
something you can do in your own home.
We believe this is the first time it has been tried in Scotland;
elsewhere reports have been rapturous. Like all good fund-raising
ventures, it is enjoyable first and foremost. So what is it? I am not
allowed to reveal it at this stage . . . but let's say we are looking
for 400 Coffee Break hostesses.
Come along and listen. You don't have to join, though of course we
hope you will. To get your complimentary ticket simply fill in the
coupon on this page and return it to: The Herald Campaign for Women's
Health, Marketing Department, The Herald, 195 Albion Street, Glasgow, G1
1QP.
* ANN SIMPSON writes: Women are so pivotal to the well-being of our
society that the quality of their own health is vital to us all. In
Scotland the statistics are not good. A recent 10-year international
study, the Monica Project, examined heart disease in 22 countries and
found that women in the north of Glasgow fared worst among a sample of
15 million people. Meanwhile the latest available figures for lung
cancer show women's mortality from the disease is higher here than
elsewhere in the world, and has, in fact, doubled in the past 20 years.
Breast cancer also continues to rise, killing seven women a day. Cancer
of the cervix accounts for about 180 deaths a year year and the annual
fatality rate for ovarian cancer is around 377 women; for cancer of the
uterus, 107 women.
What can be done? Preventative vigilence is the obvious strategy and
one already operating to some extent through networks like Well Women
clinics and the various national screening programmes. But there remains
a pressing need to increase consciousness throughout our culture about
the importance of women's health and the urgency of providing the best
possible speedy treatment and care when problems do arise.
To this end we have launched The Herald Foundation for Women's Health,
a charity whose first project is the establishment of a ''one-stop''
gynaecological clinc for women with menstrual and related disorers.
Based at the Royal Infirmary, Glasgow, the service will be
consultant-led and staffed by a dedicated team with access to the latest
technology for investigation, diagnosis and treatment, and the ability
to exclude malignant disease as a causal factor. It will operate in an
environment of personal and friendly care and the aim is to open it by
the summer. Women will be referred to it by their general practitioners
and although the majority of patients will be from the Glasgow area,
patients from other parts of the country will not be discouraged.
The cost of setting up and running the clinic requires #100,000, and
in the few months since the charity began our readers have generously
raised just over #26,000 either through individual or community
donations. Ceilidhs have been held along with church fetes and fun-runs,
and various women's groups, like the Soroptimists, have pledged support.
In one instance employers have agreed to match any sum raised for the
clinic by the women on their staff. In another, contributions have come
via company dances and public dinners. The Christmas stamps project,
organised in conjunction with the Royaly Mail, brought in #2,000. Now,
with the Big Coffee Break, we are entering the second phase of our
collecting and it this kind of collective effort which is so vital and
valuable to the Foundation's work.
Women help to make the economy go round, and when illness deals them a
serious blow the world of the family often collapses. So, as much as
this venture is about women's welfare it is about Scotland's state of
health, too. And this is why we also need the support of industry,
commerce and the professions; in fact any business where women are
integral to the workforce. Every single one of us needs to try and avert
the anguish behind the statistics.
</TEXT>
