<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Injury claim against police</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER policeman who quit the force because of disabling back
injuries, was hurt during ''restraint and arrest'' training, the High
Court in London was told yesterday.
Mr Malcolm Bradley, 35, now of Albury, Drynie Park North, near Muir of
Ord, Ross-shire, a probationary constable in the London force when the
injury occurred on January 17, 1989, is fighting for compensation from
the Metropolitan Police Commissioner, who denies blame.
His counsel, Mr Neil Garnham, said he had been paired off with another
constable, posing as a suspect, during restraint and arrest training at
Peckham Police Station, south London.
The manoeuvre being practised was known as ''press down'', and
involved Mr Bradley manhandling his colleague to the ground before
applying a wrist lock, Mr Justice Waterhouse was told.
During the exercise, Mr Bradley suffered excruciating back pain and
fell to the ground. His instructor's attempts to help him merely
redoubled his pain and probably made his back injuries more severe, Mr
Garnham said.
Mr Bradley made a ''substantial recovery'' before returning to police
duties three weeks later, but his back remained vulnerable and even
trivial manoeuvres continued to cause him pain.
He strained his back again while lifting one of his children in May
1989, and yet again in January 1990, when bending over to search a
suspect's car, this time putting an end to his police career.
Mr Bradley was retired from the force on medical grounds on January
17, 1991. He spent two years out of work before moving to the North of
Scotland, and now works as a fork-lift truck salesman, earning
#13,000-a-year, substantially less than had he been able to remain in
the force.
Mr Garnham said he still suffered severe back pain and disability, and
his back was likely to remain vulnerable for life.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The cries from the back benches</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484897</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVIDENCE that the economy is beginning to respond to earlier interest
rate hikes designed to slow it down come at a difficult time for the
Chancellor and the Governor of the Bank of England who met yesterday.
Growth is still taking place but the pace of expansion is slowing. By
that test money is dear enough already and its cost would normally be
left. There might even be room for considering the possibility of lower
interest rates later this year. At this stage in previous expansionist
cycles the need to protect sterling has imposed higher interest rates
and the famous ''stop'' of the ''stop-go'' experience, which signalled
the inability of the economy to expand without overheating. What the
markets are suffering is not, however, anything like an old sterling
crisis. Sterling is really being dragged down by other currency
movements. The dollar, to which we remain coupled, no matter how
informally, has been moving sharply downwards, while the mark is moving
up.
At the heart of the dollar's longer-term weakness is the huge
borrowings of the United States -- and the inability of American
politicians to address it by raising taxes as Messrs Lamont and Clarke
did here. The unpopularity of these British moves (notwithstanding their
inherent prudence) has not escaped American politicians and both the
President and his opponents are dallying with the possibility of lower
taxation. That seems perverse: although the American economy is itself
growing with surprising vigour it can hardly hope to wipe out its
budgetary deficit entirely by enhanced revenues from growth. That
problem is compounded by a shorter-term difficulty: foreign investors
suspect that US interest rates have temporarily peaked at a time when
the currency needs the support of even higher rates. The American
monetary authorities do not want an ever-weakening dollar but they are
presented with the same challenge as the UK, whether to reduce growth by
dearer money which would stabilise the dollar, or let the dollar slip
further.
In our case the on-going recovery should be allowed to proceed. German
hints of reducing their own rates should be given a little more time to
work, along with the modest rises other EU members have just imposed.
Today is the traditional day for changes in UK rates, and the Governor
of the Bank of England has seemed to be wedded to dearer money, so he
may have persuaded the Chancellor to act again. UK stock markets did not
seem to think that likely. They could be wrong, but the Chancellor must
be beginning to hear the cries from the back benches -- and even from
Cabinet colleagues. There are new taxes still to come into operation
next month and the Government is only two years away from the next
election. Self-interest, self-preservation, will make pleas for some
relaxation beguiling, especially when they are not contradicted by
public interest. In an age of contained inflation cheap money should
generate growth. The cost of borrowing is too dear, a fact of great
importance for new investment. Every Chancellor since 1945 has found
continuing growth elusive. We are now getting it, even if the benefits,
which are in the export industries, remain obscure to millions of
taxpayers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hughes calls on the media to leave his family alone</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN,POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE TORY Minister who resigned on Monday ''for family reasons'' after
admitting an affair yesterday called on the media to leave his wife and
children alone, following reports that his wife had played a part in the
break up of his previous marriage.
Mr Robert Hughes, MP for Harrow West, held a news conference on the
doorstep of his west London home. He told journalists his family should
be allowed to get on with their lives.
His wife, Sandra, pledged to support him after he resigned
unexpectedly as junior Public Service Minister, saying he needed time to
mend his marriage.
His departure embarrassed Mr Major, who withheld publication of the
traditional exchange of letters.
Yesterday Mr Hughes told journalists: ''On Monday, I told you all
candidly and honestly why I had to resign as a Minister. Now, whatever
you wish to say about me, that's up to you, and I make no complaint. I'm
fair game for that.
''But the fact is that my wife and three children are entirely
innocent parties in all of this, and two things have arisen since Monday
that makes it necessary for me to make yet another statement.
''Attempts have been made to trace my children by sick people who are
apparently journalists. That is not acceptable. Some newspapers have
been given lies about my wife. I wish to set the record entirely
straight.
''Sandra and I started to go out after I was separated amicably from
my first wife, so Sandra had absolutely nothing to do with the breakdown
of my first marriage.''
He refused to answer questions.
Robert Hughes:
''Sick journalists''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A shield worth keeping</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEGISLATION to protect liberal states from the malign activities of
terrorists is difficult to frame and enforce for the obvious reason that
it tends to compromise the very things it aims to protect. It is easy to
see, therefore, why proponents and opponents of this country's
Prevention of Terrorism Act can argue their case with conviction. Labour
introduced the legislation the Conservatives have maintained; but Labour
has tended to react against the way in which its Act has operated in
practice -- more than two-thirds of those arrested under its provisions
have turned out to be innocent. Now that the attempts to produce peace
in Northern Ireland seem to be bearing fruit many believe that the case
for the Act is much weakened while its drawbacks are more than ever
exposed.
It is in the nature of terrorism and its containment that some wholly
innocent people should have their rights of free movement curtailed and
that they even suffer temporary arrest. The contemporary terrorist -- as
many incidents involving the IRA will in an instant confirm -- is able
to appear completely innocent of anything. In a free society he, or she,
is able to come and go with remarkably little surveillance or restraint.
A system which is successful in about one of every three occasions in
which suspects are arrested is neither onerous nor inadequate. Most
people will think that compared with the atrocities perpetrated by the
IRA, and they should not be forgotten, the infringement of civil
liberties attendant on preventing terrorism is not too high a price to
pay. It would be better if it did not have to be paid at all, but it can
scarcely be avoided in the modern world. The Act should be kept in
operation.
It is not just the Irish dimension which supports that conclusion,
though the fact that the IRA cannot unilaterally abandon its weaponry is
a reminder that it does not yet really trust or respect the essence of
democratic politics -- its peaceful nature, and acceptance of its
outcomes whatever these happen to be. That may change with time, with
Sinn Fein becoming a normal party, but it cannot be guaranteed. Quite
apart from that, however, is the way in which this country is the focus
of other terrrorist activities, particularly those emanating from the
Middle East. Some of these activities are inspired by memories of
Britain's Imperial role but some terrorists seek to use our territory to
get at enemies among refugees resident here, or at Jewish diplomats
working here. We all need protecting, but within the limits laid down by
Parliament. These limits are specified in the Act. From time to time
they may require amendment, but they do not seem likely to be abolished
completely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
