<HEADLINE>How Donald faced up to a dramatic request</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484900</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DONALD Dewar receives a call from the BBC television drama department
at Pebble Mill in Birmingham. No, they don't want the MP for Glasgow
Garscadden to play Heathcliffe in a remake of Wuthering Heights,
although we believe he could make a pretty good stab at it.
They are making a play in which a police inspector enters a room and
says the line: ''Switch off that TV. What's that boring nonsense you
were watching anyway?''
No, Donald is not to play the polisman, although he has the height for
it. Donald's role is to be the face on the TV. For the boring bit on TV
the Pebble Mill producers wanted to use Donald talking about devolution
on the Kilroy show. Was that all right?
Donald, ever the gentleman, agreed.
Test of a true
'Muir fan
WITH a capacity of only 3200, tickets for Stenhousemuir's Tennents
Scottish Cup tie on Saturday are in short supply. Graeme Hoggen from
Lenzie, a fan of long-standing at Ochilview, was more than a little
upset when he phoned the club to find that all the tickets had been
sold.
He told the club secretary that as one of the 300 or so regular
attenders of less glamorous matches surely he should get some
preferential treatment.
''OK,'' said the Stenhousemuir official, ''If you're a genuine fan,
name the team.''
''Harkness, Clarke, Donaldson, Armstrong, McGeachie, Christie, Steel,
Fisher, Mathieson, Hutchinson, Sprott. Substitutes: Roseburgh . . .''
He got his tickets.
Digit out, BT
BRITISH Telecom have been harping on about Phoneday when we all have
to insert an extra 1 into our telephone codes. ''Your number's up! Use
your new code now'' is the message which has been appearing on phone
bills. Not leading by example, BT lists its own number in Glasgow
without the extra digit.
That sinking
feeling
DEMOCRACY is alive and well in councils up and down Scotland. Take,
for instance, the following great debate at Cumbrae Community Council,
as reported in the Largs &amp; Millport Weekly News.
The topic under discussion was vandalism of the public conveniences in
Millport.
Community council member Mary Currie asked: ''Where are the police
when they know that is a bad area? If the police made themselves shown
at the toilets on a regular basis there might not be the same
problems.''
Regional councillor Fergus Clarkson replied: ''Everyone wants
policemen everywhere, but these guys are pretty expensive and I don't
know if you would be making the best use of the police by having them
guarding your toilets. There are cheaper ways of doing it, like
surveillance cameras.''
Footnote -- The front page of the same edition of the newspapers
carried a late-breaking story: ''Police divers spent all Friday
searching for a security camera which had been stolen after being
secretly hidden in the toilets at Millport Pier . . .''
* MORE democracy in action, this time from the Western Isles Council
debating chamber in Stornoway. Councillor Donald Maclean, the relatively
new member for Lochmaddy, declared that he did not understand a report
to the finance committee. Despite attempted explanations by the chief
executive and the director of finance, Councillor Maclean, a retired
police superintendent, declared himself ''still confused''.
Some longer-serving council members told Mr Maclean not to worry and
that he would soon pick things up. Mr Maclean stood his ground: ''I
accept what the director of finance has said but I am still confused.
However, I reserve the right to be confused. That is my right and it is
my intention every time I am confused to not keep quiet.
''And no-one on this council will make me keep quiet -- whatever their
title -- when I am confused.''
And it wasn't even in the Gaelic.
That's my boy!
LESLEY Riddoch, editor of the Scotswoman newspaper, was on the BBC
Breakfast programme yesterday morning being strident, as she does so
well, about International Women's Day.
She chose the wrong person with whom to be strident, Sir Bernard
Ingham, the doughty former media adviser to Mrs Thatcher, who was on the
programme to review the daily papers. ''Do you have any children and if
so, who's looking after them right now?'' she asked.
''Yes. One. Himself. He's 38,'' replied Sir Bernard.
* UNLIKE some newspapers, we don't have to change our name as a token
gesture for International Women's Day. We have always been The Herald.
To mark the occasion, however, all the lads on The Herald were yesterday
wearing ladies' underwear. For many of us it was a new and interesting
experience.
</TEXT>
