<HEADLINE>All aboard the big dipper</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484901</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alf Young, Economics Editor, explains why the currency crisis means we
are
all in for a roller-coaster ride
HOLD on to your seats for another global currency crisis. The words
and images used to portray the latest gyrations in the relative values
of the dollar, mark, yen and pound in markets round the world owe
something to the thrill of the fairground ride.
And don't those graphs of the dollar plunging against the yen, or the
pound testing new lows against the mark, bear an uncanny resemblance to
the big dipper? Frantic dealers trying to keep on top of the market's
switchback momentum -- and make a profitable turn in the process -- add
further dramatic colour to the scene.
Yet outwith bank treasury dealing rooms, away from the specialist wire
services and computer screens, for those of us not privy to what
transpires at meetings between Ken and Eddie, the Chancellor and the
Bank of England governor, does all the fuss have any meaning or impact
on our lives? Or is it a shadow show only slightly less esoteric,
marginally more intelligible than the kind of derivatives trading
indulged in by Nick Leeson in Singapore?
Well, yes, it does matter. At the level of the obvious, it matters
every time we go abroad and have to convert to another currency. Last
week in New York I was doing the kind of mental arithmetic indulged in
by travellers everywhere. The price of clothes, CDs, even a pastrami
sandwich at Carnegie's Deli on Fifth Avenue looked that little bit more
inviting as the pound climbed into the 1.60-plus range against the
weakening dollar.
It is obvious, too, that one line of defence against a crumbling
currency is a hike in domestic interest rates. Since Monday, five member
states of the European Union have pushed up short-term rates in a bid to
ride out the turbulence. That means dearer borrowing at home, though
thankfully not yet here in the UK. That too is something everyone
understands.
Contrary to Harold Wilson's dictum, devaluation, whether within a
quasi-fixed rate mechanism like the ERM or through the downward movement
of a floating currency, really can hit the pound in your pocket.
But the constant ordering and reordering of currencies against each
other is also saying something significant, at a deeper level, about the
relative strengths and weaknesses of the economies concerned. For most
of the time, the massive round-the-clock global trading in and out of
this currency or that, is spurred by movements in the second, third or
fourth decimal point.
That's what passes for stability in a world where fixed exchange rates
are, largely, a thing of the past. Only currency traders and the
institutions or speculators who employ them get excited by the profit to
be made by correctly guessing what such fractional movements will be
later today, tomorrow or next week.
But when the pound gyrates by four or five German pfennigs in the
space of a few hours or the dollar loses five per cent of its value
against both the yen and the mark in the space of a week, stability
gives way to crisis. Central banks intervene to buy up threatened
currencies in an attempt to shore up their value.
Central bankers and finance ministers, choosing their words as
carefully as they would pick their way through a minefield, try to
restore calm. Thus yesterday in Washington the Federal Reserve chairman
Alan Greenspan was telling a house committee that the recent fall in the
dollar was unwelcome, troublesome and very likely overdone.
But he was also making it plain that he favours action on the US's
yawning budget deficit, despite last week's one-vote rejection of the
Republican amendment to balance the budget by 2002. Greenspan knows that
the amendment's failure was not well received in the world's currency
markets and is a crucial factor in the dollar's current weakness.
In Frankfurt, the mighty Bundesbank was letting it be known that the
current turbulence is not justified by economic fundamentals. In Rome,
the new Italian Prime Minister was quoting the German finance minister
Theo Waigel -- in turn, apparently, quoting the Bundesbank president
Hans Tietmeyer -- to the effect that there would be no early rise in
German interest rates and that Germany has no interest in seeing the
mark appreciate any further.
To suggest, as popular accounts generally do, that any currency crisis
consists of a flight from currencies perceived as weak into those seen
as safe havens only scratches the surface of the complex dynamics at
work.
The volume of money traded daily on the international currency markets
now swamps the slender resources of central banks. Currency markets,
whether acting on rumour, instinct or a concerted determination to test
the resolve of national institutions to resist them, can and do rule the
roost. Governments can preach calm, but they no longer have it in their
power to deliver order.
The dynamics of the current crisis are intriguing. The currencies in
favour are the mark and the yen, yet Germany and Japan both still face
daunting domestic reconstruction programmes, thanks to reunification on
the one hand and the aftermath of the Kobe earthquake on the other.
And both economies are perceived as favouring employment strategies --
determined adherence to the social chapter provisions of the Maastricht
Treaty in the case of Bonn; a lingering, if threatened, commitment to
cradle-to-grave employer paternalism in the case of Tokyo -- which
undermine competitiveness in global terms.
So why are these the safe havens in the current crisis? Why, if the UK
is now one of the strongest economies in Europe, according to Mr Major
and his ministers, is the pound testing all-time lows against the mark?
Yes, the dynamics of global currency markets can seem deeply perplexing.
One other aspect of the current crisis is worth noting. With two
devaluations and five interest rate rises in a week, the member
currencies of the wide-band ERM, apart from the mark, are having a very
rough time.
The crisis raises yet again the question of whether such a half-way
house between a common European currency and a return to freely floating
national currencies can long survive. If it doesn't, will the drive
towards a common currency be accelerated? And where will that leave
sterling on future roller coaster rides?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
