<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surprise backing for Clause 4 fight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR,PARLIAMENTARYCORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484902</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO of Scotland's leading left- wing MPs surprised colleagues
yesterday by appearing to back Labour leader Tony Blair over his Clause
4 reforms.
On the eve of the Scottish Labour Party conference in Inverness this
weekend, Mr Michael Connarty (Falkirk East) and Mr Malcolm Chisholm
(Edinburgh Leith), both of whom could have been thought to be
hard-liners, threw their weight behind the Labour leader.
The springboard for their remarks was a Westminster meeting of the
Parliamentary Labour Party, at which the vital Clause 4 reforms formed a
key part of the discussion.
The meeting was addressed by Mr Blair before debate was opened up to
test party feeling.
Mr Connarty denied he had changed his line but acknowledged that his
comments may have raised eyebrows.
He said afterwards: ''I am a member of the Campaign for Socialism in
Scotland. People have said this is a kind of 'Save Clause 4' campaign,
but it is not. It says that necessary additions can be put on to Clause
4 and is trying to ensure that the principles of Clause 4 are
maintained.
''I believe the principles will be retained and the argument that if
we put our values first we will win is correct. We are a collective
political force, there to create opportunities and policies to resist
the Government on behalf of the people. We are there to prevent
exploitation and alienation.
Mr Chisholm refused to comment on his remarks to the PLP, at what he
said had been ''a private meeting.'' However Labour sources indicated
that they felt his remarks had been significant.
One said: ''He made clear that what was more important was our
commitment to certain policy areas -- not just what our values were but
what we were actually going to do.
''He did not think Clause 4 was worth fighting for as a form of words.
What was important was giving people the right to employment and a fair
share of the economic cake.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour demands guarantees for railways</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484903</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday urged Scottish Secretary Ian Lang to give specific
guarantees on the future of Scotland's sleeper and motorail services.
The party's demands follow weeks of confusion over the consultative
procedures being adopted by British Rail, which plans to reduce the
services at the end of May.
At the same time, the rail franchising director, Mr Roger Salmon, is
due to set the minimum passenger service requirement for the ScotRail
franchise, but his decisions will not take effect until later this year.
Labour's Shadow Transport Minister Henry McLeish said yesterday that
Mr Lang and Transport Secretary Brian Mawhinney should stop ''hiding
behind the coat-tails'' of rail officials, and take immediate action to
safeguard the services until proper consultation could take place.
He said the Ministers should insist that BR takes bookings for travel
after May; continues the sleeper and motorail services to Fort William
until at least October; and guarantees that no services would be
withdrawn until all consultations are over.
Mr McLeish concluded: ''The Government's rail privatisation plans are
a disaster for Scotland's tourism economy.
''Arguments about the cost of the services are beyond belief from a
Government that has squandered more than #750m so far on privatisation,
and proposes to spend millions more on sweeteners to get this failed
sell-off going. A tiny fraction of this money would keep these services
going for years.''
Meanwhile, Labour is today expected to highlight the dangers of the
Government's decision to privatise BR's occupational health service,
which employs about 75 staff at 10 regional centres, including Glasgow.
Party officials are likely to warn that the move could reduce the
level of drug and alcohol screening of rail staff.
</TEXT>
