<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Still a case of love the sinner but hate gay sin</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARGARET VAUGHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484905</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Margaret Vaughan reports that the churches may preach acceptance of
homosexuals but are still far from accepting gay sex
A FORMER Bishop of Glasgow comes out of the closet. A nurse sacked by
the RAF for being a lesbian wins court permission to challenge the
military authorities' ban on gays. Roman Catholic Cardinal Basil Hume
says love of whatever sexual persuasion is to be treasured and
respected. And along comes the Kirk encouraging its congregations to a
deeper exploration of homosexuality.
So are the bastions of the Establishment, the church and the armed
forces, at last crumbling? Has the gay movement succeeded in breaching
the final bulwarks against acceptance? No, says Ian Dunn. The battered
trumpets will have to keep up the noise for some time yet.
''You can't say, as the churches are doing, we love the person but
don't ever take your pants down. It's an indefensible attitude,'' Ian
Dunn reflects. He has spent 25 years campaigning on gay issues in
Scotland. Now he is an activist with Outright Scotland. For him, the
widening of public debate is welcome but should lead nobody to believe
that the walls of discrimination are tumbling. Eroding, maybe, slightly.
The statement by Cardinal Hume drew a distinction between homosexual
inclination and practice. It has been interpreted in many quarters as a
''softening'' of the Roman Catholic position on homosexuality. Not so,
insists Father Tom Connelly, the press spokesman for Scotland's Cardinal
Thomas Winning.
It merely reiterated Catholic teaching: ''And that is that sexual
activity outwith marriage is always morally wrong, it doesn't matter who
does it.''
Cardinal Hume's statement had been made in response to what he
regarded as a growth in homophobic attitudes and violence against
homosexuals: ''What people are interpreting is a wrongheaded idea that
Catholics regard homosexuals as outcasts. That was never so. The church
is not intolerant. We should never talk about someone being homosexual
or heterosexual. They are persons.''
The statement says: ''Love between two persons, whether of the same
sex or of a different sex, is to be treasured and respected.'' It adds
that homophobia should have no place among Catholics. It goes on,
however, to draw a distinction between inclination and practice.
While Peter Tatchell, of the militant protest group OutRage, regarded
Cardinal Hume's statement as a significant shift, the Rev Richard
Kirker, general secretary of the Lesbian and Gay Christian Movement said
it offered anti-discrimination support only to celibate or
non-practising homosexuals.
Outright Scotland yesterday delivered a letter to Scotland's Cardinal
Winning asking whether he agreed that gay people should be treated with
dignity, respect and fairness and whether he believed such relationships
were always morally inferior to heterosexual marriages, however loveless
or dishonest.
But Ian Dunn is not holding his breath for a positive response: ''We
thought Cardinal Hume's statement was good about 'treasuring', a new
word in the debate. But I am long in the tooth. I don't think there has
been any change whatsoever, and I am not bitter. We will carry on until
the churches agree that sexual orientation is irrelevant and what
matters is whether you are a good or a bad person.''
There is in most mainstream Christian denominations an ambivalence
towards homosexuality. Last year's fiery debate at the Church of
Scotland's General Assembly exposed the fault lines in the Kirk's
thinking.
The Board of Social Responsibility, led by the Rev Bill Wallace,
produced a report which concluded that there was no compelling reason to
alter the church's view that homosexual acts were contrary to God's
will, while deploring prejudice and maltreatment of gays.
A more controversial report by the Panel of Doctrine, which examined
sex outside marriage and homosexual activity, said that love, trust,
forgiveness and faithfulness should be the significant criteria in
assessing relationships.
After a furious debate, a working party was set up to produce
guidelines for discussion by church members. The resultant discussion
document encourages wider and more explicit debate about sexual issues.
If the Assembly approves the document it will go out to congregations
and kirk sessions later this year.
But the Rev Wallace does not believe the broad Kirk view will change,
no matter the talk: ''The church makes a clear distinction between those
with a particular sexual orientation and actual sexual acts. Equally, we
would say promiscuity by heterosexuals is wrong. It is unlikely that the
church will change its position.''
The Episcopal Church in Scotland, meanwhile, is reeling from the
decision by the retired Bishop of Glasgow, the Right Rev Derek
Rawcliffe, to ''come out'' as gay.
The church yesterday offered its support to Bishop Rawcliffe and
emphasised its tolerance of homosexuality, whether within the laity or
the clergy. But privately there was bafflement. As Bishop of Glasgow,
for a decade until 1991, the churchman was regarded as an
arch-conservative on social issues. He vigorously opposed abortion, for
example, joining forces with the fundamentalist Pentecostal Church and
the Free Church of Scotland to condemn changes to the Human
Fertilisation and Embryo Bill.
''Frankly, he was regarded as a bit of a misogynist,'' a senior church
source said. ''He was married and very doctrinaire about all issues,
even, if I recall correctly, homosexuality.''
Now, as assistant bishop in the Ripon diocese, the Right Rev Rawcliffe
is said to be the highest ranking member of the church to admit being
gay. His disclosure came in a BBC interview during which he also
supported blessings for the relationships of gay priests. He says he
came to accept his gayness when he fell in love with a young man while
in the Pacific, where he spent 30 years.
He later married and thought he was no longer gay but realised after
his wife died that he was and always had been homosexual.
There are deep divisions within Anglican ranks about the gay issue.
Hardline evangelics have called for the gay bishop to be expelled. But
the Bishop of Ripon, the Right Rev David Young, said he respected his
assistant's position.
The Archibishop of York, Dr John Habgood, refused to condemn Bishop
Rawcliffe's remarks and acknowledged that the issue of homosexuality was
a ''grey moral area'' for the church. Dr Habgood added it was ''a pity''
that a bishop had chosen to speak out in public on the matter. He
emphasised that the church's position on homosexuality was clear. It is
that gay relationships ''fall short of the Christian ideal'' and require
repentance.
What is so threatening about people of the same sex enjoying emotional
and sexual relationships? If you are in the armed forces, it seems, the
Ministry of Defence believes you can ''cause offence, polarise
relationships, and induce ill-discipline with a resultant damage to
morale and the effectiveness of the unit''.
This, anyway, was the response the MoD gave to Stonewell, the gay
lobbying organisation which backed yesterday's successful move by former
RAF nurse Jeanette Smith. She was given permission by the High Court in
London to bring a challenge against the RAF decision to sack her because
she is a lesbian.
The 28-year-old woman, who lives in Edinburgh, was dismissed last year
after being denounced in an anonymous phone call. She has now been given
leave to seek a judicial review in the first of a series of test cases
being brought against the military authorities on grounds that the ban
on lesbians and gay men is contrary to European anti-discrimination law.
After the hearing yesterday Smith said: ''I'm very happy about the
decision. There are a lot of gays and lesbians out there who are
counting on us -- I did it for myself and for them.''
The Ministry of Defence, meanwhile, has indicated that it will
vigorously defend the long-standing rules banning homosexuals from the
armed forces.
The trumpets had better be polished soon.
</TEXT>
