<HEADLINE>#5000 aid for Scots television project</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING, ENTERTAINMENTS WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484906</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTS-MADE programme which is on the shortlist to replace Channel
Four's Oprah Show is the first project to receive a development loan
from the newly-established Glasgow Television Development Fund.
Elaine With Attitude, a Wark Clements/RPM Arts co-production which
features Elaine C Smith, received #5000 from the fund. It is one of
three contenders for the lucrative C4 afternoon slot, made vacant with
the departure of the Oprah Show to BSkyB.
The loan was used to make a pilot programme. A decision on the
replacement will be made later this year.
Ms Kirsty Wark, who runs Wark Clements with her husband Alan Clements,
said: ''It is absolutely vital for the growth of Scottish television
companies, particularly independents, that we look outside Scotland for
work.''
</TEXT>
