<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gorbachev in unequal fight to make it back to top</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MILLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979484907</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Four years ago he was floundering after a coup: now Gorbachev believes
he is the man to save Russia
TEN years ago this month, Mikhail Gorbachev became general secretary
of the Soviet Communist Party and by ushering in the era of glasnost and
perestroika -- the first Russian words to gain currency in the West
since pogrom -- set out to reform an unreformable system.
Effectively he put the USSR on a course which led after some five
years of great effort and tension to its destruction and the loss of the
Soviet empire.
In Moscow this week Gorbachev, now 64, probably the world's most
celebrated has-been, was cheerfully signalling that, like France's
General De Gaulle, he was still awaiting the call from the people to
save them and the country from chaos, hardship and disaster.
Increasingly critical of Russia's leaders -- especially President
Boris Yeltsin -- and Kremlin policies generally, he is hinting that he
might run for the Duma (Parliament) in elections scheduled for December,
or more likely for presidential elections due to be held next year.
''The Gorbachev era has only just begun,'' he says. ''Gorbachev is not
history. He hasn't gone. He hasn't sold out. He is not Judas. He is
still very important. Many do not want him to take part in elections. He
finds that encouraging.''
It is not surprising that Gorbachev apparently believes he could still
make some kind of a political comeback to complement his post as head of
an economic think-tank with international links.
In his day he was a brilliant manoeuvrer, compromiser (and, if
necessary, boot-licker), a politician keenly aware of the art of the
possible. And he grasps that 10 years after he let the genie out of the
bottle, the Russian political scene is a shambles, a combination of the
apocalyptic and the absurd, with every major political event promising
Armageddon before almost inevitably proving to be muddled, confused and
bizarre.
Following the Chechnya debacle, the rampant inflation and the
breakdown in law and order symbolised by the contract killing of a
television star turned executive, Yeltsin's popularity has slumped
markedly.
His most recent appearances in public, usually complete with a puffy
face and glazed eyes -- almost certainly a combination of alcohol and
pills -- have only emphasised the deterioration in his physical
condition since he snatched power from a shattered, broken Gorbachev
some three years ago.
Nor is Yeltsin's chief political rival doing much better in the
popularity polls. Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the outlandish ultra-nationalist
who became an international bogeyman after his Liberal Democratic
Party's election successes, is sounding increasingly frustrated and
lunatic at his marginal role in Russian politics.
Seizing any opportunity to grab attention, he recently paid a courtesy
call on Saddam Hussein in his Baghdad bunker. He also came out in
support of Yeltsin in the Chechnya conflict, adding that the Kremlin
should have gone even further by flattening Grozny, the capital and
leaving a huge ''crater''.
Zhirinovsky uses crude language to dismiss Gorbachev and the liberal
communists who a decade ago sought to preserve much of the old system,
but to modernise it by introducing some elements of democracy through
glasnost and perestroika.
Gorbachev he describes as a ''spotted reformer . . . who managed to
rape the entire country''. Yegor Gaidar, the former prime minister and
reformist trailblazer whose party was favoured by Yeltsin in the last
elections, is written off as a ''rabid economist'', easily identified by
his ''piggy lip-smacking''.
Zhirinovsky has proved a master media manipulator and although it is
about time the Russian electorate saw through him as a demagogue and
fascist, it is hard to rule him out as a serious contender in next
year's presidential race. But it is difficult to see ''that nice Mr
Gorbachev'' slugging it out in the same political ring as ''Mad Vlad''
and Boris Yeltsin.
For the past three years Yeltsin and his Kremlin aides have been doing
their best to cut Gorbachev down to size, stripping him of the last
remnants of his former power and removing his perks -- such as an office
in the Kremlin, a VIP Zil limousine, and an official telephone.
Last week when Gorbachev returned to Moscow from an economic seminar
in Siberia he learned that the Kremlin, in another remarkable exercise
in pettiness and spite, had also removed his modest Volga car. In fact,
when the Kremlin's bullying was exposed in the Russian press, the car
was returned -- a small victory perhaps for Mikhail Gorbachev,but not
one that was going to get him very far politically.
Gorbachev is fighting an unequal battle with his former protege. He
talks about the necessity of electing ''a fresh force headed by very
experienced leaders who do not deceive the people'', which presumably
means he has himself in mind as one of those determining Russia's
future.
Gorbachev's problem is that for millions of Russians the story of
their country over the past 10 years has been one of unremitting loss
and injured pride. He became the laughing stock of the nation when his
closest colleagues and friends staged their coup against him in 1991.
Above all he is not likely to be able to represent a real alternative
to Yeltsin who, despite everything, genuinely wants Russia to go into
the next century with a market economy, a democratic political system
and a civil society.
Gorbachev and Yeltsin have something else in common. They have both
learned the truth of words written by an eighteenth-century Russian,
Ivan Pososhkov, about the task facing Peter the Great in trying to drag
his country into the modern age. For Pososhkov wrote: ''The Czar pulls
uphill with the strength of a hundred men. But millions pull downhill.''
Yet they still want to be Czar.
</TEXT>
