<HEADLINE>MP lists contracts going outside NHS Private sector's feet 'under the operating table'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484908</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH boards in Scotland were accused yesterday of ''propping up''
private hospitals to the tune of #4.69m over the past six years.
The Cunninghame South MP, Mr Brian Donohoe, said the figure
demonstrated ''the thin end of the wedge'' that was being driven into
the operation of the 15 health boards.
He sought the information after last week's announcement by Ayrshire
and Arran Health Board that it was sending 23 cardiac surgery patients
to Ross Hall Hospital in Glasgow at a cost of #200,000.
Only three boards -- Western Isles, Orkney, and Shetland -- indicated
that they had made no use of the private hospitals for acute medical
services in the six years up to the end of last year.
Greater Glasgow Health Board accounted for the bulk of the expenditure
-- #3.86m out of the total. Among his findings were that Ross Hall had
received a total of nearly #3m worth of business from five boards --
Greater Glasgow (#2.6m), Argyll and Clyde (#267,525), Forth Valley
(#15,000), Lothian (#25,833), and Lanarkshire (#14,000).
Other private hospitals which had serviced NHS contracts included the
Glasgow Nuffield (#535,702 from 1991-94), the St John Hospital, Aberdeen
(#97,982 in 1993-94), the Fernbrae Clinic in Dundee (#15,365 in
1993-95), the Murrayfield in Edinburgh (#406,749 in 1990-95), and the
Moat Brae in Dumfries (#42,500 in 1991-94).
The largest single contract was awarded to Ross Hall by Greater
Glasgow, for a total of #1.36m covering 80 plastic surgery, 19 urology,
and 180 cardiac surgery patients.
Grampian was the only Scottish board to indicate it had made use of
HCI in Clydebank by the end of last year, for the treatment of eight
oral surgery patients, but no cost was given.
Mr Donohoe said that there was increasing pressure on health boards to
opt for private treatment as a result of the Patient's Charter.
''No-one could argue with patients being guaranteed that they will not
have to wait long periods for medical treatment, but these figures
reveal that, due to a lack of financial resources, many health boards
are opting for cut-price treatment in the private sector rather than
being able to meet the need from NHS resources themselves.
''It is clear that many private hospitals are looking at NHS business
as a means of reducing their costs and getting their feet under the
operating tables of the NHS with a view to expanding their business.
''If the Government made available the necessary level of resources
then there would be no need for the NHS patients to be faced with the
choice of going private or not receiving the treatment they desperately
need.''
A Scottish Health Department spokesman said: ''This figure of #4m or
so is not a huge proportion of our overall annual budget of some #4000m.
We are not going to deny someone the opportunity to get treatment
quickly if the private sector can give us a good deal and reduce the
waiting list.''
</TEXT>
