<HEADLINE>Disciplinary hearing for train attack policeman</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484911</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN off-duty policeman fined for punching a teenager -- overheard
telling friends he would like to throw the officer's baby out of a train
window -- is to face a disciplinary hearing, it was disclosed yesterday.
But the decision to fine Constable Richard King, trained to protect
the royal family and senior politicians, has provoked a storm of public
outrage.
Mr King, 30, who was a member of the City of London's tactical
firearms unit, was transferred to a desk job after being accused of the
assault against Mr David Hobbs on a train in June last year.
Southend magistrates found him guilty of common assault and fined him
#150 on Tuesday.
Mr King, of South Benfleet, Essex, has not been suspended from work
but it is not known if he will be reinstated to the unit if the hearing
finds in his favour. He could be sacked if it finds against him.
Mr Charlie Owen, City of London police spokesman, said the
disciplinary hearing would be conducted by the force's Commissioner
William Taylor.
''I have no idea when the inquiry will take place because it cannot
start before next week because the commissioner is away from the City,''
he said.
''It's very usual in this sort of case because when an officer is
convicted of an offence in a court of law there is an automatic inquiry.
This and other offices have been inundated with calls from members of
the public showing their support for PC King.
''If people feel very strongly we are encouraging them to put pen to
paper to express their opinions to the commissioner. There have been
some very strong views on the subject.''
Mr King's MP, Tory Robert Spink, said: ''The public must rise up and
make their opinions known so that PC King does not suffer any further.''
Sir Teddy Taylor, MP for Southend East, added: ''Surely if one's baby
is threatened one has to respond with force and vigour. One can't very
well call in the forces of law and order on the train and it would seem
to me that the decision of the father was exactly the kind of action I
would take myself.''
But Mr Hobbs, now 19, and also from South Benfleet, told the court:
''I made the remark to my friend. PC King was not meant to hear it. I
had no intention of throwing the baby out of the window.''
</TEXT>
