<HEADLINE>Councils take on Major over subsidiarity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, EUROPEAN EDITOR BRUSSELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484912</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRIME Minister John Major's doctrine that European subsidiarity --
devolution from Brussels -- stops in London is to be challenged formally
by British local authorities.
Mr Charles Gray, leader of the 24-strong UK delegation to the EU's
Committee of the Regions (CoR), said yesterday in Brussels that British
local authorities wanted legal recognition of their role in devolved
administration written into Maastricht when the treaty is revised at
next year's inter-governmental conference.
Mr Gray, former leader of Strathclyde Regional Council, denied this
was an attempt by local authorities in Britain to bypass Westminster
routinely in their dealings with Brussels. He agreed, however, that he
wanted councils to have power to challenge Westminster in the European
Court of Justice.
Such a power would be invoked in cases where the central government
ignored the subsidiarity principle at the expense of ''non-central''
government in the UK.
A group from the British local government international bureau,
representing local councils with European connections, earlier held
talks with Sir Leon Brittan, one of the UK's European Commissioners.
They explained that British local government wanted subsidiarity more
clearly defined.
''The existing definition only covers relations between the nation
states and the European Union -- a wider definition is needed to
encompass all levels of government,'' the delegation told the
Commissioner in a written briefing.
Sir Leon did not offer his blessing for the idea, Mr Gray said, but
said he would consider it.
Mr Gray was talking to reporters as the CoR prepares its input to the
Maastricht review when it will demand more powers and a divorce from the
non-elected Economic and Social Committee of the EU.
He said that the CoR had dropped reported ambitions to become a second
chamber of the European Parliament. But the idea that it could become an
EU institution will be discussed in Montpellier at the weekend.
</TEXT>
