<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>English fear factor delays Perth by-election</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER,POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484913</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister has decided to delay holding the Perth and Kinross
by-election until after the Scottish local elections on April 6.
He and his advisers are believed to have been influenced by the impact
a month later on English local elections -- where the Tories have their
backs to the wall -- if the party was to lose the Scottish seat .
Mr Major's future could be at stake if the Conservatives lose as badly
in the English poll as already has been forecast. The prospect of a
challenge to his leadership in the autumn would be enhanced if the party
was to slump into third place with fewer councillors than the Liberal
Democrats.
The Prime Minister is understood to have consulted national party
chairman Mr Jeremy Hanley, as well as the Scottish chairman, Sir Michael
Hirst, and Scottish Secretary Ian Lang.
Conservative Central Office officials argued that it would have a
demoralising effect on the English campaign if the party were to sustain
a spectacular by-election defeat the previous month.
A later date has not yet been settled. However, it could be early May,
at the same time as the English local elections, or later that month,
which would enable the Tories to use their annual Scottish conference,
held from May 10 to 12, as a launching pad for their campaign.
Mr Major and his advisers have sacrificed the advantage an April 6
poll would have given them of hindering the SNP from bussing in large
numbers of party workers from other areas.
However, national issues are likely to feature strongly in the
elections to the newly created councils and that would have strongly
influenced the Perth and Kinross campaign and vote.
The indications are that the Tories will prefer to concentrate their
campaign on the constitutional issue, attacking the SNP on separatism
and Labour on its devolution proposals.
Party sources claim to be relaxed about the possible appearance of a
Unionist candidate who would aim to reflect the frustration felt by
supporters of Ulster Unionists who are concerned at the trend of
Government policy in Northern Ireland.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said: ''The Tories are so
divided among themselvs they don't dare to face the electorate.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond said ''They can run but they can't hide. They
can play it as long as they like they are still going to be beaten.''
Sir Michael said that in deference to Sir Nicholas's family it was
felt ''inappropriate'' to hold the by-election so soon after his death
on February 19.
He said to fight the by-election simulataneously with the important
local elections would have deflected the party from concentrating on the
local issues.
He added that whenever the writ was moved ''the Scottish Conservative
and Unionist party will fight a positive campaign maintaining our
staunch defence of the Union.''
The Tories have already selected Mr John Godfrey, a London-based
banker, though with Highland roots, as prospective candidate. The
Scottish Nationalists, regarded as favourites to win the seat, choose
their candidate tonight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Monk on trial in paternity case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484914</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
From ANDREW DRUMMOND
Bangkok, Wednesday
UPPORTERS of a Thai Buddhist monk, who allegedly bedded his female
followers and visited sex clubs, screamed obscenities and threw bags of
water and itching powder over his critics as he appeared before a
religious court to answer charges today.
However the supporters of Phra Yantra Amaro Bhikku were drowned out by
loud cheers as a 10-year-old girl clutching a tin of sweets, who claims
the monk is her father, was led into the hearing.
The monk has been accused of sleeping with his followers and using an
American Express charge card to visit sex clubs in New Zealand and
Australia. He has refused to take a DNA test to prove whether or not he
is the girl's father.
At the hearing in Bangkok against the monk, who has been accused of
sleeping with a nun on the deck of a cruise liner in the Baltic Sea,
with another follower in the back of a van in Austria, and with a Danish
harpist in Copenhagen, the girl's mother gave evidence of her nights
with him while he was on a tour of Europe.
Reporters were not allowed into the religious trial at a Buddhist
temple in Bangkok.
Meanwhile the Supreme Patriarch, the head of Buddhism in Thailand, has
expressed concern about the adverse effects of the case on Buddhism and
the clergy.
At each hearing the temple is cordoned off by police. At an earlier
inquiry two women accusers of the monk were attacked by a mob and had to
be treated in hospital, while another monk who saw the incident said:
'The women would have become corpses we not intervened.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Architecture winner announced</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484915</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE winner of a #20m architectural project for Edinburgh was announced
yesterday amid uncertainty when it would be built and how it would be
funded.
The London firm of Benson and Forsyth won the #8500 first prize for a
design to redevelop Edinburgh's Cowgatehead area and extend the city's
Central Library.
But Councillor Lesley Hinds, leader of Edinburgh District Council,
said that no money was available in the council's capital programme and
the Government had changed the rules for capital receipts. She hoped,
however, that the new Edinburgh council would take the project on.
The scheme to remodel and extend the Central Library to meet the needs
of the 21st century includes a children's cultural centre.
The 150 entries were narrowed to a final ll. Glen Craig Architects, of
Edinburgh, took the #7000 second prize. Third place (#6000) went to Paul
Stallan and Nick Blair, of Glasgow, and fourth place (#5500) was shared
by McGill, Granger, and Thain, of London, and Alonso and Hernandez, of
Pamplona, Spain.
</TEXT>
