<HEADLINE>Town set to get spy cameras</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484916</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAISLEY town centre is set to get closed circuit spy cameras in a
tough bid to increase security and stamp out crimes of violence for
good.
The cost will be almost #250,000.
Councillors yesterday approved the project after hearing that 30 local
businesses, including shops and pubs and banks, were prepared to support
the plan with sums ranging from #100 to #2000.
Renfrew District Council and Renfrewshire Enterprise are each to
donate #45,000 towards the set-up costs and officials are hoping that
Strathclyde Regional Council will make a similar sum available.
Proposals to provide CCTV surveillance equipment backed up with a
24-hour monitoring team have been on the cards since the town was hit by
a wave of violence in 1992.
Licensing chiefs were so concerned about the rise in crime that a
curfew was introduced restricting access to licensed premises after
11pm. Several late-opening night clubs also had their licensing hours
cut back.
The curbs helped to reduce dramatically the number of crimes involving
offensive weapons.
</TEXT>
