<HEADLINE>Leaked paper suggests Tory Euro tactic to fight SNP</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER,POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484917</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
A LEAKED Cabinet Office paper suggests the Government should argue for
a cut in the number of European Commissioners at the EU summit next
year, pointing out that it would help in Ministers' constitutional
battle with the SNP.
The paper, prepared for the guidance of the Prime Minister and the
Foreign Secretary, Mr Douglas Hurd, notes the right of every smaller
state to have a Commissioner has been used by the Scottish National
Party to argue an independent Scotland would have more influence in the
EU than in Britain.
However, SNP leader Alex Salmond said: ''This document is unequivocal
proof that the Government secretly accepts the undoubted appeal to Scots
of independence in Europe. They are now threatening a battle against all
small nations which could seriously damage the coherence of the EU. That
battle is a Tory battle, not a British one and still less a Scottish
one.''
The paper states: ''The prospects of loss of influence for the smaller
states would therefore have implications in the constitutional debate to
the advantage of the Government's presentation of the case for the
Union.''
It adds that a similar advantage would be gained if there was a cut in
the number of votes smaller states have on EU matters decided by
qualified majority voting, but concedes this would be harder to put
across in debate ''given the difficulties with public understanding of
QMV''.
Mr Salmond added: ''The Tories are terrified of Europe. This leaked
paper shows that they are also scared stiff of the SNP and Scotland.
Their reluctance to face the electorate in Perth and Kinross is ample
proof of that.
''The Government's entire approach to Europe is based on their own
narrow partisan advantage. Developments in both Scotland and Europe are
squeezing the Westminster system out and Westminster is in a panic.
''The Tories are not only anti-Scottish but are anti every one of 10
small member states of the EU. Two-thirds of the EU's member state are
small nations like Scotland and they all benefit enormously from their
independence in Europe.
''The right to appoint a Commissioner is one such benefit. Another is
having a fair number of seats in the Parliament. But the biggest
advantage is direct representation in the Council of Ministers.''
The Government's anxiety about its position in Scotland again comes to
the fore when the paper questions the advantage of giving the European
Parliament control over the details of spending on the Common
Agricultural Policy.
Ministers had appeared favourable to this as a means of further
reducing spending on CAP, which is seen as a source of extensive fraud
in the EU.
However, the paper says: ''It is by no means a foregone conclusion''
that this ''would be in our interests since the areas in which CAP
savings were made might adversely affect Scotland''. It suggests
Ministers sound ''a note of caution''.
The paper also questions another policy which has been widely popular
within the Conservative Party -- negotiating for national parliaments to
be given an enhanced role in scrutinising EU policy. It points out that
it would be desirable to ''tread carefully'' as many other EU
parliaments are ''significantly more integrationist than Westminster''.
