<DOCNO>GH950309-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Euro-visa brings Tory protest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484919</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was planning to approve today a visa symbol for use by
all EU countries without first having the issue debated in the Commons,
whipless Tory Euro-rebel Sir Teddy Taylor protested yesterday.
The move would effectively be ''the beginning of the end of border
controls'', he warned. Raising a point of order, Sir Teddy (Southend
East), said a common-format visa bearing a Euro-symbol would ''lead
inevitably to the mutual recognition of Euro-visas''.
He said Commons Leader Tony Newton had written only on Tuesday to the
European Instruments Select Committee saying that, while he thought
there was a case for debate, it could not take place now but might take
place later in a European standing committee.
''However, I have been advised that a specific proposal to establish
such visas is to be considered at the council of home affairs Ministers
in Brussels tomorrow and it has been reported, rightly or wrongly, that
the UK Home Office Minister will agree to it,'' Sir Teddy said.
The meeting is to be attended by Home Office Minister of State Michael
Forsyth.
PEERS called on the Government yesterday to seek a cross-party
alliance on Europe and play a positive role at next year's key EU
inter-governmental conference.
Liberal Democrat peers' leader Lord Jenkins of Hillhead called for the
return of a cross-party alliance on Europe, which he said in 1971 had
supported the-then Tory Prime Minister Sir Edward Heath in talks on EC
membership and in 1975 had led to the ''overwhelming'' referendum
decision in favour of Britain joining the Community.
Tory former Foreign Secretary Lord Howe of Aberavon urged the
Government to play a role ''not of reluctance but of commitment -- our
future isn't to be found by turning our backs on our European
partners''.
Labour former Prime Minister Lord Callaghan said Mr Major was ''quite
unconvincing'' when he suggested a Labour government would ''give
everything away to Brussels''.
He said the Prime Minister portraying himself as John Bull ''didn't
suit him -- he really ought to give it up''.
</TEXT>
