<HEADLINE>White House outraged by Karachi killings</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484920</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Wednesday
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton expressed outrage over an attack in Pakistan
that killed two US consulate workers and wounded a third today. He vowed
that the United States would help track down the attackers.
However White House officials said the attack, one of the first to
target foreigners in Pakistan's violence-prone commercial capital of
Karachi, would not change Hillary Rodham Clinton's plans to visit
Pakistan later this month during a visit to South Asia.
''The attack on American diplomatic personnel in Pakistan outrages all
Americans,'' said Clinton. ''I have instructed relevant US government
agencies to work with the government of Pakistan to apprehend the
perpetrators of this cowardly act.''
He added: ''Attacks such as these should make the international
community rededicate itself to efforts to stamp out terrorism
everywhere.''
The State Department said the Americans were killed when a consulate
shuttle bus carrying them to work this morning was ambushed by at least
one man armed with an AK-47 assault rifle.
The shuttle had stopped at a traffic light on a main road when at
least one gunman leapt from a nearby taxi, shot out the windscreen, and
sprayed the van, hitting all three Americans, it said. The Pakistani
driver was unhurt.
The consulate had heightened security because of a spiral of violence
in Karachi in recent months, said spokeswoman Christine Shelly.
''The consulate bus appears to have been deliberately targeted, which
indicates that this was a terrorist attack,'' she said, adding that
Pakistani authorities had stepped up security for consulate personnel.
She said the Federal Bureau of Investigation was sending a team of
forensic investigators to Karachi and the State Department's Bureau of
Diplomatic Security was sending personnel to boost security at the
consulate in Karachi and the embassy in Islamabad.
The dead were identified as Gary Durell, 45, a communications
technician, and Jackie Van Landingham, 33, a consulate secretary. The
third victim, Mark McCloy, who worked in the consulate's mailroom, was
wounded and in stable condition in hospital.
There was speculation that the attack might have been linked to
Pakistan's arrest and extradition to the US last month of Ramzi Ahmed
Yousef to stand trial for organising the 1993 World Trade Centre bombing
in New York.
The White House said that remained open to question, but McCurry said
Americans were being advised to ''exercise prudent security precautions
in the region surrounding Karachi''.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
