<HEADLINE>Queen to visit Belfast and Armagh</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484922</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Queen is expected to visit Northern Ireland today to open a bridge
across the River Lagan in Belfast and to restore city status to Armagh,
the ecclesiastical capital of Ireland.
Notwithstanding the IRA ceasefire, a major security operation is being
mounted at both venues where the Queen is expected to meet many local
people.
Despite a week of rumours and newspaper reports, no public
confirmation of the royal visit is expected from the Northern Ireland
Office until the Queen has arrived.
Belfast councillors, including the 10 from Sinn Fein, have not been
invited to the opening of the multi-million pound Lagan Bridge. The
Unionist Lord Mayor, Mr Hugh Smyth, will represent the council.
Sinn Fein president Mr Gerry Adams was dismissive of the visit last
night. He said: ''This is very much a local thing. I would not even be
that concerned. Mrs Windsor can come and go as she wants. Our people
will deal with that at the appropriate level.
''We don't actually have a department which deals with the Windsor
family.''
The one Sinn Fein member of Armagh council, Mr Noel Sheridan, is
expected to boycott the visit to the city despite an invitation which is
understood to have been issued to councillors to attend the ceremony.
However, the Queen is expected to meet both the Church of Ireland
Primate, Archbishop Robin Eames, and the Catholic Primate, Cardinal
Cahal Daly, during her visit to Armagh, where she will open a school.
Thirty years ago, the Queen visited Belfast to open another bridge
just 100 yards up the River Lagan, and her official Rolls-Royce was
damaged when a member of the public hurled a brick from the fourth floor
of a building she was passing.
With the outbreak of the violence, it was thought too dangerous for
her to visit the province and it was not until her jubilee tour of the
nation in 1977 that she returned -- missing out Belfast. Even then, a
bomb exploded in the grounds of the Ulster University in Coleraine,
County Londonderry, shortly after she left.
A further 14 years were to pass before she returned in 1991. Two years
later, she visited again to hold a garden party for 1200 people at
Hillsborough Castle,
</TEXT>
