<HEADLINE>Loch Lomond, once the exile's nostalgic ideal, has become Britain's biggest speedboat free-for-all</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484923</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jim Freeman unveils by-law plans which aim make the banks bonnie
again.
LOCH Lomond, once an international byword for tranquil beauty -- the
exile's nostalgic Scottish ideal -- but in reality the biggest speedboat
free-for-all left in Britain, is about to undergo a revolution.
For the first time, the ever-growing ranks of pleasure boaters are to
have their behaviour governed by by-laws in an effort to preserve what
is left of the tattered environment of Scotland's best-known natural
landmark and to impose sanity on the loch's 30 square miles of water.
But for many lovers of the bonnie banks, the by-laws package devised
by Loch Lomond Park Authority comes far too late and is too weak. Their
great sadness is that the concept of tranquillity and peaceful enjoyment
has not been the central pillar of the structure.
Instead, a compromise will be put in place before summer so the
speedboat cowboys, the water skiers and the jet bikers will still,
unless they voluntarily change their behaviour overnight, be able to
rampage unhindered over 90% of the water, encouraged to do so by a speed
limit of 50 knots.
On the face of it, there is little to curb the jet skiers who have in
recent years been seen deliberately harrying young shelducks, running
them down until these beautiful birds have been driven off the island
shores where they were once commonly seen.
The water-ski boats which chased and decapitated swans in Luss Bay and
Net Bay will still be on the loch. The speedboat thugs who deliberately
cut the lines of fishermen and have tried to swamp the small boats of
elderly pensioners who have fished the loch for a lifetime, still have
licence to carry on.
That is the down side. The other side is that, according to Mr Nick
Pennington, park officer for the authority, a significant start has been
made, a foundation laid on which it may yet build.
''The pressure for by-laws started about five years ago when we began
getting requests to do something about the behaviour of speedboat
owners, water skiers and jet skiers. The pressure came from residents
around the loch, from individuals at places like Duck Bay, Luss and
Millarochy Bay, residents of caravan sites and people working around the
loch who faced daily and nightly disturbance and noise and physical
pollution.''
He adds: ''The complaints eventually centred on people water skiing
and jet skiing from 5am until midnight. The park authority became the
focus for examining what could be done. It was a major turnaround,
because when I first came to Loch Lomond, the message I was getting
about regulation was 'over my dead body'.''
The radical change in attitude came, says Mr Pennington, with the
advent of the jet ski and it happened in six months. Since the first
survey of craft was carried out five years ago, the number of boats has
remained roughly the same.
There has been a swing, however, from sailing boats and low-powered
craft to fast, high-powered boats, says Mr Pennington. The view around
the loch is that the speedboats are driving out, not only the wildlife,
but also those who seek peaceful and gentle enjoyment.
Taking the initiative, the park authority -- drawn from the four local
authorities around the Loch -- brought together all the key players,
ranging from the police to the water-ski clubs and the commercial
interests which benefit from the current set-up.
There was input from the Marine Safety Agency and from Scottish Office
lawyers, only for the whole idea to come unstuck because of inadequate
legislation.
The Countryside Act could only apply if the park authority had owned
or controlled all the loch. But it was reckoned that at least 122 people
around the bonnie banks had a proprietorial interest and, under the
weaker Civic Government (Scotland) Act, any one objector could kill off
the by-law plan.
In the event, six objectors brought matters to a grinding halt.
It was left to the Scottish Office to ride to the rescue -- after
considerable public pressure, much of it through this newspaper -- and
an amendment was pushed through Parliament removing the right of veto
and giving discretion to the Secretary of State.
The considerable public support which emerged was reinforced by a
sheriff who presided over the fatal accident inquiry into the death of a
young woman, killed in a collision between two speedboats off Inchmurrin
island.
The two local authorities directly concerned, Dumbarton and Stirling
district councils duly drafted the by-laws, which now await the
endorsement of the Scottish Office. The Herald has been told that the
Scottish Office environment department is ''doing everything it can'' to
have the by-laws in place for summer.
Every boat with an engine will thereafter have to be registered with
the park authority before it can take to the water and, when it does, it
will have to display a registration number.
As with a car, if ownership is transferred, the park authority must be
notified. The owner and master will have clear responsibilities for the
vessel's conduct.
The sea-going collision rules have been adopted wholesale, which means
that every boat on the loch with an engine must carry and display lights
after dark, sound a horn at regular intervals in bad visibility, and
adhere rigidly to the rules of the sea when vessels are approaching each
other on collision course.
Reckless navigation is an offence, as is drunken navigation. Young
people under 14 cannot drive a power boat unless under supervision.
Perhaps most important, and possibly the most contentious aspect, will
be the speed limits. Around the 100 miles of shoreline, powered boats
will be restricted to six knots -- 7mph -- when they are within 150
metres of the shore. There are exceptions around hotels, clubs and
marinas used by water skiers and jet skiers -- both of which activities
appear to require an audience to give them any point.
Areas of the loch which have been the focus of intense activity in the
past have been specially regulated. The Narrows, the area embraced by
the islands of Inchcruin, Inchmoan and Inchconnachan, are all
restricted.
Much favoured by families because of the sheltered water and sandy
beaches, the danger from irresponsible water and jet skiing had become
serious in recent summers. With speedboats carving through enclosed
water where children were swimming or playing, many feared that this
would be the site of the loch's first major tragedy.
Similarly, an imaginary line has been drawn from Ross Priory on the
bottom shore to Balmaha Pier, leaving the entire area of Endrick Mouth
with its national nature reserve, Aber Island and Net Bay as a
speed-free zone. This is an area where holidaymakers have witnessed the
hunting down and decapitation of swans, and where ospreys have sought to
hunt on the wide shallows.
In some other especially-sensitive areas, including the River Leven,
Fruinmouth and the mouth of the Endrick, speed is to be determined by
wake height, the master of each boat ensuring that his vessel will leave
a wake no higher than eight inches. This is partly for safety reasons in
restricted passageways and partly to cut erosion, allowing plants such
as the loch's wild water lillies to regenerate.
Outside the 150-metre mark and in the unrestricted areas, power boats
will be allowed to travel at 50 knots. The idea is to force the noise,
the danger and the physical pollution, particularly from water and jet
skiers, further offshore.
The areas left uncontrolled were the result of hard lobbying by the
water-ski interests and their business friends on the loch shores, who
argued for some sheltered areas where they could go in poor weather.
Water-ski boats will be forced to carry a driver and an observer to
convey the skier's signals to the navigator. The boat must also be
equipped with a rear-view mirror and a maximum of two skiers at a time
can be towed.
The laws specifically state that no water skier shall ski in a manner
which would annoy other boat users or members of the public and no water
skier should ski while under the influence of drink or drugs.
Parascending, a sport involving massively-engined boats which had
appeared on the loch in the last two summers, is banned without specific
authority and another pastime, towing ''ringos'', ''biscuits'' or
''bananas'' is restricted to 15 knots.
Loch Lomond's anglers, the oldest group on the water and --
ironically, since it has done more to preserve the loch than anyone else
-- the group which has suffered most from the increased disturbance,
also face regulation.
Few remain out after dark, but those who do will have to display
lights, and those practising the art of trolling, trailing salmon lures
behind their boat, will have to display an orange buoy or disc to warn
other users of the trailing lines.
Are the by-laws too timorous and will they be ignored by yobs and
cowboys? Mr Pennington is hopeful that they will not.
''It is a compromise. This is the first time there has been any
management on the loch, and to have tried to impose more controls at
this stage might have been counter-productive, leading to the whole
exercise failing. It is a base on which we can build in the future, but
let us first see that it works.
''I hope people do not think that everything is going to be regulated
to the last inch. It will be kept under review, but this is an
experiment which should make users recognise the potential dangers and
make them aware of the need to behave carefully in their own interest
and that of others.''
Advertisments for Loch Lomond's first water-borne rangers were placed
this week. The park authority has settled on a patrol boat which can
also be used as a work boat for laying buoys. It will not be used by the
rangers to chase miscreants.
''Had we wanted that, we would have gone for a boat capable of 60 or
70 knots,'' says Mr Pennington, ''but we are not an arm of the police.
The police will advise us on training, but we want to advise and help
people enjoy the loch in a safe and responsible way.''
Water-ski boats
which chased and
decapitated
swans will still
be on the loch
The idea is to
force the noise,
the danger and
physical pollution
further offshore
</TEXT>
