<HEADLINE>Peer's move on succession fails</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484924</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HEREDITARY peer failed in the Lords last night to gain support for
his backbench Bill which would have ensured his son was not denied the
right to inherit his title.
Peers backed by 46 votes to 14, a majority of 32, a wrecking amendment
to stop Lord Kilmarnock's Legitimated Persons (Succession to Titles)
Bill getting a second reading.
The measure would have allowed a male child to succeed his father even
where his parents had married after his birth.
Under the current rules of succession, Lord Kilmarnock's son is unable
to inherit his title because he was born out of wedlock -- even though
his birth was subsequently legitimated. The crossbench peer married his
wife five years after the birth of their son, now 23.
Lord Kilmarnock, whose title dates from 1831, told the House that his
measure was ''modest'' and cited historical precedents where patents
conferring peerages had been varied.
However, Tory Lord Morris, opposing the Bill, warned it would ''cause
chaos''.
He claimed that was why it was supported by lawyers who he said would
get so much work out of it.
Fellow Tory Viscount Oxfuird protested the Bill would have ''severe
consequences'', particularly as it would act retrospectively.
Baroness Trumpington, for the Government, said Ministers remained
neutral on Private Members' Bills but she made clear a number of
shortcomings in Lord Kilmarnock's measure which she said had been
explained to him by the Lord Chancellor, Lord Mackay of Clashfern.
The Queen had given her consent for peers to debate the Bill as it
would have required changes in the laws of succession to peerages. The
royal family would not have been affected by the measure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Controversial Cosla chief official to quit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH,LOCAL GOVERNMENTCORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484925</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE chief official of the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities, Mr
Roy MacIver, is to retire at the age of 52.
Mr MacIver told delegates on the first day of Cosla's annual
conference in Dunblane that after almost 10 years he planned to give up
the post of secretary general which is to be advertised at a salary of
around #80,000 a year.
He denied his decision was anything to do with the criticism of his
running of the convention's headquarters in Edinburgh contained in an
independent report a year ago.
The report by Strathclyde Regional Council's chief executive Neil
McIntosh was commissioned after some Cosla staff had complained of
sexual harassment and bullying.
Mr MacIver was not the subject of the complaints but his ''hands-off''
management style was criticised in the report which found shortcomings
in the internal communications at Cosla headquarters.
In all, Mr McIntosh made 16 recommendations about changing the way the
convention was administered and some senior councillors at the time
accepted privately that the situation had damaged Mr MacIver's position.
Mr MacIver admitted yesterday that he had found last year ''extremely
difficult''. But he added: ''If I felt the report had affected my
position, I would have announced my departure long before now.''
He said his decision to retire came in the context of the changes
which would be taking place both internally within Cosla and in local
government re-organisation as a whole.
Cosla's Labour president, Councillor Rosemary McKenna, said Mr MacIver
had been instrumental in developing policy in key areas in Scotland and
had made an extremely valuable contribution to local government and
Cosla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bank dealer may co-operate with Serious Fraud Office to win extradition to Britain Leeson 'being made a scapegoat'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484926</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
dealer Mr Nick Leeson claimed yesterday that he is being made a
scapegoat by people seeking to divert blame for the collapse of Barings.
They raised the possibility that they might co-operate with the
Serious Fraud Office to build a case for extradition to London in order
to avoid Mr Leeson being sent for trial in Singapore.
''The reporting so far has not even scratched the surface of matters
which went on within the bank and the management of the bank,'' Mr
Leeson's British lawyer, Mr Stephen Pollard, told a news conference in
Frankfurt.
''Everyone seems very concerned to focus the blame on Mr Leeson.
That's neither accurate nor fair.''
Mr Pollard said: ''Everything he did, he did as an employee of
Barings, he did for Barings Bank and hoping it would be to the advantage
of Barings. There's no suggestion that there was any personal gain to Mr
Leeson.''
He conceded that the possibilities of fighting Singapore's extradition
request were ''strictly limited'' under German law.
But he added: ''If there were an extradition request from England,
that would open up all sorts of alternatives to an extradition to
Singapore. It's certainly our best hope.''
Mr Leeson's German lawyer, Mr Eberhard Kempf, said they might seek to
help build a case for Mr Leeson's extradition for trial in Britain.
''It's not an ordinary procedure to try to get an extradition request
for a client but this isn't an ordinary case. If we felt he's going to
be extradited to Singapore we would definitely prefer him to go to
London.''
Mr Pollard said Mr Leeson, 28, had given them ''very interesting
information about what was going on in the bank'' at the time of the
crash and the period leading up to it.
They might offer help to the SFO ''if it were sought''.
Mr Pollard said he had spent five to six hours with Mr Leeson on
Tuesday and yesterday in Hoechst Prison, Frankfurt, where he is being
held without bail while Singapore puts together its extradition case.
''He's calm, he hasn't lost his sense of humour, he's confident, he's
coping very well with his imprisonment.
He dismissed reports that Mr Leeson was greatly disturbed and had come
close to suicide.
Mr Pollard said Mr Leeson had not ''fled'' Singapore with his wife
Lisa, but had taken a holiday.
When he read that Barings had collapsed and police were seeking him,
he decided to fly back to Britain where he felt more comfortable about
dealing with the situation.
''They had left Singapore knowing there was a problem with the bank,
that Mr Leeson's trading had not been successful,'' said Mr Pollard.
Leeson sent his letter of resignation the following day because he
knew there was a problem which might lead to his sacking, but he had not
had the slightest thought that the bank was about to crash.
It was three days later that they learnt of the crash when they
happened to see an English language newspaper in the Malaysian resort of
Kota Kinabalu.
The newspaper also mentioned they were being sought by Malaysian
police.
''Their first thought was to get back to countries they understood,
where they knew the system, where they felt they would have got a fairer
hearing than in the Far East,'' said Mr Pollard.
''There was a flight to Frankfurt leaving the following morning. The
next flight to London was either one or two days after that.
''They took the point of view that they were best to take the flight
to Frankfurt with the view of phoning a British solicitor from Frankfurt
with a view to meeting them off the plane at Heathrow.''
The SFO said it was too early to say if it would be seeking to
extradite Mr Leeson or anyone else.
But investigators are likely to note with interest the tentative --
and highly unsual -- offer of help from lawyers representing a possible
suspect.
Barings refused to comment on the claim that Mr Leeson had been made a
scapegoat for the failings of the bank's management.
It will say nothing on the issue until after an official inquiry into
the collapse has been completed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Error admitted on Aitken report</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484927</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CABINET Secretary Sir Robin Butler admitted last night that he had
been ''careless'' in a key part of his report which cleared Treasury
Chief Secretary Jonathan Aitken of alleged impropriety.
Sir Robin made his admission before the Treasury and Civil Service
Select Committee at Westminister.
His report at the height of the ''sleaze'' row last year detailed his
investigation into allegations that Mr Aitken had a free stay at the
Ritz Hotel in Paris.
Sir Robin told the MPs he had looked into the affair on the orders of
the Prime Minister who had not wanted to be seen ''sitting on his
hands'' about the allegations.
He admitted under cross-examination from Tory backbencher Quentin
Davies (Spalding) that his report had referred to Mr Aitken and his wife
paying their bill at the hotel in full.
Mr Davies said: ''One of the salient facts about this was that Mr
Aitken and his wife were not staying at the Ritz. Mr Aitken was staying
alone at the Ritz.''
Sir Robin replied: ''You are right that the word 'their' should have
read 'his'. I was careless.''
He agreed he had not interviewed House of Fraser chief Mohamed
Al-Fayed, a key player in the saga, but he said: ''I interviewed the
witnesses to the extent I thought necessary.''
Mr Davies quoted Sir Robin's report as finding the evidence against Mr
Aitken to be ''entirely unsubstantiated'' or ''demonstrably false''.
Labour's Diane Abbott (Hackney North and Stoke Newington) told him
that Cabinet Secretaries were ''compromised'' when they did the ''dirty
work'' of Prime Ministers.
''To many people, it will look as if you were used by Jonathan Aitken
to give some credibility to what remains a very opaque episode,'' she
added.
</TEXT>
