<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish workersget lowest pay rises</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484929</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS in Scotland received the lowest increases in average earnings
last year at just 1.3% compared to the UK average of 2.7%, according to
a new study from the Low Pay Network.
Analysis of Government statistics shows that average earnings figures
conceal massive pay divisions by areas, occupations and gender and that
relatively few higher paid workers can mask low pay by distorting
averages.
Greater London had the second lowest average increase last year at
1.8% while other areas enjoyed rises averaging between 3.5% and 3.7%.
Regional divisions between pay levels remained ''enormous'' with
workers in Scotland earning #114.70 a week less than the #415.50 London
average.
Although average earnings rose by 2.7% to #325.70 in the year to April
1994, the difference between regions and occupations and between men and
women was ''massive'', said the Low Pay Network.
The report's co-author, Ms Morag Gillespie, said the figures showed
that regional disparities in pay were persisting. She added that there
were significant areas of low pay in all regions although in several,
including Scotland's oil industry, it was masked by some people earning
very high wages.
The gap between male and female earnings showed a slight improvement
over 1993/1994 with women receiving 72.2% of male earnings compared with
71.6% in 1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Seaside town set for #3m facelift</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484930</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE EAST Lothian town of Port Seton, a popular destination for
holidaymakers, is to undergo a #3m facelift.
East Lothian District Council yesterday unveiled plans for a
redevelopment at the town's east promenade covering an area including
the now redundant swimming pool and pond hall, a derelict fairground
site and garage.
Included in the project are:
* A new promenade with landscaped gardens, a cycleway, play areas,
pleasure boat and lily ponds;
* A ''Gala Square'';
* A landscaped ''eastern gateway'' to Port Seton including a civic
sculpture;
* A special needs housing block, built under a restored pond hall
clock; and
* Visitor shelters, birdwatching facilities and viewpoints.
The council is hoping to get funding by developing partnerships with
private and public sector organisations. It will also seek cash aid from
the European Union and the National Lottery.
The project has been welcomed by the town's recently expanded Seton
Sands caravan park, which accommodates 3500 people in the summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Meaning of life</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484931</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW YORK: An Australian physicist whose inquiries into the nature of
the universe have breached the barriers dividing science and theology
has won the Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion. Paul Davies, 48,
author of more than 20 books, was honoured for numerous findings
indicating a purpose and design to human existence.
</TEXT>
