<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Military death widens Belgian bribe scandal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, EUROPEAN EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484932</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
A POLITICAL scandal gripping Belgium and threatening the leadership of
Nato claimed another victim yesterday when the former chief of staff of
the country's air force was found dead, apparently having committed
suicide.
Lieutenant-General Jacques Lefevre, 65, was found in a hotel room near
his home in central Brussels the day after being implicated in the
so-called Agusta scandal which now clouds the future of two of Belgium's
most prominent politicians, Mr Willy Claes, secretary-general of Nato,
and Mr Karl van Miert, European Competition Commissioner.
The general is thought to have poisoned himself after being named as a
conspirator in a corrupt arms deal by a lawyer recently taken into
custody.
His death is the latest sensation in the saga which has made a heroine
of a Belgian investigating magistrate, cost the careers of three
Ministers, and caused the murder of a prominent political fixer, who was
gunned down in a Liege car park after promising to tell the full story.
His killers, suspected of working for the Mafia, have never been caught.
Mr Claes, one of Belgium's most popular and respected politicians, and
Mr van Miert have denied wrongdoing but their futures are seen as
threatened by the scandal.
Agusta is an Italian firm of helicopter manufacturers which won a
#200m contract, allegedly by corrupt means, to supply the Belgians with
46 attack and reconnaissance helicopters in 1988.
After the deal was agreed, the treasurer of the Belgian Flemish
socialist party -- to which Mr Claes and Mr van Miert belong -- was
found to have received more than #1m from the Italians. The money was
paid into a Swiss bank.
In 1991 Mr Andre Cools, former leader of the Walloon socialists in
Liege, was shot dead in a local car park. He was a political kingpin and
his death caused a shock in Belgium.
Examining magistrate Mrs Veronique Ancia concluded that Mr Cools had
been involved in shady dealings.
Her inquiry was hampered by local officials but she broke through when
the Italian authorities, carrying out their own ''clean hands''
corruption inquiry, raided Agusta's offices and found a fax sent to a
Belgian. It talked of ''reassurance'' for the Belgian socialist party.
When Mrs Ancia charged three Ministers, they all resigned, almost
causing the fragile Belgian coalition government to collapse. She coaxed
the Swiss authorities into naming the beneficiaries of the Swiss bank
account.
They were found to be associates of the Flemish socialists. They were
picked up along with Mr Etienne Mange, a former party treasurer who
admitted receiving the #1m via the Swiss account.
After his arrest, Mr Mange implicated Mr Claes. He said that Agusta
had not offered a bribe, merely a ''donation'', and that Mr Claes knew
of this. Mr Claes has denied any such knowledge to Nato ambassadors.
Mr Claes has always denied any knowledge of a financial offer from the
Italians. Last week, however, he suddenly admitted he had a ''vague
memory'' of an offer, but had taken nothing to do with it. He says he
intends to remain in his new post in Nato.
Lt-Gen Lefevre's death yesterday takes the scandal for the first time
into the heart of the Belgina military. He was air force chief of staff
when the government took the decision to buy Agusta's helicopters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greenhouse gas curbs are working, says Gummer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEASURES to curb greenhouse gases have been a resounding success,
according to new Government figures yesterday. By the turn of the
century, the amount of carbon dioxide being released into the atmosphere
is set to fall below 1990 levels by up to 13m tonnes of carbon.
This is in sharp contrast to the target set by then Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher five years ago to peg CO[2] at 1990 levels by the year
2000.
Environment Secretary John Gummer told a London news conference the
success had been achieved through big reductions in the amount of coal
burning for electricity generation and more use of gas and nuclear
power. He claimed that Government privatisation of the utilities had
helped.
''I think this is a triumph of liberalism of the market place that we
foretold,'' he said. ''I am pleased that on this occasion the crystal
ball turned out to be true.''
Britain's commitment to cutting greenhouse gases from industry and
traffic was backed up by Mr John Major in 1992 when he signed the
Climate Convention at the Earth Summit.
Labour and some green lobby groups claimed the Government's
predictions were ''hopelessly optimistic''.
Research by economic forecasters published last month warned that
increased use of oil products for private and public transport would
cause Europe to miss its target of stabilising emissions of greenhouse
gases.
Mr Bob Ainsworth, Labour MP for Coventry North East, said the UK could
not hope to achieve stabilisation by 2000.
He said: ''These figures are ridiculous. Government policies aimed at
reducing carbon monoxide emissions have failed catastrophically. I
calculate they are at least 40% short of their target.''
However, Greenpeace said the Government's prediction that it could cut
emissions of the global warming gas CO[2] by between 10% and 15% showed
that it could go much further.
''The Government has done virtually nothing to achieve this target. It
is obvious that, if proper measures were introduced to encourage
efficient energy use, the UK could meet a 20% cut in CO[2] emissions
within 10 years,'' said Mr Matthew Spencer, Greenpeace atmosphere
campaigner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
