<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>PC cleared on computer charge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484935</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLICE officer with 27 years' experience spoke of his relief last
night after being cleared at Stirling Sheriff Court of using police
computers to help a friend beat a speeding charge.
Police Constable Donald Woollhead, a custody officer at Stirling, is
believed to be the first officer in Scotland to have been tried under
the 1990 Computer Misuse Act.
At the end of a day-long trial, Sheriff Robert Younger said he was not
prepared to draw inference of guilt against Mr Woollhead, who had denied
using the force's Trace computer to search for details of speeding
offences.
Afterwards, Mr Woollhead, who will learn over the next two weeks if he
is to face an internal disciplinary inquiry, said: ''After 17 months
with this hanging over me, I'm delighted.''
He said he had been practising on the force computer at the time the
prosecution alleged he had logged in to look for information to help his
friend.
During the trial, the court heard that Mr Woollhead, 47, of Gartclush
Gardens, Bannockburn, had been a friend for over 20 years of the man he
was accused of helping, lorry driver Daniel McPhail.
Mr McPhail, 48, of Muiralehouse Road, Bannockburn, told the court that
when he was booked for speeding in Tullibody, Clackmannanshire, in April
1993 he noted the registration number of a woman driver being handed a
speeding ticket at the same time.
He called the woman as a witness at his trial at Alloa Sheriff Court,
and after she gave evidence showing traffic police had been booking two
drivers at the same time -- possibly confusing the readings on a radar
gun -- the case against him was found not proven.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ministry of Defence's policy on homosexuality is both irrational and unlawful, counsel maintains. Sacked lesbian takes on the RAF</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484936</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN RAF nurse sacked for being a lesbian yesterday won leave to
challenge in court the ban on homosexuals in the armed forces.
Miss Jeanette Smith, 28, of Albert Street, Leith, was granted the
go-ahead at the High Court in London to seek judicial review of the
decision to sack her last November.
It is the first in a series of test cases being brought against the
Ministry of Defence on grounds that its ban on lesbians and gay men is
contrary to European anti-discrimination law.
If the cases succeed, the Ministry could have to pay millions of
pounds in compensation.
Miss Smith's counsel, Mr Rambi de Mello, said the European directive
could be applied to discrimination against homosexuals. The armed
forces' policy on homosexuality was both irrational and unlawful.
The judge, Mr Justice Latham, said the RAF had started its own
internal appeal procedures but had not indicated that its policy was up
for reconsideration.
''The policy itself is one with which people may have strong views
both ways, which creates problems,'' he said.
The Ministry said it would vigorously defend its long-standing rules
banning homosexuals from the armed forces. It now has 38 days to prepare
its side of the argument so the case can go to a full hearing.
Stonewall, a gay rights pressure group, and Rank Outsiders, which
supports gays and lesbians in the forces, say at least 300 other men and
women have been sacked in the last five years, and many intend to take
action if the test cases succeed.
Outside the court Miss Smith hugged her partner, Margarette Fleming,
30, before they faced the media.
She said: ''I'm very happy about the decision. This is the
breakthrough we needed. There are a lot of gays and lesbians out there
who are counting on us -- I did it for myself and for them.
''We've got a very long way to go, but this is a start. Hopefully now
I've opened the floodgates, others will follow.
''The MoD is wrong. Who someone sleeps with has absolutely no bearing
on how they do their job. It's as simple as that.''
The RAF has a policy stating that ''homosexuality, whether male or
female, is considered incompatible with service in the armed forces''.
When Miss Smith was discharged last November, her certificate said her
services were no longer required because she was ''unable to meet
service obligations through circumstances beyond her control''.
Her counsel argued that her relationship with her lesbian partner was
analagous to a marriage, and they were entitled not to be treated
differently from other married couples by the military authorities.
After the hearing, Stonewall's director, Ms Angela Mason, said the
Ministry's ban was ''wicked and cruel'' and amounted to blatant
discrimination.
''It's extraordinary that in this century people can still be
witch-hunted on the grounds of their sexual activity,'' she said.
Ms Mason said that most European and Nato armed forces did not ban
homosexuals, but Ministry of Defence police had branches dedicated to
tracking down gays and lesbians within the ranks.
She also contrasted the treatment received by homosexuals with that of
the four Parachute Regiment soldiers who were allowed to stay in the
Army despite pleading guilty in court last month to a serious attack on
a civilian.
A number of similar test cases are pending and are likely to be taken
eventually to the European Court of Justice in Luxembourg.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UN chief spells out urgency of women's needs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484937</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Copenhagen, Wednesday
THE United Nations summit to fight poverty, unemployment, and social
injustice marked International Women's Day today by declaring that women
were the biggest victims of all three.
''There is no single group which illustrates the three themes of this
conference better than women,'' UN Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali said in a speech to the Copenhagen gathering.
''The highest percentage of unemployed are women, the poorest of the
poor are women, the socially marginalised and excluded are women,'' he
added.
''Poverty cannot be eliminated, productive employment cannot be
expanded, and social integration cannot be achieved unless women wholly
and equitably participate in social development.''
The UN estimates that about 1.3 billion people live in chronic poverty
and that 70% are female. Over the past 20 years the number of women in
extreme poverty grew by 50% while the rate for men was 30%, UN data
shows.
In her summit address, US First Lady Hillary Clinton announced a #62m
aid package from Washington to fight female illiteracy in the developing
world and called on other governments to follow suit.
''I am pleased to announce today that the United States will allocate
$100m over a 10-year period to provide enhanced educational
opportunities for hundreds of thousands of girls and women in Africa,
Asia, and Latin America who currently live in poverty,'' she told
delegates from more than 100 countries.
''I respectfully urge other governments to join the United States in
creating or expanding the opportunities for all women worldwide,'' she
added.
In her Women's Day speech Mrs Clinton hammered home the plight of
women in developing countries and their unequal share of the world's
ills.
Elsewhere around the world women used the the day to put across a
serious message.
In the Somali capital Mogadishu, hundreds of women marched to call for
peace between the country's rival warlords.
Women in Rwanda marked the day by recalling an even greater tragedy,
at a ceremony at a tiny chapel near Kigali where some 300 women and
children were butchered by a Hutu death squad.
Women's Affairs Minister Aloyisia Inyumba said girls as young as 12
were still giving birth after being raped by the militiamen who
slaughtered their families.
She launched a programme of mass adoption of the 120,000 abandoned
children in the country. ''Everybody in Rwanda should have a family,''
she said.
In Algeria, a three-year civil war between the Government and Muslim
fundamentalists has left 10,000 widows an 140,000 orphans, according to
a family victims' association.
Women held a symbolic ''trial'' in an Algiers hotel and held the
Muslim hard-liners responsible for the violence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Three killed by avalanche in Glencoe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484938</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RESCUERS yesterday found the bodies of three climbers who had been
caught in an avalanche and swept 1000ft down a mountain in Glencoe.
They were identified last night as a group from the Greater Manchester
area who had gone missing at the weekend. The discovery was made during
a search on 3345ft Buachaille Etive Mor.
It brings the official number of deaths in Scottish climbing accidents
this year to 14. In addition, six climbers are still missing. They
include another group of three, from West Yorkshire, who disappeared in
the same area of Glencoe two weeks ago and are also feared to have died
in an avalanche.
Northern Constabulary named the three found yesterday as Mr Gregory
Taylor, 30, of Sale, Mr Simon Blundell, 34, of Westhoughton, Bolton, and
Mr Kevan Ashurst, 29, of Lymm, Cheshire.
Their bodies were found in a snow-filled gully below Curved Ridge.
Police and rescuers said the climbers had been hit by an avalanche as
they were coming off the ridge and hurled 1000ft down the face of the
mountain.
The trio were only reported missing after they failed to return to
work after a planned long-weekend's climbing trip.
Mr Taylor's wife, Paula, first feared something had gone wrong on
Monday night. She raised the alarm early on Tuesday morning before
travelling to Scotland to be nearer to the search site.
Her mother, Mrs Sheila Taylor, said: ''Paula first suspected something
may have happened when Greg did not ring her on Monday. At first, she
was more cross than worried as he often goes away for the weekend and
will not get in touch. But when she called his office on Tuesday and
discovered he had not been in touch, she raised the alarm.
''Greg liked it when the weather conditions were severe. He always
said it had to be bad to be good.''
The six climbers still missing on Scottish mountains include a father,
his 18-year-old son, and the son's friend, all from West Yorkshire, who
are feared to have died in an avalanche on Buachaille Etive Mor two
weeks ago.
Another climber, from the Manchester area, fell through a snow cornice
on Ben Nevis earlier in February.
Two men have been missing in the Cairngorms since Saturday. Mr Allan
Mitchell, 22, of Ramsbottom, Greater Manchester, and Mr Graham Holland,
22, of Rossendale, had set off on a week-long climbing trip. The search
for the pair resumed yesterday but in scaled-down form and rescuers have
all but given up hope of finding them alive.
Mr Mitchell, who worked in a mountaineering shop in Keswick, wanted to
become an instructor at the Glenmore Lodge Outdoor Pursuits Centre in
the Cairngorms.
His father, Brian, said: ''He was told he needed more experience of
winter climbing in Scotland before he could be considered for the job.
That is why he went up there. Both he and Graham are experienced
climbers.''
The 14 deaths resulting from mountain accidents this year include Dr
Ian Barnett, 31, of the Doctor's Residence, Law Hospital, Carluke,
Lanarkshire, who died earlier this week as a result of injuries he
received almost three weeks ago when he slipped 200ft down Creag
Meagaidh, near Laggan in Lochaber.
His climbing companion, Mr Ewen Fraser, 29, of Eglinton Street, Beith,
Ayrshire, is in a stable and satisfactory condition in intensive care at
Glasgow Royal Infirmary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Stupid' road-racing drivers sentenced</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484939</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER strode from the public benches into the well of a court
yesterday, stood in front of a young woman in the dock, and told her:
''You killed my son.''
Moments earlier 18-year-old Debbie Hardy had been cleared of causing
the death of Greg Turner, a passenger in her car went it crashed upside
down into the Cromarty Firth.
The jury at Tain Sheriff Court found her guilty of dangerous driving
and of speeding on the Alness-Invergordon road last June.
Sheriff Donald Booker-Milburn had dismissed the jury and left the
bench ''for five minutes'' to consider the sentence when Mrs Kath Turner
made her emotional outburst.
Hardy's smiles of relief at being cleared of causing Mr Turner's death
turned to tears as Mrs Turner strode up and confronted her.
Shaking with emotion, Mrs Turner told the accused: ''To think your own
sister is disabled and in a wheelchair because of the same kind of
driving. You killed my son. I hope you can live with it. I can't. You
have taken our son.''
Moments later the sheriff, fiscal, and the sheriff clerk returned to
the court unaware of what had been said.
Sheriff Booker-Milburn fined Hardy, a hairdresser, of Queen Street,
Invergordon, a total of #1000 and banning her from driving for four
years and ordering her to resit her test. He said that if she had been
found guilty of causing 18-year-old Mr Turner's death by dangerous
driving, he would have had ''no hesitation'' in imposing a lengthy
period of imprisonment.
Hardy had a co-accused, 18-year-old Clare Mackay, of Delny Farm
Cottages, Invergordon. She was found guilty of careless driving and
racing and was fined a total of #600, banned for two years, and ordered
to resit her test.
The sheriff, who described the pair's driving as ''stupid and wholly
irresponsible'' said racing, as they had done, was just as bad as
dangerous driving.
He expressed his sympathy to the relatives of the dead youth and said:
''I will do everything in my power to stop this sort of speeding,
especially on that stretch of road.''
The three-mile Alness-Invergordon road is notorious for young people
speeding. The trial had heard of smoking tyres and Hardy and Mackay's
cars driving bumper to bumper at high speed.
What started as an exchange of V-signs between the two cars as they
''cruised'' Alness ended when Hardy's car left the road and plunged
upside down into the Cromarty Firth.
Mr Turner was said to have been the only person in Hardy's car to try
and stop his friends egging her on to go faster and catch Mackay. He
died a day later from his injuries.
Outside the court Hardy refused to say anything, but Mrs Turner said:
''It is unbelievable that girl went out and drove like that when her own
sister was crippled because of the same sort of driving.
''The boy who was driving at least admitted it. She has shown no
remorse and has not even said she is sorry for what happened.''
Mr Turner's father, Reg, said: ''She should have been jailed for the
dangerous driving. It's the only thing that's going to stop this sort of
thing.''
During the trial the court was filled daily with young people from the
surrounding area.
</TEXT>
