<DOCNO>GH950309-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Island councillor at odds with conservation group over reason for his board dismissal Quarry backer ditched by SNH</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS, HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN ISLAND councillor has been removed as a member of Scottish Natural
Heritage's North West Regional Board because he publicly criticised the
group's opposition to the superquarry at Lingerbay on Harris.
However, Mr Angus Graham, vice-convener of the Western Isles Council,
believes his hostility to a scheme to grant the Countess of Sutherland's
family #150,000 not to fell trees on its land, finally lost him his
board seat, and the #6000-a-year that went with it.
Mr Graham supports the quarry, as does the Western Isles Council,
because of the jobs it will bring. He was quoted in last week's edition
of the Skye-based West Highland Free Press as saying the conservation
group had made a fundamental mistake in objecting to the superquarry,
and that its case was flawed.
Yesterday, he received a letter dated March 4 from writer and
scientist Sir John Lister-Kaye, who runs a field centre near Beauly, and
who chairs the group's regional board: ''I am deeply dismayed to see
that you have again hit out at SNH in last week's West Highland Free
Press.
''You will remember our clear agreement that, after the events of last
year, in particular our meeting in the Station Hotel in Inverness, or
with Mr Magnus Magnusson at the Stornoway Office launch, and my letters
of May 19 and June 7, you would not make any statements about SNH to the
press without clearing it with me or Mr Peter Tilbrook (regional
director).
''You will know that your two-year appointment to SNH's North West
Regional Board technically runs out at the end of March, in three weeks
time. I had genuinely hoped to be able to continue without any changes
to the board for another year, but this requires my clear recommendation
to the main board at Tuesday's meeting and, because I have put my head
on the block for you twice already, I do not feel that I am in a
position to make that recommendation.''
Yesterday, Mr Graham replied to Sir John categorically denying that he
had ever given him or Mr Magnusson an undertaking to toe the SNH line on
Lingerbay.
Mr Graham recalls Sir John publicly criticising Highlands and Islands
Enterprise for cutting back financial support for environmental
education. He had been asked if he was speaking on behalf of the
regional board.
''You insisted that you had been making a personal observation, but
neither you, nor the press, made that distinction. Neither did you
mention that your own organisation had been in receipt of HIE funding
for environmental education.''
Mr Graham tells Sir John: ''I firmly believe, however, that a more
important reason for you terminating my board membership has been my
opposition to your proposal to establish a national nature reserve at
Loch Fleet, on land owned by a trust of the Strathnaver Sutherland
family.
''I still believe it would be a scandal for SNH to rush to give
#150,000 of public money to a private landowning family trust, for a
scheme whose real conservation value is, to say the very least, highly
questionable. It would serve only to confirm the worst public perception
of quangos, the propriety of the way they operate, and do an enormous
disservice to SNH, which could undermine its future work.''
Mr Graham challenges Sir John now, to consider whether his close
involvement with the Loch Fleet project has undermined his ability to
act as an impartial chairman.
After receiving Mr Graham's letter, Sir John told The Herald that
there was no truth in the suggestion that debate was stifled on the
board, where members had every right to disagree, or try and influence
SNH policy. That was different from always conducting debates in the
press.
''The Loch Fleet project, meanwhile, played no part in my thinking on
Mr Angus Graham. The negotiations are still going on, so I cannot really
comment apart from to say it would mean a first rate nature reserve
which could make a very positive contribution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Windermere points to bitter experience on speed limits</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE word from south of the Border -- particularly from Lake Windermere
and Poole and Langstone harbours in Dorset -- in relation to Loch
Lomond's by-laws is not encouraging.
''How long will it be before the Scottish authorities come to the same
conclusion that we did?'' asks Mr John Nash, one of the senior planners
at the Lake District National Park.
After years of trying to regulate the use of fast powerboats on
Windermere, to curb water skiing and jet skiing in the interests of
safety and the environment, the national park authority conceded defeat
and sought a by-law to impose a blanket 10mph speed limit on the lake.
Such was the outcry, headed by lakeside businessmen who claimed the
speed limit would cost 730 local jobs, that a public inquiry was called.
The result is due this spring, but there appears to be limited room to
manoeuvre. Mr Nash believes the answer will be a straight yes or no,
with the possibility of a ''no, but''. Everything would then depend on
what the but is.
The fact is that Windermere had deteriorated into little more than a
hellhole, choked with cars round its shores and choked by speedcraft on
its waters.
The Countryside Act of 1968 allowed the lakes to be regulated and
10mph limits were imposed at Ullswater, Derwentwater and Coniston Water.
Boat numbers have actually increased there over the years, as
small-craft owners took advantage of the safer conditions.
It was hoped at that time, says Mr Nash, to regulate Windermere
without coercion, so the steering committee never managed to come to
grips with levels of noise or speed. They could find no consensus, no
simple solution. Registration of all craft appeared to offer a solution.
''We thought we could keep the lid on the different activities if we
had the power to licence the different craft and their numbers and the
terms on which they operated,'' he says, adding that in the late 1980s
that became an unattainable goal. A private Bill was promoted in
Parliament but because of the objections it went nowhere.
In 1991, matters came to a head. The Windermere park authority reached
the conclusion that it was 16 years since it said the lake would be open
to powerboats but, with the dramatic change in circumstances, it was
time to think again. The original concept of quiet enjoyment in the
national parks was dusted off and the collision course set with the
commercial interests.
''It was a different world. There had been an increase in the size of
powerboats, an increase in their numbers, in their speed and in the
times they were used. It had become impossible to reconcile with the
idea of quiet enjoyment,'' he states.
The decision to fight for Windermere has cost the authority around
#450,000, money which the national parks could have put to better use.
Ironically, those most bitterly opposed to the speed limit, the power
boating interests, are not regarded as a major economic factor in an
area which attracts between four and five million visitors a year.
There may be a lesson there for Loch Lomond, where the pressures from
commercial interests appear to have had a dominant say in the philosophy
behind the by-laws.
In places like Poole, the pressure from water skiing, jet skiing and
power boating has reached breaking point.
Poole Harbour has imposed a blanket speed limit of 10mph and has zoned
areas for water skiing and jet skiing. It has been forced to redraw its
by-laws in the face of the increasing misbehaviour, which resulted in a
boy being killed a year ago.
Assistant harbour master Mr John Milner says they now have very strict
rules for water skiing, brought in last year, as the harbour became more
dangerous. Speeds of 40 knots were not unusual, he says, with 4000
vessels on the water at a time not an unusual sight.
As with Loch Lomond, there is a right of navigation on Poole Harbour.
That means that regulation has to be concentrated on safety reasons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government and Sinn Fein near key decision Exclusion orders lifted as terror laws renewed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE,STEPHEN MCGREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484942</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government and Sinn Fein are approaching a key point in the
delicate process of bringing them into political negotiations for a
stable peace in Northern Ireland.
Britain requires that the IRA begins handing over arms such as Semtex
explosives, ground-to-air missiles, and heavy machine guns before it can
claim the right to a meeting with a Government Minister.
Sinn Fein, reacting to comments made by Northern Ireland Secretary Sir
Patrick Mayhew in Washington on Tuesday, still is demanding that there
should be no preconditions to it taking part in the political
negotiations of the peace process.
Although Sir Patrick insisted in the Commons that there was ''no
change whatsoever'' in the Government's position, Unionists and some
Tories angrily claimed that Ministers were now ''in full retreat'' in
the face of IRA intimidation.
However, Mr Martin McGuinness, of Sinn Fein, said yesterday: ''I have
been involved in discussions on and off and contact with representatives
of the British Government for the last five years. Never at any stage
did the British Government mention that there had to be a
decommissioning of IRA weapons. This issue has only come on stream since
the IRA cessation of August 31 last year.''
Mr McGuinness claimed that the British Government was changing the
rules.
The shadow-boxing has reached a delicate stage, with the Ulster
Unionists at their most anxious about how to proceed towards political
negotiations.
They have produced a suggestion for a formalised handing over of
weapons to be supervised by an independent and foreign army general,
preferably Canadian. The paramilitary loyalists also have to be
convinced that the IRA is prepared to hand over offensive -- as opposed
to defensive -- weapons. On this issue, the peace process could stall.
Democratic Unionist leader Ian Paisley said people in the province saw
the ''so-called ceasefire and peace process'' as being of advantage to
the terrorists.
He said: ''The IRA can at this time dictate when this peace can be
broken and in the interim the Government are dancing to a tune of
concessions in order to keep the Provisional IRA sweet ...
''The fact is that the IRA has no intention whatsoever of
decommissioning or surrendering arms.''
Meanwhile, last night, representatives of the Protestant
paramilitaries said that they too wanted ministerial contact.
In the Commons, Home Secretary Michael Howard announced that he was
lifting exclusion orders on republicans formerly banned from travelling
to mainland Britain.
However, the Government is insisting on maintaining for another year
the rigorous provisions of the Prevention of Terrorism Act.
MPs voted overwhelmingly last night in favour of retaining the Act.
Its continuation for another year went through by 314 votes to 212 as Mr
Howard confirmed to the Commons that he was lifting 16 of the 56
exclusion orders currently in force.
However, he made clear he had considered whether it would be possible
to go further and had not done so for two reasons.
First, it was clear that if the ceasefires broke down there might be
very little warning, if any, and without doubt many of the targets
would, as before, be on this side of the water.
Second, the police remained satisfied that among those still excluded
were some who would be likely to play some part in mainland terrorism
were it to resume.
''I shall continue to keep the need for each of the orders under
review, but I am not prepared to take unnecessary risks at this stage,''
he said.
The Home Secretary referred to the thorny issue of surrender of
weapons, and appeared to reflect the softer line on this issue taken by
Sir Patrick Mayhew.
Mr Howard said: ''It remains the Government's earnest hope that those
who have previously supported the use of violence to advance their cause
can be brought fully and irrevocably within the political process. That,
of course, means that there needs to be substantial progress on the
issue of decommissioning arms and explosives.
''It would, in our view, be wholly irresponsible to dismantle our
defences while the paramilitary organisations remain intact, while they
continue to carry out brutal punishment beatings, while their command
structures, weapons and explosives remain in place and while they retain
the capability to resume violence at very short notice.''
The Government would keep the situation under review, and there was a
better chance now than at any time in the past 21 years that an end may
soon be in sight to such annual debates.
However, he added, the prospects remained uncertain.
For Labour, Shadow Home Secretary Jack Straw made clear that the
official Labour line was voting against renewal of the Act because the
Government had failed to agree to a comprehensive review of all
anti-terrorist legislation.
''In the changed circumstances of a sustained ceasefire, now is the
time to review precisely what anti-terrorist legislation we need. Labour
wants a bi-partisan approach in this area and I greatly regret that the
Government has not accepted the proposals we have made to achieve the
consensus we seek.''
THE HOME Secretary last night pledged that he will never authorise
damages payments as a result of the challenge to his exclusion orders
policy by Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams in the European Court.
Mr Howard was pressed by angry Tories amid fears that the case could
lead to claims by up to 500 other IRA sympathisers who have been banned
from Britain at some time under emergency laws.
Tory Terry Dicks (Hayes and Harlington) angrily demanded ''that
irrespective of what any European Court says about Adams this Government
will take no notice of that and flatly refuse to pay him and his ilk any
money at all''.
Mr Howard replied, to Tory cheers: ''I shall never authorise any
payment of damages as a result of this case.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
