<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Water treatment advance in battle against legionella</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484943</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH water treatment company yesterday announced what it
believes is a big breakthrough in the battle against legionnaire's
disease.
The Deveron Environmental company of East Kilbride has developed a
treatment system which it says can combat the legionella bacterium
responsible for the disease.
The system was launched yesterday in Glasgow at the biggest
environmental exhibition and conference ever held in Scotland.
Mr Robert Wilson, a director of the firm, has spent two years
researching the problem. He explained: ''Cooling towers associated with
cooling water systems provide the ideal habitat for the bacteria to
multiply.
''Treatment of cooling water systems has depended on regular cleaning
and disinfection, using bleach and ongoing chemical dosing, to minimise
corrosion and effect good microbiological control. This traditional
treatment is not always effective because it cannot remove or control a
thin microbiological layer -- the biofilm -- which is present in 90% of
water systems.''
His company's approach to the problem was to remove the biofilm and
other surface debris which could harbour the legionella bacterium, by
using a powerful but environmentally-friendly biocide which had Drinking
Water Inspectorate approval for use in potable water.
''Quite frankly, our claim is that our treatment removes biofilm and
traditional treatments do not,'' said Mr Wilson.
The firm says that the system, known as DELTA PA (Deveron
Environmental Low Toxicity and Polymer Assist), has already been put to
use and is a proven success. It is being launched through 20
distributors in the UK and there are plans for expansion into Europe and
the US.
Deveron is working with the Viscona company of Hawick to produce the
chemicals used in the system.
It acknowledges research into the problem undertaken by Mr Jimmy
Walker, a Scot, at the Government's Porton Down centre for
microbiological research, and says it will continue to be associated
with the centre.
The system was launched at the combined Envirotec '95 and Scottish
Water and Effluent Treatment event at the Scottish Exhibition and
Conference Centre.
The two-day event, which has attracted about 200 exhibitors, was
officially opened by Mr Brian Fitzgerald, chairman of CBI Scotland's
environment committee, who said industry wished to play its part in
creating and sustaining a healthy environment in Scotland while creating
wealth and employment.
''Industry does pollute and should not hide from this, but recognising
the issues is only a first step. There is a long way to go before each
and every company meets its environmental responsibilities.''
The event organiser, Mr Don Morrison, revealed plans for a conference
in Aberdeen this autumn to debate the shape of water and sewerage
services as Scotland's three new water authorities prepare to take over
these services from regional councils.
</TEXT>
