<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mandela rules out meeting with Winnie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484944</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Cape Town, Wednesday
PRESIDENT Nelson Mandela today ruled out meeting his estranged wife,
Winnie, saying he had delegated his deputy Thabo Mbeki to deal with the
controversy over her behaviour and allegations of corruption.
''Mr Mbeki is handling this matter. Mr Mbeki is a highly gifted and
resourceful leader and it is a matter that is within his capacity,''
Mandela told reporters in the garden of his Tuynhuys office in Cape
Town.
Mandela recently instructed Mbeki to talk to Mrs Mandela, a deputy
minister in his government of national unity, about allegations of
corruption in housing deals and a breach of discipline when she
travelled to West Africa in defiance of an order to cancel the trip.
The deputy minister of arts and culture has refused, however, to meet
Mbeki, telling him by letter that she would discuss the matter only with
Mandela.
* The British High Commission said the Queen was likely to honour
President Mandela on her first state visit to South Africa later this
month. However spokesman Nigel Casey said it need not be an honorary
knighthood, and added that speculation that Mrs Mandela might take the
title ''Lady'' was misguided.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
