<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Footprint only clue to death of farmer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484947</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE cause of a farmer's death remained a mystery after an inquest in
his home county of Gloucestershire yesterday.
Mr Clive Warner, 55, was found dead at Hardgate Farm, Bonnykelly, New
Pitsligo, near Aberdeen, last November 10.
The deputy Gloucester coroner, Mr Alan Crickmore, said there were
signs that he had shot himself accidentally with his double bore
shotgun.
But the evidence was not conclusive enough for him to record an
accidental death verdict, he said.
Instead, he recorded an open verdict on Mr Warner, who had moved to
Scotland from Stonehouse and Eastington, near Stroud, Gloucestershire.
Mr Warner's wife, Beryl, found him lying dead on the road outside
their home at 5.45pm.
His shotgun was lying nearby with one cartridge spent and the only
significant clue to the cause of his death was a footprint from his
wellington boot in the earth on top of a nearby stone wall.
PC Kevin Goldie, who investigated the death, said that earlier Mr
Warner had spoken about going out to shoot a wild goose on his land in
preparation for a visit by his son the next day.
On the day of his death he had seemed ''cheery'' when he said goodbye
to his wife in the morning and he had no financial worries.
Mr Crickmore said there was no evidence pointing to suicide but the
only evidence suggesting an accident was the footprint on the wall and
that was not enough to reach a firm conclusion that death was
accidental.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
