<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>South Africa in Scottish jobs plea</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484949</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN who spent 13 years imprisoned with South Africa's President
Nelson Mandela was in Scotland yesterday urging business leaders to
bring jobs to his country.
Mr Tokyo Sexwale, Premier of South Africa's Gauteng region, was
released in 1990 after being held on Robben Island for alleged terrorism
and conspiracy to overthrow the old regime.
Now he is in government himself spearheading South Africa's bid to
attract international investment and create quality jobs and conditions
which would not seek to exploit black workers.
Mr Sexwale, who today meets the Foreign Secretary, Mr Douglas Hurd, in
London, said he was in Glasgow ''to touch base with Scotland -- a part
of the UK quite well known in South Africa''.
Yesterday, after meeting CBI chiefs and Lord Provost Tommy Dingwall,
Mr Sexwale said: ''We recognise that Britain is a critical investor for
South Africa.
''We must address the question of quality of life of our people and we
recognise that can only be done by encouraging job creation. We must
broaden the base of ownership and the economy of South Africa.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ancient chain goes on show</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484950</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PROVOST'S silver chain of office has gone on show in Inverness
District Council's museum before the authority ceases to exist after
local government reorganisation. The chain, which is too heavy to wear
for long periods, is over 1300 years old and belonged to a Pictish chief
or high priest. It was discovered while the Caledonian Canal was being
excavated in 1800.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
