<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nursing home in bid to halt screening of documentary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON,CHIEF REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484953</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEGAL action is expected today in a bid to block the screening of a
BBC Scotland documentary tonight which purports to expose ''appalling''
standards of care for the elderly in a Lanarkshire nursing home.
The owners of Orchard House in Crossford yesterday threw its doors
open to The Herald and declared: ''We have nothing to hide.''
Nursing staff broke down in tears and also strenuously denied the
allegations in the Frontline Scotland programme, shown to the media in
advance of scheduled screening.
Residents also insisted that they have no complaints about standards,
and expressed shock that their home could close if allegations following
the two-month undercover investigation are proved.
Secret footage is at its most disturbing when showing a man allegedly
confined to a ''restricter'' chair for up to 24 hours a day and at risk
of strangulation if sliding down.
But his wife and daughter last night declared that they have no
concerns about his treatment. They prefer him to be in the chair,
supervised throughout the night, rather than be ''doped up'' to ensure
he stays in bed.
Ms Lilias McAdam, 40, of St Nicholas Road, Lanark, said the family has
complained to the BBC about the footage, and added: ''We are seeking
legal advice with a view to court action.''
''We believe the care at Orchard House is fabulous, and has done
everything possible to help him. We do not want him doped up, and prefer
he is allowed, when necessary, to sit up in a chair which does not hurt
him or keep him totally still and he can talk to staff.''
In the programme, five registered or auxiliary nurses -- no longer
working at the home -- catalogue alleged indignities suffered by
residents which would breach health care guidelines.
The five include Ms Adele Bryson, who resigned last year then lost an
industrial tribunal action against the home. Two relatives of former
residents are also featured, expressing concern at a lack of stimulation
or care at the home, where weekly bills for the 63 residents are
#330-a-head.
Allegations include grave shortages in emergency first aid and oxygen
equipment, and:
* Face-cloths, also used to wipe bottoms, being used by more than one
resident, with the cloths washed rather than boiled;
* A scabies outbreak, blamed on poor hygiene in the laundry, and:
* Clothes, including underwear, being passed on from former residents,
including some who had died.
The home owners -- former policeman Raymond Baigent and his wife
Margaret -- deny any impropriety.
They gave The Herald free rein to walk about the property, which was
warm and well-appointed, and also speak to residents and staff.
However, their lawyers had last night sought an interim interdict in
the Court of Session to prevent publication of the programme's contents
because its allegations were said to be ''grossly defamatory''.
The application was rejected by Lord Morton of Shuna, who ruled that
freedom of the press should be upheld as far as possible.
He added the pursuers would have the remedy of damages if anything was
said that was defamatory to them.
The Baigents, who have not seen the programme, earlier told The Herald
that they would have talked to the BBC had a direct rather than covert
approach been taken when it was being made.
They also claimed the allegations arise from long-running feuds over
the purchase of Orchard House; financial rows in connection with a
former resident, and past troubles with disgruntled staff.
In the documentary, ex-auxiliary Cathy O'Hare, 42, of Carluke, alleges
the home is like looking in a shop window and seeing a cake. But, she
adds: ''You have to be a resident at a nursing home to know that
underneath the icing it's rotten.''
Colleague Adele Bryson, a registered nurse, now working at Law
Hospital, also denied her complaints of the home follow the industrial
tribunal failure. She stood by the allegations, and said of their
rubbishing at Orchard House: ''I have done nothing wrong other than be
the whistle-blower . . . everyone is entitled to their opinion.''
Former employee Sandra McCulloch confirmed she did not raise concerns
with authorities over an 18-month period, relying only on an an
anonymous letter from a staff member sent to the health board. She
argued no-one would have believed an auxiliary.
Auxiliary Margaret Clelland, at the home since it opened more than six
years ago, cried when told of the allegations. Her father-in law has
been a resident, and she has recommended the home to villagers in
Crossford: ''We have to clear our names. I could not have worked here if
it was as portrayed.''
Enrolled nurse Jean Patterson, also of Crossford, said: ''I do not
know why such things are being said. We have nothing to hide.''
Resident Catherine Tomney, 82, whose family visits twice a week, said
of the home: ''It's very good. The nurses are nice. We are well looked
after. I hope it does not close. It is my home.''
Friend Nan Burt, 88, said: ''I have never seen anything bad here. We
are well looked after. It could not be better.''
The oldest resident, Molly Thomson, 94, said on told that registration
could be withdrawn: ''Oh, no. I do not want to go anywhere else. They
are very nice people, and will do anything for you.''
Lanarkshire Health Board, the registers, said yesterday: ''We can
confirm the board is currently investigating allegations in relations to
aspects of the running of Orchard House nursing home. Investigations are
on going. When concluded, we will consider what action, if any, will be
appropriate in response to the findings.''
The BBC said undercover filming was instituted after hearing ''many
complaints from a number of sources.'' A spokesman said the owners were
asked for an interview but declined, and added: ''We stand by the
programme and will leave it to the viewer to decide whether Orchard
House is a well-run nursing home. We will oppose any application for any
interdict.''
Continued on Page 2
Continued from Page 1
</TEXT>
