<DOCNO>GH950309-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Damages for limbo dancer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484954</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HIGH Court jury in London yesterday awarded a limbo dancer #36,401
damages against the Metropolitan Police over a beating-up which ended
his career.
But most of the award to Mr Gabriel Thomas will be swallowed up by
legal costs which he must pay after refusing a police offer of #40,000
to settle the case.
Mr Thomas was on the verge of the big time before the incident after a
charity telethon at the London Arena in Docklands in May 1990, the court
heard.
Known as King Gaby, he was one of the best limbo dancers in the world
with the ability to go under a bar just seven or eight inches from the
floor.
But persistent pain in his rib-cage after the assault meant he no
longer had the flexibility and balance needed to perform, his QC, Lord
Gifford, told the judge, Sir Michael Davies.
Mr Thomas, 37, of St Katherine's Way, Tower Hamlets, east London, had
to turn down a #25,000 touring contract and was now unemployed.
Lord Gifford said the police arrived as Mr Thomas was leaving the
venue after an argument with a security guard, who mistakenly thought he
should not be on the premises.
He was pushed against a wall, thrown to the ground and kicked, dragged
by his hair to a van and detained at Limehouse police station for six
hours.
He was charged with using threatening behaviour calculated to cause a
breach of the peace, but acquitted by magistrates.
By a majority of 10 to two, the jury found Mr Thomas had been
assaulted and awarded him #15,815 general damages, #16,185 plus #4,091
interest for lost earnings, and #310 for damage to his stage costume,
dentures, watch and shoes.
But it rejected his claims of false imprisonment and malicious
prosecution.
The Metropolitan Police said it did nothing wrong. It claimed Mr
Thomas was justifiably ejected from the venue, was abusive to officers
and no excessive force was used against him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Champion of gay rights</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484955</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE wasn't much time for celebrations yesterday for the couple from
Leith.
Their trek down to London had required a 5am start and the avalanche
of media interest after the court hearing had taken its toll.
''I think we are too exhausted,'' Miss Jeanette Smith said.
Her victory has propelled her overnight into celebrity status as a gay
rights champion, but it has not been an easy battle.
''I have been as low as I can go. I have thought about jumping off
Arthur's Seat, but I have brought myself out of the depths and I am
ready to fight'', she said.
Miss Smith joined the RAF at the age of 23 and realised she was
lesbian two years later.
''In five and a half years with the RAF, my conduct was exemplary. I
had been recommended for promotion twice but the minute they found out I
was a lesbian they decided I was unable to do my job'', she said.
Her relationship with her lover, Miss Margarette Fleming, would
scarcely turn an eyebrow in civilian life. They live quietly and
responsibly, acting as legal guardians for Miss Fleming's 17-year-old
niece.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
