<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Exclusion orders that failed to keep out the terrorists</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BRUCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484957</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSION orders under the Prevention of Terrorism Act have never
stopped a single infiltrator from entering the British mainland with
malice in mind.
The only people who have been kept out of Britain are media figures
such as Mr Gerry Adams and Mr Martin McGuinness, along with about 50
known activists who could have caused problems for the Government by
exposing the secret talks with the IRA or raising civil rights issues in
public.
The real terrorists came ashore from fishing boats or other craft on
the west coast of Scotland. The Brighton bombers, the active service
unit which almost wiped out the Tory party's top echelon on the eve of
their annual conference, landed by boat at Ayr under cover of darkness
before making their way south.
The 12-mile North Channel between the Antrim coast and Scotland was a
secure highway for both sides of the sectarian divide. The Provisionals
sent active service units east. The loyalists sent weapons west.
Despite the best efforts of the Royal Navy, that traffic was seldom
interrupted. The semi-permanent presence of a patrolling warship in the
busy channel was a purely psychological barrier. The two-way flow
continued virtually unabated for 25 years.
The only real benefit of the Prevention of Terrorism Act to the
security forces has been the right to detain suspects for up to seven
days while withholding the bulk of their civil rights, and the right to
question them without legal recourse to tape-recorded interviews.
The law, renewable annually, also provides for easy access to
extensions of custody on the flimsiest of grounds. Suspects regularly
spend up to 14 days under interrogation with no legal representation if
police or security forces presented even a shred of a prima facie case.
However, the mainly IRA targets of the legislation have had to be
caught on the mainland before that could be done. It happened from time
to time. The James Gray Street arrest of a Provo active service unit on
the south side of Glasgow made headlines.
The truth behind it was that the almost bungled raid on a block of
tenement flats had stretched police resources to the limit. The police
had also refused help from the Army's special forces. In the end, they
were lucky. Nobody died in an assault which could have cost many lives.
Under the unwritten rules of the game, there were few complaints when
real terrorist teams were captured and questioned. The screams of
anguish occurred over the more public and sensitive area of civil
rights.
Sinn Fein always claimed the Act contravened not only British domestic
law but also breached the conventions of European legislation. Mr Adams
argued forcefully that Britain's EU membership gave him ''freedom of
expression and freedom to reside and move freely within the territory of
member states''.
The Government's view has always been that freedom of expression and
movement, while inherently important, have to take a back seat to the
more pressing issue of national security.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Magnusson outlines changes in approach</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484958</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAGNUS Magnusson yesterday called on Scottish landowners to accept
that designations such as sites of special scientific interest were
facts of modern life with which they could live and draw considerable
benefit.
Mr Magnusson, the chairman of Scottish Natural Heritage was addressing
the Scottish Landowners Federation conference in Perth. He said that SNH
thinking had moved on from seeing designations as the ''be all and end
all'' for nature conservation.
''Designated islands of specialness cannot ensure the long-term
survival of species; air pollution is no respecter of boundaries and
climatic change may force the migration of species anyway. We have to
look beyond the bulwark.
''Besides trying to 'protect the best and forget the rest' ignores the
fact that conservation is for people too and that means valuing the
commonplace and the accessible as well as the rare and remote.''
He added that there had been a shift in perspective since the days
when conservation and development were polar opposites.
SNH was offering a helping hand with the difficult transition from
yesterday's short-term yield to tomorrow's all-embracing philosophy of
sustainability, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>VE-Day events fill up royal diaries</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484959</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE largest gathering of heads of state and government in Britain
since the 1953 Coronation will assemble in London to mark the 50th
anniversary of VE-Day.
VIPs from more than 50 foreign and Commonwealth countries will attend
the Victory in Europe commemorations over the weekend of May 6 to 8.
Almost every senior member of the royal family will take part in the
events. The Prince and Princess of Wales will be appearing together in
public for the first time since Christmas Day at Sandringham.
The Duchess of York will not take part in the commemorations. She has
had no royal engagements since her unofficial marriage separation was
announced in March 1992.
The Queen Mother, 94, and Princess Alice, 93, will participate.
As well as set-piece events in the capital, there will be
commemorations in other cities, including Cardiff and Edinburgh.
On Monday, May 8, the Prince of Wales travels to Cardiff for a peace
service in Llandaff Cathedral, while the Princess Royal and Commander
Laurence attend a service at St Giles' in Edinburgh.
Also on Monday, a concert in the forecourt of Buckingham Palace for
the Queen, Queen Mother, and Princess Margaret will relive the palace
balcony scene of 50 years ago.
Members of the royal family will also travel to Norway and France to
take part in ceremonies to mark the 50th anniversary of peace.
On Friday, May 5, the Queen, the Duke of Edinburgh, and the Prince of
Wales will attend a joint session of the Houses of Parliament at
Westminster.
The following day, the Queen Mother and Princess Margaret will perform
the opening ceremony for a three-day event at Hyde Park.
The first set-piece event will be on Saturday May 6 with a reception
and banquet for heads of state and government at Guildhall when the
Queen will make a speech.
Other members of the royal family present will be the Duke of
Edinburgh, Prince of Wales, Duke of York, Prince Edward, Princess
Margaret, Duke and Duchess of Gloucester, Duke and Duchess of Kent,
Prince and Princess Michael of Kent, Princess Alexandra and Sir Angus
Ogilvy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
