<HEADLINE>Aberdeen lawyer charged</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484960</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SOLICITOR from Aberdeen was among three men accused of conspiracy to
defraud who had their cases transferred to Southwark Crown Court for
trial by Bow Street Magistrates Court in London yesterday.
Mr George Esson, 46, a solicitor of Springfield Road, Aberdeen, Mr
Rodney Hylton-Potts, 49, a solicitor of Chelsea, and Mr John Whybrow,
45, a property trader of St Johns Wood, are charged with conspiring to
defraud between June 1, 1988, and January 1, 1990.
Mr Hylton-Potts and Mr Whybrow are also charged with obtaining a
pecuniary advantage relating to an overdraft by falsely representing
that Mr Whybrow was the beneficiary to a certain trust fund and that the
overdraft was secured against paayment from that fund.
All were allowed bail and ordered to live at their addresses and
notify police of any change of address.
</TEXT>
