<DOCNO>GH950309-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>More Scottish beaches earn high praise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484963</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIRTEEN Scottish beaches were highly praised for the quality of their
bathing water and facilities in a survey published yesterday.
The latest edition of the Reader's Digest good beach guide, produced
in association with the Marine Conservation Society, lists almost twice
as many recommended Scottish sites as last year's version, which had
seven.
One beach, at Gullane, has been downgraded, but the publishers were
yesterday unable to give an exact explanation for its lower status.
Those awarded the guide's recommended ranking are: Thorntonloch, White
Sands Bay, near Dunbar, and Belhaven Beach, Dunbar (all Lothian);
Silversands, Aberdour, Shell Bay, Earlsferry, West Sands, St Andrews,
and Tentsmuir Sands (all Fife); Lunan Bay and Montrose (both Tayside);
Balmedie and St Combs (both Grampian); Nairn Central and Dornoch (both
Highland).
The society admitted that a large number of other Scottish beaches,
especially on the west coast and islands, could merit inclusion, but
scientific data about the water conditions was not available.
However, it was critical of the standards of beaches in many parts of
the UK, where it described bathing as ''like swimming in a public
toilet''.
Many fail to meet minimum European bathing water standards, including
Blackpool, Great Yarmouth and Brighton, said the society.
A total of 900 beaches are listed in the guide, but a
''disappointingly low'' number met the stringent water quality standards
laid down by the MCS.
Environmentalist Jonathon Porritt says in the foreword: ''It is an
unfortunate fact of life that for many of us the average trip to the
seaside involves unpleasant encounters with sewage, sewage-related
debris and sometime sickness -- not the best ingredients for a nice day
at the beach.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Funds inquiry launched into child charity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484964</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE charities' watchdog in England is investigating the Child Aid
Foundation, the children's charity chaired by Major General Graham
Hollands, a close friend of the Duchess of York.
Several representations have been made to the Charity Commission based
in London about the organisation.
The Scottish Charities Office in Edinburgh said it was aware of the
concerns and the interest shown by its English counterpart.
However, it added that it ''was not policy'' to discuss what, if any,
complaints had been made against the organisation north of the Border.
One complaint to the Charities Commission has come from the British
Institute For Brain Injured Children which is currently treating a
two-year-old girl from Giffnock, Glasgow, who has cerebral palsy.
The institute has written demanding to know where the cash the Child
Aid Foundation allegedly promised it has gone.
Mr Keith Pennock of the institute, based in Bridgwater, Somerset,
said: ''We deal with many families from Scotland and give them help and
advice.
''We have one family here just now and have a number of others waiting
to come down.
''Thirty-five Scottish children have followed our home programmes and
more than three-quarters of them made significant progress with their
sight, hearing, speech or mobility.
''All we want to know is where the money we expected for the institute
has gone.''
Other charities to complain include Meningitis Research, the
Meningitis Trust -- which up until last year funded a research programme
in Edinburgh -- and the Cot Death Foundation.
Major General Hollands, 53, met the duchess on the ski slopes several
years ago and is on the board of her personal charity, Children In
Crisis.
A spokeswoman for the duchess said in a statement: ''Major General
Hollands has been on the board of her personal charity, Children in
Crisis, since March 1994, during which time he has made a significant
contribution to the charity's projects.
''Children In Crisis is aware that Major General Hollands is working
with the Charity Commission in an informal inquiry into the charity,
Child Aid.''
Child Aid was set up by South African John Tungay to advance education
and relieve poverty, distress and suffering of children in any part of
the world. He is said to have quit two weeks ago through ill health.
No-one from Child Aid was available for comment yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
