<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000158</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000158</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour comes under attack over its handling of debate into abolition of the verdict. Lawyers plead 'not proven' case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484969</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of Scotland's leading criminal lawyers, Mr Donald Findlay, QC,
yesterday launched a scathing attack on the campaign to abolish the
controversial not proven verdict.
He led an all-party line-up of top advocates who publicly joined
forces to defend the verdict and attack the handling of the issue by
Labour, and in particular Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson.
They chose to make their move on the eve of the Labour Party
conference in Inverness. Delegates are likely to debate the issue, and
it was claimed yesterday the party is on the brink of adopting abolition
of the verdict as policy.
Mr Findlay, a supporter of the Conservative Party, described attempts
to abolish the verdict as ''fundamentally ill conceived'', and said Mr
Robertson had leapt on the issue ''in a scandalous manner''.
The campaign to abolish the verdict gathered momentum following the
Amanda Duffy case, when a not proven verdict was returned against a man
accused of her murder. Public concern over that verdict led to a
petition being presented to Scottish Secretary Ian Lang, calling for its
abolition.
''I have every sympathy with the Duffy family,'' said Mr Findlay.
''But George Robertson turned it into a political issue because he
perceived it as an issue that could be turned to the Labour Party's
advantage. I believe it was done for purely cynical motives.''
Mr Findlay said he believed the number of acquittals would rise if the
not proven verdict was abolished. ''People do not want, as a jury, to
convict, because they know that that involves prison and all the rest of
it. They won't do that unless they are sure that they have got the right
man.
''If you have two verdicts the inclination will be 'we are not going
to take that big step to guilty unless we really are sure'. That is why
I believe the acquittal rate will go up.''
Mr Findlay added that the not proven verdict would not be abolished in
the lifetime of the present Government.
The Labour Party is currently consulting its members on the future of
the verdict. However, it was also claimed yesterday that the
consultation process was being undermined by the desire of senior party
members to adopt abolition as party policy.
The attack on Labour's handling of the issue came from advocates
representing all of Scotland's main political parties at a briefing
called by the Muir Society -- an organisation of Labour and radical
lawyers -- in Glasgow.
They included Mr Gerry Carroll an advocate and Labour councillor, Mr
Hugh Mathews, QC, the Scottish National Party's legal affairs spokesman,
and advocate Mr James Reilly, a member of the Liberal Democrat Party.
Mr Reilly said: ''It is impossible to overstate the importance of this
matter and, equally, it is impossible to overstate the importance of a
full and frank debate on this issue.''
Mr Carroll launched a thinly veiled attack on what he saw as attempts
by senior Labour Party members to force through a policy without proper
consultation.
''Clearly some members of the party have decided that the not proven
verdict should be abolished prior to the consultation process coming to
a conclusion.''
Mr Mathews said that the fact that sheriffs and magistrates sitting
alone -- without a jury -- used the verdict, was proof of its viability.
Mr Robertson could not be contacted for comment last night, but a
spokesman said: ''The not proven verdict proposal was made in a
consultation paper. That paper was produced by an independent committee
of legal experts.
''Mr Robertson has already stated in the second reading of the
Criminal Justice Bill that the issue should be the subject of a free
vote.
''Mr Robertson has always opposed the not proven verdict on principle,
not just on the grounds that the Duffys are his constituents.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Law appointment</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
