<RECORDNO>979484970</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Lord Advocate, Lord Rodger of Earlsferry, has appointed Mr Paul
McBride as an Advocate-depute to succeed Mr Ian Peebles, who leaves the
post at the end of this month after three years in office. Mr McBride,
30, a Strathclyde University graduate, was admitted to the Faculty of
Advocates in December 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Golden keys</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484971</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 1908 Steinway piano which is decorated with watercolours by the
Scottish fresco painter Phoebe Anna Traquair and was bought by the
present owners for #350 in Inverness in 1952, is expected to fetch up to
#80,000 at a Phillips in London on March 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Film first</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484972</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORT William's Studio Cinema looks set to hold in May the British
premiere of the new Rob Roy film starring Liam Neeson which was filmed
in the Lochaber town and Glen Nevis last summer. Cinema manager John
McDermott said yesterday he was also optimistic of getting Mel Gibson's
Braveheart, also filmed in Glen Nevis, when it comes out in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cries for help start search</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484973</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAJOR search on 3700ft Creag Meagaidh, near Laggan, ended last night
with two climbers being found safe and well.
Two hillwalkers had heard cries for help just before 4pm. Lochaber
mountain rescue team was called out and a Navy Sea King helicopter from
Prestwick, which had just taken the bodies of the three climbers killed
in Glencoe to Fort William, went to the scene.
The two climbers were found by a dog handler with the Lochaber team.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#32,000 grant to aid women</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484974</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE Business Development announced yesterday -- International
Women's Day -- that it had pledged #32,000 to tap the ''massive
potential'' of women entrepreneurs.
The grant, approved by Strathclyde Regional Council's economic and
industrial development committee, will be used to help and encourage
women in business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Power companies deny policy change</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484975</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO power companies yesterday denied they have changed their policy by
conceding the need to bury underground sections of the power line which
forms part of the planned #175m undersea interconnector linking Scotland
and Ulster.
The denial came as the senior counsel for ScottishPower and Northern
Ireland Electricity, Mr Donald Mackay, QC, made final submissions at the
public inquiry into the scheme which began in Ayr on October 4.
Rejecting the U-turn suggestion Mr Alan Rainey, NIE's group manager in
charge of projects, said: ''We have made no changes to the basis for our
applications for the required consents, which have been fully examined
by the public inquiry over the past five months.
''As our closing submissions at the inquiry makes very clear the
application is for an overhead power line. There has therefore been no
U-turn.''
Mr Rainey added: ''We have always accepted that one result of the Ayr
Inquiry could be for conditions to be attached to any consent granted.
''We have been at pains to emphasise the implications of such a
condition being imposed.
''If, however, any condition were to call for the undergrounding of
sections of the power line these would need to be very carefully
examined.''
The local authorities involved came in for heavy criticism from Mr
Mackay as he summed up the power companies' case to the Scottish Office
Reporter, Mr James McCulloch.
Mr Mackay said it was clear that the three authorities -- Strathclyde
Regional Council and Cumnock and Doon Valley and Kyle and Carrick
districts -- had been against the project from an early stage, and
having decided on such outright opposition they failed to give the
project the kind of proper consideration and assessment that the power
firms and the public were entitled to expect.
It is expected that the outcome of the inquiry will become known in
January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Search switched</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484976</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The search for 70-year old British yachtsman Harry Mitchell from
Southsea, Hampshire, the oldest competitior in the BOC round the world
race, was switched to a new area, a week after an emeregncy radio beacon
on his 40 ft yacht Henry Hornblower was activated 1040 miles west of
Cape Horn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bridal suite: sea views, rooms separate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484977</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARRIAGE is an institution; as is prison, it was once famously
remarked.
That might not have leapt to the minds of Elizabeth Weston and Charles
Millar, a bride and bridegroom from Glasgow, as they sealed their union
at Oban Register office, but they might more readily have made the
connection later as they spent the first night of their married lives
behind bars, as did John Kennedy, their best man.
The wedding had gone well up until about midnight last Friday at
Oban's Regent Hotel.
The function had been boisterous but good-natured, said manager Hamish
McKinnon, until a row allegedly broke out in a bedroom leaving one man
injured. The incident was dealt with jointly by police and hotel
security. In all, 14 guests had to be ejected from the hotel.
Police granted Miss Weston's request, made in the form of loud and
continuous protests, not to be parted from her new husband on their
wedding night by arresting her in connection with an alleged breach of
the peace.
A police spokesman stressed that the pair spent the night in separate
cells and confirmed: ''Three people have been reported to the
procurator-fiscal in connection with public order offences.''
A friend, who did not want to give her name, answered the door at the
couple's Maryhill home and confirmed that they had since continued with
their honeymoon plans. They could not be contacted in Malta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000167</DOCID>
