<DOCNO>GH950309-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ministers are accused over workers' rights</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484979</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLITICAL furore erupted last night after a Labour MP published a
''leaked'' circular which, he said, showed Ministers wanted to deprive
temporary workers of rights by ending their contracts just before they
qualified for them.
Publishing the document at Westminster, Mr Richard Burden said it
stated: ''All new temporary appointments in the Employment Service will
be limited to 51 weeks.'' The MP for Birmingham Northfield said the aim
was to avoid workers qualifying for full employment rights.
He said the document was clearly not meant for public viewing, and
recipients were instructed to ''destroy 31 July 1995''.
The document, entitled Dept of Employment ES Personnel Notice 5/95,
showed the work history of potential recruits was to be checked to
ensure that the prospective employee would not have cumulatively worked
for the qualifying period to gain full rights if he/she was employed, he
said.
It stated: ''If it is not checked, we might later find that the
individual has already worked for up to two years and might now be in
the position of having enough service to qualify for a wide range of
employment rights.''
It goes on to instruct personnel staff never to promise a good
temporary member of staff another job at the end of their contract.
Mr Burden said: ''The efficiency implications of disregarding good,
proven staff are to be ignored in the Government's obsession with
ensuring employees have no rights.''
He said Employment Secretary Michael Portillo's department should be
''setting a good example to employers. Instead they are saying
Dickensian conditions are welcome -- even in the Government's own
backyard.
''The Government's obsession with denying people job security means
they would rather sack good, proven staff than allow them basic
employment rights.''
Later, Mr Burden's office issued copies of the leaked document which
made clear that the document states: ''All new temporary appointments to
the ES will be limited to 51 weeks''.
The Employment Department denied the document revealed changes to the
way casual staff were being treated within the service.
The document was simply a reminder to personnel managers that they
should not abuse temporary staff who could not be promoted within the
service.
''It is a reminder to them that if they have to bring in casual staff,
then they should not abuse the system. If they need to fill a position
on a long-term basis, they should be going through the proper
recruitment procedures.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Insurance offer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484980</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH local authority is to introduce an insurance protection
scheme for council house tenants in the wake of the Paisley floods in
which hundreds of uninsured residents lost their possessions.
Renfrew District Council hope to introduce the low-cost household
contents insurance cover as a matter of urgency.
Householders who wish to join the scheme will be able to pay weekly
premiums along with their rent.
The minimum weekly cost -- #1.35 or #1.05 for pensioners -- will
entitle those contributing to #9000 and #7000 worth of cover
respectively.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Detractors will be brought to book by Allison</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484981</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Scottish organiser of the Labour Party in Scotland, Mr Jimmy
Allison, warned yesterday that he had ''a lot more up his sleeve'' if
his detractors unfairly criticised him over his book Guilty by
Suspicion, which reveals the in-fighting in the Labour Party.
The book is being published just as Labour is holding its Scottish
conference, and when there are divisions over leader Tony Blair's
attempts to change the party's Clause 4.
Mr Allison, who yesterday presented a copy of his book to Glasgow's
Labour group leader Pat Lally, said he would be at the party conference
to discuss the contents of the book, which details how he was forced out
of office because he disagreed with the censorship from London
headquarters.
''I respect the views of ordinary party members who may well be
critical of me, and will accept that with the seriousness it deserves,''
he said. ''Anyone who wants to discuss it with me is fine. There won't
be the slightest hassle.''
As to whether he was just settling old scores with the book, he said:
''That's rather a sour way of putting it. I think it was more of
correcting some inaccuracies.''
Councillor Lally had no doubts on where he stood on Mr Allison's
ability. He said: ''Jimmy Allison really was the finest organiser I have
ever known. I think it's been a pretty sad loss for the party that we
haven't had his services for the past few years.''
So far publishers Argyll Publishing have produced 2000 copies of the
book which will officially go on sale tomorrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ASH fumes at hearse's early demise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484982</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANTI-smoking campaigners were understandably fuming yesterday when an
imaginative No Smoking Day media event went embarrassingly wrong.
The Action on Smoking and Health organisation had gone to great
expense to hire a hearse for the day as a prop for photo opportunities
for newspaper and television cameramen in Edinburgh and Glasgow.
The gleaming vehicle, which did not carry a symbolic coffin but bore
the more subtle message, ''Smokers' Compartment'', was to have been
driven around central Edinburgh and Glasgow as a reminder to
tobacco-users that the habit could lead to an early demise.
However, its mission ended abruptly when it broke down on the A8 near
Edinburgh Airport on the way to the first engagement and failed to
appear for either of the photocalls.
The hearse could not be said to have gone up in smoke but the
mechanical problem was so serious that the vehicle was still immobile,
with the bonnet up, several hours later.
Later, Ms Alison Hillhouse, chief executive of ASH, said: ''It was
very disappointing, because there was a lot of media interest. There was
nothing we could do. There wasn't another hearse available.''
Meanwhile, figures out yesterday claimed that cancer will affect more
than ten million people worldwide by the turn of the century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Child's asthma persuades parents to give up smoking</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484983</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPLE whose baby son needed repeated hospital care because of his
asthma turned the tide on his illness by giving up smoking.
Stewart and Chrisleen MacPherson, this year's No-Smoking Day Quitters
of the Year, told yesterday of their guilt as they watched David, now
two, struggling for breath.
Their other sons, Jonathan, 6, and Paul, 4, rubbed it in when they
watched the smoking warnings on television and asked their parents:
''Are you going to die?''
The last straw was just over a year ago after they had been up most of
the night caring for David.
''We woke up next morning and decided, that's it, no more
cigarettes,'' recalled Mr MacPherson, 26, after they had received their
prizes -- they were also regional winners for Argyll and Clyde area.
The Greenock couple, who will spend a weekend at the Troon Marine
Highland Hotel, now have a baby daughter, Lauren, four months, who they
were determined would be a smoke-free baby from the outset. David,
meanwhile, has not had to go back to hospital once since they stopped.
''It has made a difference to me too -- I felt like an old man when I
was smoking, out of breath all the time, now it is as if the chains have
been taken off from round my chest,'' said Mr MacPherson.
Mrs MacPherson, 27, who has smoked for eight years, said: ''The
cravings lasted for a couple of months but they have passed now. You
have to be determined to do it.''
The couple, who smoked 20 a day each, reckon they have saved #1700
over the past year by not smoking.
The Health Education Board for Scotland, who organised the national
competition, estimate that smoking causes one in six of all deaths in
Scotland, and according to the Imperial Cancer Research Fund Scottish
women have the highest rate of tobacco-related deaths in the world.
Models are joining a campaign to stop smoking in the fashion business
and to set an example to teenagers.
The Put Smoking Out of Fashion movement, backed by the Health
Education Authority, aims to counter the new ''realism'' in fashion
images and its impact on young people.
The models have the campaign logo printed on their cards to tell
prospective clients they will not use any tobacco products within
fashion photography.
They are backed by an HEA report, Smoking and Fashion: A Fatal
Combination, by Dr Paul Cobley and Adam Briggs, senior lecturers at the
London Guildhall University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Actress on the scent of millions</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484984</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACTRESS Elizabeth Hurley yesterday became the new multi-million dollar
face of cosmetics company Estee Lauder after a two-year search among the
world's most beautiful women.
The long-term contract will catapult her to international fame and is
reported to be worth several million dollars.
Miss Hurley, 29, the girlfriend of film actor Hugh Grant, is scarcely
known outside Britain.
Estee Lauder said it had made an exhaustive search and more than 15
women were considered. ''In Elizabeth, we have found the ideal Estee
Lauder International woman. Women worldwide can relate to her warm and
charismatic beauty,'' said the American company's president, Jeanette
Sarkisian Wagner.
Miss Hurley, who caused a sensation at the London premiere of Grant's
Four Weddings and a Funeral film in a revealing Versace dress held
together with safety pins, will initially appear in adverts for the
company's new fragrance.
On screen, she had her first break in the title role of Dennis
Potter's TV drama Christabel and went on to play a murderous flight
attendant in the film Passenger 57.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Churches reaffirm attitudes towards practising homosexuals Bishop was not aware he was gay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979484985</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE former Scottish Episcopal Bishop of Glasgow and Galloway, the Rt
Rev Derek Rawcliffe, revealed last night that he was not aware he was
gay while he worked in Scotland.
Mr Rawcliffe said it was long after his wife died, in 1987, that he
had faced up to the prospect of his homosexuality.
''People might say that it is easy for me to admit that I am
homosexual now I have retired, but that is not the case. I was not aware
then that I was homosexual.''
Speaking from his home in the village of Bardsey, between Leeds and
Wetherby, the 73-year-old cleric added: ''When I married I thought I was
no longer gay. I went on thinking that until circumstances forced me to
realise that I still was, and always have been.''
Mr Rawcliffe, who is now an assistant bishop in the Church of England
at Ripon, is believed to be the highest member of his Church to ''come
out''. He was bishop of Glasgow and Galloway from 1981 to 1991.
He admitted on Tuesday's BBC2 Newsnight programme that he was
homosexual, and said he was in favour of blessings for the relationships
of gay priests.
Mr Rawcliffe said he had taken the decision to go public in the hope
that it would ''cause the Churches to consider their position in
relation to homosexuality''.
However, Scottish Church leaders showed no signs yesterday of
softening their traditional attitudes to practising homosexuals, in the
face of Mr Rawcliffe's revelations.
Glasgow's Roman Catholic Cardinal Thomas Winning stated his Church's
position was that people with a homosexual orientation were not
condemned, but physical homosexual activity was seen as morally wrong.
Mr Bill Wallace, convener of the social responsibility committee of
the Church of Scotland, said: ''We accept that some people have a
homosexual orientation, but we are strongly of the view that genital
sexual acts are wrong.''
While not criticising practicising homosexuals, the Scottish Episcopal
Church did not support them either yesterday. A spokesperson for the
Scottish Episcopal Bishop of Glasgow and Galloway, the Rt Rev John
Taylor, said: ''The Church has no official line or policy on this issue.
Within the Church there are a wide variety of views.''
Mr Rawcliffe yesterday refused to answer questions about whether he
had engaged in gay sex, and criticised Churches who draw a distinction
between homosexual orientation and practice, saying ''that is a false
distinction''.
''There was a time some years ago when I did take another view and
would have separated orientation from practice. And I think that is both
false and cruel, to say we are gay but not allowed to exercise that.
''If God was really saying that, that would be cruel. We don't say to
heterosexual people 'well God has made you, God has given you this
sexuality, but you have not to use it'. Part of our human existence is
giving and sharing love and affection, and why should that be denied to
those who are gay?
''I came to the conclusion, when I was a teenager, that the practice
of homosexuality was wrong by taking notice of the scripture of Saint
Paul. Thirty years or so later, I came to the conclusion that this was a
misunderstanding.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unsafe sweets alert</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484986</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR council workers were suspended yesterday after a load of
contaminated food went missing on route to a council incinerator at
Hillhouse in Hamilton.
Urgent warnings were sent out throughout Lanarkshire last night,
alerting the public not to eat any of the food because it would make
them ill.
A local baker had called in Hamilton District Council's environmental
health officers to destroy 500 puddings which had ''gone off''. But
police were alerted when a number of the defrosted sweets turned up for
sale at a nursing home for the elderly in the town.
A Strathclyde Police spokesman said last night: ''We are investigating
the disappearance of a quantity of foodstuffs which was to be destroyed
by local health officers.
''We understand four environmental health workers have been suspended
pending our inquiries.''
The puddings included raspberry pavlovas, blackcurrent cheesecake, and
strawberry gateaux -- all normally sold in a frozen condition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Abortion Bill closer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484987</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Irish Government Bill to amend the country's law that bans abortion
passed its first parliamentary test last night.
The Bill -- which will make information about foreign abortion
facilities more freely available in the Irish Republic -- secured
crucial second stage approval in the Dail by 85 votes to 67.
The Government's win had been expected despite a decision by the main
Fianna Fail opposition party to vote against the Bill and intensive
lobbying of all members of the House by the powerful Irish anti-abortion
pro-life lobby.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major rebuilding project planned for Erskine Hospital</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484988</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Erskine Hospital, Scotland's only nursing facility for disabled
ex-Service personnel, is to be extensively rebuilt at a cost of millions
in order to conform with new community care guidelines.
The foundation running the Renfrewshire hospital, which has been
forced to apply for registration as a nursing home to qualify for
central and local government support, announced yesterday it would be
phasing out its dormitory accommodation in favour of modern units more
in tune with changing policies on the care of the elderly and disabled.
The work will accelerate the hospital's continual upgrading of
facilities and is expected to start later this year, the hospital's
annual meeting was told yesterday.
Details of the work were not available, but the hospital's central
building, a listed mansion house, will not be seriously affected.
The appointment of Lieutenant General Sir John MacMillan as chairman,
succeeding Vice Admiral Sir Thomas Baird who has decided to step down
after nine years' service, was also endorsed.
Sir John was confident the hospital could fund the work from reserves,
currently standing at #25.7m.
However, he would not rule out the possibility of a public appeal for
assistance when the full details of the programme are finalised.
However, Sir Thomas sounded a warning note when he indicated he
thought the charity's financial strength would be ''severely tested'' by
the scheme.
The hospital currently needs to raise #1.9m a year to cover its
running costs and that is likely to rise as a result of the planned
work, treasurer Iain Grimmond predicted yesterday.
The hospital, which looks after 355 patients, received #5.6m in
ordinary income and spent #7.4m last year, leaving it with a deficit of
#1.8m before items such as legacies and donations were taken into
account.
Legacies were #500,000 down on 1993 at #3.1m, with donations down
#80,000 to #960,000. However, the charity raised #1.3m through the sale
of investments which, coupled with legacies and donations, left Erskine
#2.9m in surplus for 1994, a slight decrease on 1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950309-000178</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950309-000178</DOCID>
<DATE>950309</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lang may delay loch plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN,HOME AFFAIRS REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484989</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN announcement by Scottish Secretary Ian Lang about the creation of a
body to run the affairs of Loch Lomond and the Trossachs is thought to
be imminent -- but fears are growing that he may be planning to lay the
entire responsibility on local government.
One source on the loch told The Herald yesterday that the coded
Scottish Office messages were that Mr Lang would leave it to the new
local authorities to come forward with proposals. It could be at least
another two years before any governing body is in place.
Lovers of Loch Lomond in particular fear that the loch could lose out
in terms of resources just as years of effort to bring in regulations on
power boating are set to bear fruit.
A new set of by-laws aimed at improving water-borne safety and at
preserving the loch's rapidly-deteriorating environment are with the
Scottish Office, which hopes they will in place for summer.
Scottish Natural Heritage is also due to announce as part of the
package that it has set aside more than #300,000 to provide the Loch
Lomond Park Authority with a patrol boat and water-borne rangers.
The Hutchison Committee, which Mr Lang commissioned to report on
management and conservation issues, was precluded from recommending any
kind of board similar to a national park board which points Mr Lang
towards another local government solution.
The present authority, created from four local authorities bordering
the loch, is widely regarded as worthy, but lacking proper finance and
teeth. After reorganisation, responsibility will pass to three
authorities.
Its current geographical area covers about 170 square miles. Include
the Trossachs, and the park would jump to more than 600 square miles,
possibly taking the focus, and any resources, off Loch Lomond and its
problems at a vital time.
While the cases are not exactly parallel, Mr Lang's voluntary
principle solution to the management of the Cairngorms -- appointing a
chairman and letting him pull together the diverse and often
bitterly-opposed interests to work out solutions -- was met with almost
universal dissatisfaction.
Mrs Hannah Stirling, of the Friends of Loch Lomond, said yesterday:
''The body we already have is too fragmented, so we do not want another
of the same.t.''
