<HEADLINE>Judge backs care report</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484990</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
A JUDGE last night dismissed an action to prevent publication of
newspaper articles today in a ruling of major significance for freedom
of information and freedom of the press.
The owners of a Lanarkshire nursing home -- the subject of a BBC
Scotland documentary tonight -- had applied for an interdict to prevent
Caledonian Newspapers and others from reporting the allegations in the
programme of ''appalling'' standards of care.
Lord Morton of Shuna ruled the freedom of information and freedom of
the press should be upheld as far as possible, and said he had to
protect press freedom and public interest.
He added that the pursuers -- husband and wife Raymond and Margaret
Baigent, of Orchard House Nursing Home, Crossford -- would still have
the remedy of damages if anything defamatory was said of them.
Ironically, today's story in The Herald raises questions over the
accuracy of the Frontline Scotland investigation into conditions at the
home, which included the BBC using hidden cameras and speaking to five
former nursing staff.
The Baigents' counsel, Mr Neil Davidson, had argued that if damage was
done to someone's reputation then money could not compensate adequately,
and that the remedy he sought would pre-empt that damage occurring in
the first place.
Mr Davidson also produced evidence from doctors, a health board, and
others that gave the home ''a clean bill of health''.
However, Lord Morton indicated he could not judge what was or was not
defamatory on the basis of the information before him. He questioned
whether people should be prevented from complaining about matters of
public interest and said he knew nothing about the merits of the
complaints.
Mr Bill Dunlop, counsel for The Herald, said the press required
freedom to investigate and to report. On the basis that pursuers did not
know what defenders were going to publish, they could not possibly claim
it was defamatory. Furthermore, the material would only be defamatory if
it were untrue.
The Herald, he said, had carried out its own research and the owners
of the home were given the opportunity to comment on the allegations. He
said that claims of victimisation by the home owners would also be
reported.
Interdict should not be a vehicle to gag the press, Mr Dunlop
continued. If defamation occurred, the home owners would be entitled to
seek damages. If the newspaper was not allowed to publish today, the
broadcast would go ahead and by tomorrow the story would be old hat.
Mr James Taylor, representing another publication, argued that the
press were being used as a ''stalking horse'' to test the case before
any action against the BBC was raised. He said the whole matter should
have been dealt with at once rather than raising a separate action
against the BBC today.
Lord Morton refused the interdict and awarded expenses against the
pursuers.
Mrs Gillian Wade, for The Herald's lawyers, Bannatyne, Kirkwood, and
France, said last night: ''This is a victory for press freedom.''
