<HEADLINE>Power investors may sue Treasury</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE,POLITICAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979484991</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ELECTRICITY share prices continued to tumble yesterday as the
Government was accused of a #4000m ramp, misleading share buyers when it
knew consumer price reductions were in the offing.
Last night at Westminster and in the City, rumours were building up
that the institutions at home and abroad in countries such as Japan and
America were considering suing the Government for a false prospectus on
the electricity shares sale.
Ministers hotly denied the accusation and were yesterday pointing the
finger of blame for the debacle firmly in the direction of the
regulator, Professor Stephen Littlechild.
Sir George Young, Financial Secretary to the Treasury, said: ''We
would reject any such accusation very strongly. We discussed the
prospectus with the regulator last Friday and we put the issue to the
lawyers and the financial advisers and in the light of their advice we
decided to go ahead.''
Labour is accusing the Government of insider dealing over the #4000m
sell-off of National Power and PowerGen which came just before the
regulator was planning a new pricing regime for the electricity
companies.
Yesterday, part-paid shares in PowerGen fell a further 4p to 185[1/2]p
and National Power fell 2p to 174[1/2]p. Northern Electric, which on
Tuesday reluctantly recommended acceptance of a 1100p-a-share takeover
bid by Trafalgar House, lost 104p to 793p. ScottishPower fell 2p to 312p
while Hydro-Electric lost the same amount to 307p.
Shadow Trade Secretary Jack Cunningham told BBC Radio yesterday: ''I'm
in no doubt that the Government has to face the charge that it is guilty
of breaching the terms of the Criminal Justice Act, 1993. It is quite
clear, because the Treasury's merchant bankers have admitted it, that
they knew of Professor Littlechild's intention to reconsider his pricing
controls -- and that comes under the heading of inside information in
the Act of Parliament.''
